WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.820 --> 00:00:07.410
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz:
Thank you, everyone,

00:00:07.410 --> 00:00:08.920
so much for being here today.

00:00:08.920 --> 00:00:11.930
I have some brief opening
remarks before we get

00:00:11.930 --> 00:00:13.360
to our first wonderful panel.

00:00:13.360 --> 00:00:19.680
I wanted to begin with a
territorial acknowledgment,

00:00:19.680 --> 00:00:23.460
which I will read from because
I cannot memorize anything.

00:00:23.460 --> 00:00:25.990
We acknowledge the
Piscataway and Pamunke peoples,

00:00:25.990 --> 00:00:28.750
whose traditional and unseeded
territory we're gathered

00:00:28.750 --> 00:00:30.050
upon today.

00:00:30.050 --> 00:00:32.660
Gathering here, we pay
respect to the elders,

00:00:32.660 --> 00:00:34.950
both past and present.

00:00:34.950 --> 00:00:37.420
We acknowledge the grave
harm that colonialism brought

00:00:37.420 --> 00:00:39.030
to these lands and
in particular,

00:00:39.030 --> 00:00:42.310
the erasure of both indigenous
and African identities

00:00:42.310 --> 00:00:44.720
under not only slavery
but racist laws

00:00:44.720 --> 00:00:46.050
that segregated all peoples

00:00:46.050 --> 00:00:49.680
into the binary classification
of white and black.

00:00:49.680 --> 00:00:52.060
We honor those who have
lived and do live now

00:00:52.060 --> 00:00:54.410
at the intersections of
identity and experience

00:00:54.410 --> 00:00:56.720
which we will be
exploring today.

00:00:56.720 --> 00:00:59.420
We also honor and thank
Piscataway Indian leader,

00:00:59.420 --> 00:01:01.600
Chief Turkey Tayac,
whose leadership

00:01:01.600 --> 00:01:03.510
in the indigenous
social justice movement

00:01:03.510 --> 00:01:05.960
of the 20th century
played a pivotal role

00:01:05.960 --> 00:01:08.390
in reclaiming indigenous
identity not only here

00:01:08.390 --> 00:01:11.220
but in communities aligned with
the American Indian Movement

00:01:11.220 --> 00:01:14.010
for self-determination
around the world.

00:01:15.750 --> 00:01:17.230
Thank you again, Dan
[assumed spelling],

00:01:17.230 --> 00:01:19.410
for such a nice introduction.

00:01:19.410 --> 00:01:23.480
It has been just an incredible
year to spend in what,

00:01:23.480 --> 00:01:25.280
I hope you'll agree,
is an incredible space,

00:01:25.280 --> 00:01:30.500
in addition to the wonderful
reading and the conversations

00:01:30.500 --> 00:01:32.380
that I've been able to have
and events that I've been able

00:01:32.380 --> 00:01:34.660
to organize and participate in.

00:01:34.660 --> 00:01:36.320
One of my very favorite things

00:01:36.320 --> 00:01:38.720
about being here is just
wondering around the building

00:01:38.720 --> 00:01:41.090
which I hope you'll take
the opportunity to do

00:01:41.090 --> 00:01:43.010
if you have time today.

00:01:43.010 --> 00:01:46.460
My work here is focused
on, as Dan mentioned,

00:01:46.460 --> 00:01:49.700
the ethics of Mars exploration,
specifically the ways

00:01:49.700 --> 00:01:52.380
in which our plans
for space intersect

00:01:52.380 --> 00:01:55.270
with our histories
here on earth.

00:01:55.270 --> 00:01:57.050
And in particular, the way

00:01:57.050 --> 00:02:01.590
in which we employ historical
narratives and use those

00:02:01.590 --> 00:02:04.440
to discuss space has a
way of reshaping the way

00:02:04.440 --> 00:02:08.100
that we interpret what
happened here on our own planet.

00:02:08.100 --> 00:02:11.240
And so these affect not only
our understanding of the past

00:02:11.240 --> 00:02:12.890
but of the present
and the things

00:02:12.890 --> 00:02:14.190
that we might do in the future.

00:02:14.190 --> 00:02:17.680
And so I've been spending time
here digging into the stories,

00:02:17.680 --> 00:02:20.950
we tell about why we go to
space and who we conceive

00:02:20.950 --> 00:02:23.530
of being an explorer,
and also, of course,

00:02:23.530 --> 00:02:28.070
the rapidly changing
policy landscape

00:02:28.070 --> 00:02:31.900
that is now shaping what
we will do in the future.

00:02:31.900 --> 00:02:33.200
So you heard a little bit

00:02:33.200 --> 00:02:36.020
about the chair's
position here from Dan.

00:02:36.020 --> 00:02:38.100
I wanted to remark also

00:02:38.100 --> 00:02:41.800
that Barry Blumberg was not
himself an astrobiologist

00:02:41.800 --> 00:02:43.930
despite having been
the first head

00:02:43.930 --> 00:02:46.270
of the NASA Astrobiology
Institute.

00:02:46.270 --> 00:02:50.670
His specialty was actually in
infectious disease and he--

00:02:50.670 --> 00:02:54.390
I think it's interesting that he
was the person who felt it was

00:02:54.390 --> 00:02:56.380
so important for there
to be this dialogue

00:02:56.380 --> 00:02:57.800
between the sciences
because he--

00:02:57.800 --> 00:03:00.630
between the sciences
and the humanities

00:03:00.630 --> 00:03:04.310
because he himself was a
person who was just interested

00:03:04.310 --> 00:03:05.680
in a wide variety of things.

00:03:05.680 --> 00:03:10.280
He won the Nobel Prize actually
for identifying hepatitis B.

00:03:10.280 --> 00:03:12.950
And so when I-- some of their
reading that I got to do

00:03:12.950 --> 00:03:17.060
about him, he was allotted as
having prevented more cases

00:03:17.060 --> 00:03:19.360
of cancer than anyone
in history.

00:03:19.360 --> 00:03:21.680
So if anyone is looking
for something to put

00:03:21.680 --> 00:03:24.220
in their memorial, no pressure.

00:03:24.220 --> 00:03:29.400
But he was, it sounds
like, an incredible guy.

00:03:29.400 --> 00:03:33.190
And so it's been a real
honor to spend time

00:03:33.190 --> 00:03:37.180
in such a unique position where
one has the opportunity to deal

00:03:37.180 --> 00:03:39.560
with both issues in
the humanity and--

00:03:39.560 --> 00:03:43.470
in the humanities and in science
as well because very few places

00:03:43.470 --> 00:03:47.060
or positions like
this exist, I think.

00:03:47.060 --> 00:03:48.810
So as I mentioned, one

00:03:48.810 --> 00:03:51.310
of the things I've really
enjoyed doing is wandering

00:03:51.310 --> 00:03:56.090
around the library aside from
our many incredible collections.

00:03:56.090 --> 00:03:59.430
We also have a wonderful
collection of Ethernet cables

00:03:59.430 --> 00:04:02.640
that are retrofitted
in the basement.

00:04:02.640 --> 00:04:04.600
But the thing that I
specifically wanted

00:04:04.600 --> 00:04:10.410
to touch on-- is that somebody's
alarm, I think, is going off.

00:04:10.410 --> 00:04:13.910
So, one of the things that I
happen to cross while walking

00:04:13.910 --> 00:04:18.160
around here was Thomas
Jefferson's Library and just

00:04:18.160 --> 00:04:19.460
down across the way there.

00:04:19.460 --> 00:04:21.770
And, what was most
striking to me

00:04:21.770 --> 00:04:24.760
about it was not
necessarily books themselves

00:04:24.760 --> 00:04:28.470
but actually the exploration of
the organization that he is--

00:04:28.470 --> 00:04:31.720
which was based on
Francis Bacon's method

00:04:31.720 --> 00:04:38.300
of organizing libraries into
memory, reason and imagine.

00:04:38.300 --> 00:04:42.750
And so, Bacon thought of this
as being memory being history,

00:04:42.750 --> 00:04:44.330
reason being philosophy

00:04:44.330 --> 00:04:48.190
and imagination being
specifically poetry.

00:04:48.190 --> 00:04:50.990
But I immediately saw how these
three categories could really

00:04:50.990 --> 00:04:53.290
shape the way that I was
thinking about this sort

00:04:53.290 --> 00:04:56.300
of multifaceted exploration
of Mars

00:04:56.300 --> 00:04:58.420
and the ethics surrounding
our going there

00:04:58.420 --> 00:05:02.050
of human beings actually
living beyond Earth.

00:05:02.050 --> 00:05:05.720
So today, we'll dive into
memory from the standpoint

00:05:05.720 --> 00:05:08.140
of these historical narratives
that I mentioned earlier

00:05:08.140 --> 00:05:11.700
and how they reshape-- how we
think about our own history.

00:05:11.700 --> 00:05:14.350
And we'll also talk
about reason.

00:05:14.350 --> 00:05:18.150
So not just philosophy, as
Bacon [inaudible], but also some

00:05:18.150 --> 00:05:21.890
of the newer things that
we've discovered about Mars

00:05:21.890 --> 00:05:25.420
and its own history and
also the policy landscape

00:05:25.420 --> 00:05:28.300
that we're now entering
into in space.

00:05:28.300 --> 00:05:31.060
And, we'll end also
with imagination talking

00:05:31.060 --> 00:05:34.140
about futurisms from
perspectives

00:05:34.140 --> 00:05:36.340
that are often not centered

00:05:36.340 --> 00:05:37.980
in the conversation
about our future.

00:05:37.980 --> 00:05:41.430
And I hope that you'll stay
the entire day if you can.

00:05:41.430 --> 00:05:42.730
I think it will be really fun.

00:05:42.730 --> 00:05:45.400
We'll also have a number
of wonderful performances

00:05:45.400 --> 00:05:49.360
that we'll speak to each one of
the panels that we have here.

00:05:49.360 --> 00:05:51.690
So, thank you all
so much for coming

00:05:51.690 --> 00:05:55.060
and thank you tremendously
to all of the panelists

00:05:55.060 --> 00:05:57.800
who are here today and who
have taken the time to travel

00:05:57.800 --> 00:05:59.700
and be part of this event.

00:05:59.700 --> 00:06:04.020
So without further ado, we'll
move on to our first panel.

00:06:04.020 --> 00:06:09.740
So, the panels today are divided
into three beats, each augmented

00:06:09.740 --> 00:06:11.590
by a performance as
I mentioned before.

00:06:11.590 --> 00:06:15.680
And this first panel is
called the Right Stuff.

00:06:15.680 --> 00:06:18.270
So the overview for this
was that Tom Wolfe's book,

00:06:18.270 --> 00:06:21.200
"The Right Stuff",
was really seminal

00:06:21.200 --> 00:06:25.250
in creating this archetype of
this sort of fighter pilot,

00:06:25.250 --> 00:06:28.470
space cowboy astronaut.

00:06:28.470 --> 00:06:30.750
And it really cemented that idea

00:06:30.750 --> 00:06:36.340
of like all astronauts being
Chuck Yeager in popular culture.

00:06:36.340 --> 00:06:39.510
And, in many ways, it also
drew on frontier themes

00:06:39.510 --> 00:06:40.940
that have been used
to talk about space.

00:06:40.940 --> 00:06:43.290
And so, in this first
panel, we'll be talking

00:06:43.290 --> 00:06:44.590
about how these narratives

00:06:44.590 --> 00:06:47.250
of space exploration
influence our modern ideas

00:06:47.250 --> 00:06:49.100
about who can explore space.

00:06:49.100 --> 00:06:52.600
And what it means to really
have the right stuff and how

00:06:52.600 --> 00:06:55.450
that meeting might evolve
and how we could change it.

00:06:55.450 --> 00:07:00.340
So without further ado, I
will introduce our panelists.

00:07:00.340 --> 00:07:03.630
Our first panelist today
is Brenda J. Child.

00:07:03.630 --> 00:07:06.390
Brenda is Northrop professor
and chair of the Department

00:07:06.390 --> 00:07:08.680
of American Studies at
University of Minnesota,

00:07:08.680 --> 00:07:10.640
and former chair
of the Department

00:07:10.640 --> 00:07:12.710
of American Indian Studies.

00:07:12.710 --> 00:07:14.160
She is the author
of several books

00:07:14.160 --> 00:07:15.840
in American Indian history,

00:07:15.840 --> 00:07:17.530
including "Boarding
School Seasons:

00:07:17.530 --> 00:07:20.880
American Indian Families,
1900-1940",

00:07:20.880 --> 00:07:22.950
which won the North
American Indian Prose Award,

00:07:22.950 --> 00:07:26.680
"Holding Our Worlds Together:
Ojibwe Women and the Survival

00:07:26.680 --> 00:07:30.140
of Community", "Indian Subjects:
Hemispheric Perspectives

00:07:30.140 --> 00:07:31.980
on the History of
Indigenous Education".

00:07:31.980 --> 00:07:35.960
Her 2014 book, "My
Grandfather's Knocking Sticks:

00:07:35.960 --> 00:07:38.550
Ojibwe Family Life and
Labor on the Reservation",

00:07:38.550 --> 00:07:41.010
won the American Indian
Book Award and Best Book

00:07:41.010 --> 00:07:43.320
in the Midwestern History Award.

00:07:43.320 --> 00:07:46.150
She's a member of the Board of
Trustees of the National Museum

00:07:46.150 --> 00:07:48.210
at the American
Indian-Smithsonian

00:07:48.210 --> 00:07:50.080
and past president of
the Native American

00:07:50.080 --> 00:07:52.470
and Indigenous Studies
Association.

00:07:52.470 --> 00:07:54.960
Child was born on the Red
Lake Ojibwe Reservation

00:07:54.960 --> 00:07:57.610
in northern Minnesota
where she's a member

00:07:57.610 --> 00:08:00.010
of a committee writing
a new constitution

00:08:00.010 --> 00:08:01.800
for the 12,000 member nation.

00:08:01.800 --> 00:08:03.100
Please welcome Brenda Child.

00:08:03.100 --> 00:08:04.400
[ Applause ]

00:08:04.400 --> 00:08:12.580
Our next panelist is Brian Nord.

00:08:12.580 --> 00:08:15.860
Brian Nord's current research is
in teaching intelligent machines

00:08:15.860 --> 00:08:19.080
to search for clues of the
universe's origin and destiny.

00:08:19.080 --> 00:08:21.350
In particular, he uses
artificial intelligence

00:08:21.350 --> 00:08:24.680
to study the cosmos, including
dark energy, dark matter,

00:08:24.680 --> 00:08:26.410
and the early universe.

00:08:26.410 --> 00:08:29.100
Nord also communicates with
the public regarding science,

00:08:29.100 --> 00:08:31.950
science policy, diversity,
and inclusion.

00:08:31.950 --> 00:08:34.620
He trains scientists in
public communication,

00:08:34.620 --> 00:08:36.930
advocates for science
funding and works

00:08:36.930 --> 00:08:38.850
with high school
students in the classroom

00:08:38.850 --> 00:08:40.840
and in research environments.

00:08:40.840 --> 00:08:42.970
Nord is a visiting
research assistant professor

00:08:42.970 --> 00:08:45.030
in the Department of
Astronomy and Astrophysics

00:08:45.030 --> 00:08:46.950
and a senior member
of the Kavli Institute

00:08:46.950 --> 00:08:51.250
for Cosmological Physics, KICP,
at the University of Chicago.

00:08:51.250 --> 00:08:54.470
He leads a team of
researchers who apply AI

00:08:54.470 --> 00:08:56.440
to questions in cosmology.

00:08:56.440 --> 00:09:00.340
Nord is co-leader of education
and public engagement at KICP,

00:09:00.340 --> 00:09:02.320
where he organizes a
year-long institute

00:09:02.320 --> 00:09:05.100
that provides opportunities for
high school students to innovate

00:09:05.100 --> 00:09:08.990
in hands-on physics experiences
outside the classroom.

00:09:08.990 --> 00:09:12.200
Nord is also the co-creator
of ThisIsBlackLight.com,

00:09:12.200 --> 00:09:15.570
an online curriculum to teach
the black experience in America.

00:09:15.570 --> 00:09:16.870
Please welcome Brian Nord.

00:09:16.870 --> 00:09:18.170
[ Applause ]

00:09:18.170 --> 00:09:27.200
Our next panelist is
Chanda Prescod-Weinstein.

00:09:27.200 --> 00:09:30.720
She's a postdoctoral research
associate in theoretical physics

00:09:30.720 --> 00:09:34.860
at the University of Washington,
Seattle, and lead axion wrangler

00:09:34.860 --> 00:09:36.310
and social media team member

00:09:36.310 --> 00:09:39.010
for the NASA STROBE-X
Probe Concept Study.

00:09:39.010 --> 00:09:42.710
In 2019, she will be an
assistant professor of physics

00:09:42.710 --> 00:09:44.880
at the University
of New Hampshire.

00:09:44.880 --> 00:09:47.170
Her driving impulse is
to understand the origin

00:09:47.170 --> 00:09:49.800
of spacetime and the
particles that populate it,

00:09:49.800 --> 00:09:53.190
as well as how everything
got to be the way it is.

00:09:53.190 --> 00:09:56.170
Recognized as one of 15 Black
Women Who Are Paving the Way

00:09:56.170 --> 00:09:59.300
in STEM and Breaking
Barriers by Essence Magazine.

00:09:59.300 --> 00:10:01.710
Prescod-Weinstein studies
particle astrophysics

00:10:01.710 --> 00:10:03.010
and cosmology.

00:10:03.010 --> 00:10:06.180
And her research spans from
large scale cosmic acceleration

00:10:06.180 --> 00:10:08.950
to the very small
dark matter particles.

00:10:08.950 --> 00:10:11.870
She also has a strong interest
in feminist philosophies

00:10:11.870 --> 00:10:15.140
of science and science,
technology and society--

00:10:15.140 --> 00:10:18.470
excuse me, science
technology and society studies.

00:10:18.470 --> 00:10:19.910
And she was the recipient

00:10:19.910 --> 00:10:23.760
of the 2017 LGBT+ Plus
Physicists Acknowledgement

00:10:23.760 --> 00:10:25.540
of Excellence Award.

00:10:25.540 --> 00:10:28.290
Her work was featured in
Huffington Post, Gizmodo,

00:10:28.290 --> 00:10:32.350
Nylon and the African-American
Intellectual History Society.

00:10:32.350 --> 00:10:34.550
Please welcome Chanda
Prescod-Weinstein.

00:10:34.550 --> 00:10:37.600
[ Applause ]

00:10:37.600 --> 00:10:44.120
Our next panelist
is Ashley Shew.

00:10:44.120 --> 00:10:46.530
Ashley Shew is assistant
professor in the Department

00:10:46.530 --> 00:10:49.470
of Science, Technology, and
Society at Virginia Tech,

00:10:49.470 --> 00:10:52.400
and works in philosophy of
technology at its intersection

00:10:52.400 --> 00:10:53.700
with disability studies,

00:10:53.700 --> 00:10:56.360
emerging technology,
and animal studies.

00:10:56.360 --> 00:10:58.230
She is the author of
"Animal Constructions

00:10:58.230 --> 00:11:02.100
and Technological Knowledge"
and co-editor of "Spaces

00:11:02.100 --> 00:11:05.600
for the Future: A Companion to
the Philosophy of Technology".

00:11:05.600 --> 00:11:06.900
Shew is a recent awardee

00:11:06.900 --> 00:11:11.280
of a National Science Foundation
CAREER Grant, running from 2018

00:11:11.280 --> 00:11:14.310
to 2023, to study
narratives about technology

00:11:14.310 --> 00:11:17.630
from the disability community
that often stand in contrast

00:11:17.630 --> 00:11:18.930
to dominant media

00:11:18.930 --> 00:11:21.160
and engineering narratives
about disability.

00:11:21.160 --> 00:11:22.960
Please welcome Ashley Shew.

00:11:22.960 --> 00:11:28.220
[ Applause ]

00:11:28.220 --> 00:11:32.150
So each of the panels will
have a slightly different

00:11:32.150 --> 00:11:33.910
panel format.

00:11:33.910 --> 00:11:36.610
And for this morning, our
panelists have elected

00:11:36.610 --> 00:11:38.660
to give an opening statement.

00:11:38.660 --> 00:11:43.460
So we'll just begin from
left to right with Dr. Child.

00:11:43.460 --> 00:11:44.760
&gt;&gt; Brenda J. Child: Great.

00:11:44.760 --> 00:11:46.060
Thank you.

00:11:46.060 --> 00:11:47.360
Is this on?

00:11:47.360 --> 00:11:48.660
Can you hear?

00:11:48.660 --> 00:11:49.960
OK. Great.

00:11:49.960 --> 00:11:52.760
So I spend most of my
time, my scholarly life,

00:11:52.760 --> 00:11:57.070
thinking about American Indian
lives in the early 20th century.

00:11:57.070 --> 00:11:59.130
And so when Lucianne
first invited me,

00:11:59.130 --> 00:12:03.070
I thought she must have
the wrong person in mind

00:12:03.070 --> 00:12:06.540
as someone who's trained
in American Indian history.

00:12:06.540 --> 00:12:10.310
But I really appreciate
being invited in for the work

00:12:10.310 --> 00:12:13.650
that you're doing and how
broadly you're thinking

00:12:13.650 --> 00:12:15.130
about interdisciplinarity.

00:12:15.130 --> 00:12:17.940
It's really exciting to be
part of this conversation

00:12:17.940 --> 00:12:21.940
and to read the work of
these, to me, young scholars

00:12:21.940 --> 00:12:23.760
and the work that they're doing.

00:12:23.760 --> 00:12:26.450
It's very exciting.

00:12:26.450 --> 00:12:29.460
American Indians often
use the word survival

00:12:29.460 --> 00:12:33.860
to describe the last 500 years
of European settler colonialism.

00:12:33.860 --> 00:12:37.940
In fact, just earlier this week,
I was reading a dissertation

00:12:37.940 --> 00:12:42.840
by a young scholar from
Canada who went a step further

00:12:42.840 --> 00:12:47.050
and used the term "surthivance",
and I thought, well,

00:12:47.050 --> 00:12:49.410
that's an interesting idea.

00:12:49.410 --> 00:12:53.810
As survivors, many of
us are thriving today

00:12:53.810 --> 00:12:57.370
and that's really
exciting to see especially

00:12:57.370 --> 00:12:59.380
from the vantage point
of the university,

00:12:59.380 --> 00:13:02.600
the things that are going
on in Indian country today

00:13:02.600 --> 00:13:04.070
and with our students.

00:13:04.070 --> 00:13:09.410
Of course, not all of us are
thriving but it's exciting

00:13:09.410 --> 00:13:12.240
to be part of some of the
work that's taking place

00:13:12.240 --> 00:13:14.560
in Indian country today.

00:13:14.560 --> 00:13:17.650
As indigenous people, I
just want to say thinking

00:13:17.650 --> 00:13:22.220
about that term surthrivance, we
want to be around in the future

00:13:22.220 --> 00:13:25.380
and we, of course, have
been in this country

00:13:25.380 --> 00:13:29.430
and in North America and the
Americas for a very long time.

00:13:29.430 --> 00:13:32.820
So perhaps in the future, we
would like to travel to Mars.

00:13:32.820 --> 00:13:34.680
I'll leave that open.

00:13:34.680 --> 00:13:37.650
That sounds like sort
of an exciting thing.

00:13:37.650 --> 00:13:40.910
Of course, this conversation
and the ideas

00:13:40.910 --> 00:13:45.300
that Lucianne has presented
made me think about how,

00:13:45.300 --> 00:13:48.630
as American Indian people,
we were very big players

00:13:48.630 --> 00:13:54.120
in the explorations that
took place 500 years ago.

00:13:54.120 --> 00:13:56.170
So why not participate

00:13:56.170 --> 00:13:59.020
in interplanetary
exploration as well.

00:13:59.020 --> 00:14:01.650
And I guess it got me
thinking just a little bit

00:14:01.650 --> 00:14:05.730
about what indigenous people
have to offer in thinking

00:14:05.730 --> 00:14:09.210
about interplanetary
exploration.

00:14:09.210 --> 00:14:12.480
Of course, as I mentioned,
we helped out a lot

00:14:12.480 --> 00:14:17.090
in the settlement of North and
South America, teaching settlers

00:14:17.090 --> 00:14:22.260
to do things famously like grow
corn and learn how to survive

00:14:22.260 --> 00:14:23.740
in this new environment.

00:14:23.740 --> 00:14:27.370
So we have that experience
to offer.

00:14:27.370 --> 00:14:32.500
Perhaps less well known or maybe
we don't think of this as often

00:14:32.500 --> 00:14:36.270
because of the way that
American Indian people settle--

00:14:36.270 --> 00:14:39.380
have settled in more
recent centuries.

00:14:39.380 --> 00:14:42.890
And so, since the reservation
era, people tend to think

00:14:42.890 --> 00:14:46.360
about American Indians
as living within a kind

00:14:46.360 --> 00:14:49.740
of geographically bounded
space, but that's not the way

00:14:49.740 --> 00:14:51.040
that we've always lived.

00:14:51.040 --> 00:14:52.730
We were, in fact, big settlers.

00:14:52.730 --> 00:14:55.350
We moved around through
the Americas.

00:14:55.350 --> 00:14:58.840
I'm from the Great Lakes from
Minnesota and in our part

00:14:58.840 --> 00:15:02.490
of the world, we traveled
by canoe and we know

00:15:02.490 --> 00:15:07.050
from new scholarship that's
taking place in the Pacific

00:15:07.050 --> 00:15:09.230
that indigenous Hawaiians
and people

00:15:09.230 --> 00:15:13.320
from the Pacific were
amazing travelers.

00:15:13.320 --> 00:15:16.940
And in fact, we have a new
scholar who's joined us

00:15:16.940 --> 00:15:19.790
at the University of
Minnesota who is teaching a--

00:15:19.790 --> 00:15:22.800
he's from Guam and knows a lot

00:15:22.800 --> 00:15:27.140
about Pacific traditions
of canoeing.

00:15:27.140 --> 00:15:30.240
And he's teaching a class
on comparative canoes

00:15:30.240 --> 00:15:32.010
at the University of Minnesota.

00:15:32.010 --> 00:15:34.900
And actually has a double-hulled
canoe that he stores

00:15:34.900 --> 00:15:37.420
in the University Boathouse.

00:15:37.420 --> 00:15:42.140
So, native people have been
travelers for quite a long time

00:15:42.140 --> 00:15:43.890
and we have had, of course,

00:15:43.890 --> 00:15:47.470
some famous native people
who've been travelers.

00:15:47.470 --> 00:15:50.220
You probably know thinking
about this part of the world

00:15:50.220 --> 00:15:55.120
that Pocahontas traveled from
the Chesapeake to London.

00:15:55.120 --> 00:15:58.110
She's probably one of the most
famous of native travelers.

00:15:58.110 --> 00:16:00.690
And there's-- If you
head over to the NMAI

00:16:00.690 --> 00:16:05.830
and you see the Americans
exhibit, there is a large story

00:16:05.830 --> 00:16:08.610
about Pocahontas and
how she's kind of played

00:16:08.610 --> 00:16:13.960
into American history and
even American imaginings

00:16:13.960 --> 00:16:15.580
of native people.

00:16:15.580 --> 00:16:18.520
There's another famous traveler
that I often think about,

00:16:18.520 --> 00:16:22.480
a man named Black Elk, who was
a Lakota who traveled to Europe

00:16:22.480 --> 00:16:24.350
to perform in the
Wild West shows

00:16:24.350 --> 00:16:26.920
and this was a fairly
common experience.

00:16:26.920 --> 00:16:28.220
I have a friend who's
just written a book

00:16:28.220 --> 00:16:31.160
about indigenous London,
about the early Inuit

00:16:31.160 --> 00:16:33.870
and other travelers
from the Americas

00:16:33.870 --> 00:16:36.570
who came sometimes
involuntarily,

00:16:36.570 --> 00:16:40.310
sometimes at their own
will to parts of Europe.

00:16:40.310 --> 00:16:44.090
At the University of Minnesota,
I feel really fortunate

00:16:44.090 --> 00:16:48.220
because I have a-- you know, I
always have wonderful colleagues

00:16:48.220 --> 00:16:51.100
to rely on and I just
want to mention the work

00:16:51.100 --> 00:16:53.850
of David Chang who's
written a recent book

00:16:53.850 --> 00:16:55.200
about Native American--

00:16:55.200 --> 00:16:58.500
or Native Hawaiian
global geographies.

00:16:58.500 --> 00:17:00.970
And what he has asked
us to do is to kind

00:17:00.970 --> 00:17:05.530
of shift the paradigm, and
he has a couple of questions

00:17:05.530 --> 00:17:08.010
that I'm just going to
kind of post to you.

00:17:08.010 --> 00:17:11.500
So he says in his new
book, what if we were

00:17:11.500 --> 00:17:15.800
to understand indigenous
people as active agents

00:17:15.800 --> 00:17:21.670
of global exploration rather
than the passive objects

00:17:21.670 --> 00:17:24.980
of that exploration,
which is I think what most

00:17:24.980 --> 00:17:28.250
of us have learned
in studying American

00:17:28.250 --> 00:17:30.680
or European or world history.

00:17:30.680 --> 00:17:34.650
So he also says, what
if instead of conceiving

00:17:34.650 --> 00:17:39.780
of global exploration as an
activity just of European men

00:17:39.780 --> 00:17:43.090
and we know the names, right,
even if we're not experts,

00:17:43.090 --> 00:17:45.930
Columbus, Magellan, Cook.

00:17:45.930 --> 00:17:48.990
We thought of it
instead as an activity

00:17:48.990 --> 00:17:52.040
of the people they discovered.

00:17:52.040 --> 00:17:55.170
And this is the shift
that he tries to make.

00:17:55.170 --> 00:17:59.600
And so, Chang also says, what
could such a new perspective

00:17:59.600 --> 00:18:03.360
on the project of
global exploration reveal

00:18:03.360 --> 00:18:06.900
about the meaning of
geographical understanding

00:18:06.900 --> 00:18:10.530
and its place and
struggles overpower

00:18:10.530 --> 00:18:14.210
in the context of colonialism.

00:18:14.210 --> 00:18:16.940
So, I highly recommend his book.

00:18:16.940 --> 00:18:20.040
When I read a book
like this that is full

00:18:20.040 --> 00:18:22.930
of provocative ideas and
also beautifully written,

00:18:22.930 --> 00:18:24.510
I'm always really jealous.

00:18:24.510 --> 00:18:27.190
So I wish I could say
these were all my ideas,

00:18:27.190 --> 00:18:30.750
but I want to leave you
with some of those points

00:18:30.750 --> 00:18:34.050
that he makes and highly
recommend his new book

00:18:34.050 --> 00:18:39.080
which is called, "The World
and All the Things upon It."

00:18:39.080 --> 00:18:41.380
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz:
Thank you.

00:18:42.990 --> 00:18:44.290
&gt;&gt; Brian Nord: Good morning.

00:18:44.290 --> 00:18:46.780
Thank you to Lucianne and the
Kluge Center for having us

00:18:46.780 --> 00:18:48.230
and having this discussion.

00:18:48.230 --> 00:18:50.040
And it's a privilege
to be sitting here

00:18:50.040 --> 00:18:54.710
with you folks to
talk about this.

00:18:54.710 --> 00:18:58.460
The idea of continuing
to go out there that--

00:18:58.460 --> 00:19:00.800
as if it's a necessity,
as if it's our--

00:19:00.800 --> 00:19:04.360
as if it's our destiny
is a clear question.

00:19:04.360 --> 00:19:07.720
I used to be on the side
of, oh, we have to go

00:19:07.720 --> 00:19:09.610
because it's what's next.

00:19:09.610 --> 00:19:11.460
And in the last decade,

00:19:11.460 --> 00:19:14.160
that whole perspective
has been changing for me.

00:19:14.160 --> 00:19:18.680
And, in the last couple of
years as I began to work

00:19:18.680 --> 00:19:22.040
on the intersection of
artificial intelligence

00:19:22.040 --> 00:19:25.010
and astrophysics, it has also
provided a new lens to think

00:19:25.010 --> 00:19:30.970
about what work and what work
means to us an individuals

00:19:30.970 --> 00:19:34.540
and what work means to society.

00:19:34.540 --> 00:19:38.090
If we are going to go out there,
if we're going to go further,

00:19:38.090 --> 00:19:41.020
it is-- very likely, it is
going to be highly automated.

00:19:41.020 --> 00:19:42.800
It is very likely that software

00:19:42.800 --> 00:19:44.790
and advanced algorithms are
going to be a key part of that.

00:19:44.790 --> 00:19:47.920
And if we think about
the huge complex machines

00:19:47.920 --> 00:19:51.940
that drive our society,
governments, corporations,

00:19:51.940 --> 00:19:54.900
those were already sort of like
advanced algorithms, in a way.

00:19:54.900 --> 00:19:57.490
They're these complex things
that we can't interpret

00:19:57.490 --> 00:19:59.340
that we don't know
how they work.

00:19:59.340 --> 00:20:01.350
And they have commodified
human beings.

00:20:01.350 --> 00:20:04.590
That is how those
systems have survived.

00:20:04.590 --> 00:20:08.110
And so when we accelerate
that machinery

00:20:08.110 --> 00:20:11.730
with artificial intelligence,
what will that mean for work

00:20:11.730 --> 00:20:13.180
as we're in space,
what will that mean

00:20:13.180 --> 00:20:18.150
for how human bodies are
continued to be treated?

00:20:18.150 --> 00:20:32.170
So I think if we are going to--
if we're going to consider how--

00:20:32.170 --> 00:20:34.000
if we're going to think
carefully about how we're going

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:38.290
to get out there, if we're
going to refocus who we center,

00:20:38.290 --> 00:20:42.550
we need to ask how
we've been doing it here

00:20:42.550 --> 00:20:44.180
and if we're ready
for that change.

00:20:44.180 --> 00:20:50.120
And if we're ready for-- if
we're ready to say we're going

00:20:50.120 --> 00:20:53.030
to out there and try to be
something different out there,

00:20:53.030 --> 00:20:54.960
what makes us think we can
do that if we weren't ready

00:20:54.960 --> 00:20:58.030
to be something different here.

00:20:58.030 --> 00:21:01.300
I think we're here
right now on Earth

00:21:01.300 --> 00:21:04.640
with these new technologies,
we're in an inflection point.

00:21:04.640 --> 00:21:09.570
And, we have a decision to
make about whether we are going

00:21:09.570 --> 00:21:13.240
to continue to allow
power to accumulate

00:21:13.240 --> 00:21:16.850
through these technologies or
if we're going to find a way

00:21:16.850 --> 00:21:20.170
to shift that power to folks
who haven't had it before.

00:21:20.170 --> 00:21:24.150
So that's one lens through
which I view this challenge.

00:21:24.150 --> 00:21:27.110
As-- With my role in
University of Chicago

00:21:27.110 --> 00:21:29.840
as Lucianne mentioned,
I'm the faculty leader

00:21:29.840 --> 00:21:31.980
for the Space Explorers Program.

00:21:31.980 --> 00:21:34.890
This is a method-- This is
a thing that's being going

00:21:34.890 --> 00:21:36.190
on for 25 years.

00:21:36.190 --> 00:21:37.490
I recently joined it.

00:21:37.490 --> 00:21:41.060
And we're trying to
shift it in a way

00:21:41.060 --> 00:21:46.240
to prepare a new generation of
thinkers and feelers and humans

00:21:46.240 --> 00:21:50.980
for approaching work and
research in a different way.

00:21:50.980 --> 00:21:52.840
So the nuts and bolts
of this program are

00:21:52.840 --> 00:21:54.960
that we have essentially
30 students per year,

00:21:54.960 --> 00:21:56.540
they're from-- they're
in high school.

00:21:56.540 --> 00:21:58.090
And, right this year,

00:21:58.090 --> 00:22:00.800
it's coming out their
rising sophomores.

00:22:00.800 --> 00:22:04.040
And we engage with them in--

00:22:04.040 --> 00:22:06.880
they're in labs inside
the University of Chicago,

00:22:06.880 --> 00:22:09.270
but it's meant to be a
non-classroom environment

00:22:09.270 --> 00:22:13.130
so that they can more experience
science as an everyday thing.

00:22:13.130 --> 00:22:16.650
So they can more experience
science and technologies

00:22:16.650 --> 00:22:20.260
and build a habit like what many

00:22:20.260 --> 00:22:22.430
of my colleagues are
researchers and scholars there.

00:22:22.430 --> 00:22:23.910
So there's a habit of thinking,

00:22:23.910 --> 00:22:26.390
at least in our current
academic context.

00:22:26.390 --> 00:22:27.690
And so we want to develop--

00:22:27.690 --> 00:22:30.880
those students to develop those
skills so that they're ready

00:22:30.880 --> 00:22:34.010
for the next set of
challenges which--

00:22:34.010 --> 00:22:35.330
it's not about memorizing
things,

00:22:35.330 --> 00:22:36.740
it's about knowing how to think.

00:22:36.740 --> 00:22:41.480
It's about knowing how
to approach problems.

00:22:41.480 --> 00:22:46.820
So this last year, to put a
finer point on this, our--

00:22:46.820 --> 00:22:53.340
the idea was that-- so how
do we have you learn how

00:22:53.340 --> 00:22:57.650
to do research that's not
trying to think about things

00:22:57.650 --> 00:23:00.530
from the back of a book,
trying to figure out what's

00:23:00.530 --> 00:23:01.980
in the back of a book.

00:23:01.980 --> 00:23:04.080
It's how do you think about
a problem that matters to you

00:23:04.080 --> 00:23:06.500
and how do you apply
science and technology to it.

00:23:06.500 --> 00:23:09.150
And so this year,
the 30 students went

00:23:09.150 --> 00:23:11.970
through three different
teams, 10 students each,

00:23:11.970 --> 00:23:14.800
and we asked them, how would
you develop a civilization

00:23:14.800 --> 00:23:19.600
on a foreign terrestrial body,
on another terrestrial body,

00:23:19.600 --> 00:23:22.550
extraterrestrial
body, 400,000 people

00:23:22.550 --> 00:23:25.380
with the main considerations
being energy generation

00:23:25.380 --> 00:23:27.320
and energy distribution.

00:23:27.320 --> 00:23:31.960
And in a way more
critically, how do you engage

00:23:31.960 --> 00:23:34.700
with those questions from
an ethical point of view?

00:23:34.700 --> 00:23:37.360
And so they were charged
to answer questions about,

00:23:37.360 --> 00:23:39.860
how do you help people survive
and how do you ask about--

00:23:39.860 --> 00:23:44.120
how do you think about how human
bodies and humans are treated

00:23:44.120 --> 00:23:45.560
in that kind of environment.

00:23:45.560 --> 00:23:48.880
And, somewhat to my
amazement, but then again not,

00:23:48.880 --> 00:23:51.320
because these students
are amazing,

00:23:51.320 --> 00:23:55.670
they came back with
amazing answers.

00:23:55.670 --> 00:23:58.180
They only had a week
to think about this.

00:23:58.180 --> 00:23:59.990
And they blew us away.

00:23:59.990 --> 00:24:02.320
It was amazing.

00:24:02.320 --> 00:24:06.140
And so, I think about--
when we think about work

00:24:06.140 --> 00:24:08.520
from the context of AI and
automation, we think about work

00:24:08.520 --> 00:24:12.670
from the perspective of research
and how do we build skills

00:24:12.670 --> 00:24:14.100
from other generation.

00:24:14.100 --> 00:24:20.070
I'm asking myself, how do we
rethink how we train ourselves,

00:24:20.070 --> 00:24:22.920
how we rethink, how--
not only, you know,

00:24:22.920 --> 00:24:26.740
what the right stuff is, but how
do we think ahead to be ready

00:24:26.740 --> 00:24:31.120
for what the next important
kind of right stuff is.

00:24:31.120 --> 00:24:34.750
Thank you.

00:24:34.750 --> 00:24:39.860
&gt;&gt; Chanda Prescod-Weinstein:
So, you guys are amazing

00:24:39.860 --> 00:24:43.400
to follow Norse kind of way.

00:24:43.400 --> 00:24:46.220
So Spanish artist,
Santiago Sierra,

00:24:46.220 --> 00:24:49.080
recently told The Guardian U.K.
newspaper, this was actually

00:24:49.080 --> 00:24:52.280
in the newspaper, I think,
yesterday or the day before,

00:24:52.280 --> 00:24:53.700
"Planting a national flag

00:24:53.700 --> 00:24:56.980
in a hitherto unvisited
place has never been an

00:24:56.980 --> 00:24:58.530
innocent gesture.

00:24:58.530 --> 00:25:02.240
This is how colonial
processes always begin".

00:25:02.240 --> 00:25:06.450
So because I am a black and
Caribbean-American descended

00:25:06.450 --> 00:25:09.480
from slaves, I'm more
familiar with the great law

00:25:09.480 --> 00:25:12.630
of the Iroquois than I
am with any moral rules

00:25:12.630 --> 00:25:15.780
that my African ancestors lived
by because I'm actually not sure

00:25:15.780 --> 00:25:18.050
who my African ancestors were.

00:25:18.050 --> 00:25:20.650
And my basic understanding of
this law is that it teaches

00:25:20.650 --> 00:25:23.160
that we must consider the
impact of our actions on those

00:25:23.160 --> 00:25:26.050
who will live seven
generations from now.

00:25:26.050 --> 00:25:28.560
And I know that when
colonial processes begin,

00:25:28.560 --> 00:25:31.340
no one is really thinking of
the next seven generations.

00:25:31.340 --> 00:25:33.970
It's just not how
colonialism works.

00:25:33.970 --> 00:25:36.840
And so because of this, the list
of anxieties that I experience

00:25:36.840 --> 00:25:39.400
when thinking about the
right stuff is really

00:25:39.400 --> 00:25:42.360
about whether we are--
have the right stuff.

00:25:42.360 --> 00:25:44.620
When I think about humans
arriving on another planet

00:25:44.620 --> 00:25:49.150
like Mars, you know, questions
I'm asking myself, could--

00:25:49.150 --> 00:25:51.260
and when we go to the
moon which is actually one

00:25:51.260 --> 00:25:53.700
of the first destinations,
I think, is could mining

00:25:53.700 --> 00:25:56.700
on the moon forever alter how
our future generations see this

00:25:56.700 --> 00:26:00.510
majestic and natural
satellite of Earth?

00:26:00.510 --> 00:26:03.560
Who will profit, who will
perish in the expedition?

00:26:03.560 --> 00:26:06.850
Will such missions ultimately
exacerbate inequalities

00:26:06.850 --> 00:26:08.860
that already exist on Earth?

00:26:08.860 --> 00:26:13.700
And in fact, well, missions to
Mars make life on Earth worse.

00:26:13.700 --> 00:26:16.220
How can we have these
conversations with a language

00:26:16.220 --> 00:26:19.930
that refuses to untwine
itself with the lingua franca

00:26:19.930 --> 00:26:23.740
of settler colonialism,
so discovery, exploration,

00:26:23.740 --> 00:26:26.220
settlement, colonizing,
you dig a little bit deep

00:26:26.220 --> 00:26:28.340
and these words come back
to settler colonialism.

00:26:28.340 --> 00:26:32.700
And then, what are possible
future generations on Mars?

00:26:32.700 --> 00:26:35.800
So by this, I don't
necessarily mean human

00:26:35.800 --> 00:26:39.610
or even Earth-originating life,
but who and what do we eclipse

00:26:39.610 --> 00:26:44.460
by choosing to lay
claim to land elsewhere.

00:26:44.460 --> 00:26:47.830
So I think about this
as a Star Trek fan.

00:26:47.830 --> 00:26:51.330
And, I mean, I'm in annual
Star Trek convention,

00:26:51.330 --> 00:26:56.320
gold ticket holding, seen every
episode of every series fan.

00:26:56.320 --> 00:26:59.590
Anyone who follows me on
social media had seen the many,

00:26:59.590 --> 00:27:01.700
many pictures to prove it.

00:27:01.700 --> 00:27:04.260
And we'll only think the show
has its problems on the whole,

00:27:04.260 --> 00:27:07.340
I've lived its expansive
vision not just of humanity

00:27:07.340 --> 00:27:11.000
but of humanoidity of all
of us humanoids learning how

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:13.020
to share not just a
planet but a galaxy.

00:27:13.020 --> 00:27:15.920
And so as a physicist,
I spend some time

00:27:15.920 --> 00:27:17.950
at the conventions
explaining to fellow fans

00:27:17.950 --> 00:27:20.850
that warp-speed travel,
travel at the speed of light,

00:27:20.850 --> 00:27:22.400
is probably not going to happen.

00:27:22.400 --> 00:27:25.340
And this means that the
key generative moment

00:27:25.340 --> 00:27:27.520
for first contact
with another species

00:27:27.520 --> 00:27:30.190
in the Star Trek universe,
humans reaching warp one

00:27:30.190 --> 00:27:31.490
and catching the attention

00:27:31.490 --> 00:27:33.250
of the Vulcans is probably
never going to happen.

00:27:33.250 --> 00:27:34.820
It's probably not possible.

00:27:34.820 --> 00:27:38.140
And it's likely possible that
even if Vulcans did exist

00:27:38.140 --> 00:27:40.700
and had better space travel
technology than we do,

00:27:40.700 --> 00:27:42.930
they still can't
travel at warp either

00:27:42.930 --> 00:27:46.750
and more likely they figured out
how to live multigenerationally

00:27:46.750 --> 00:27:48.670
on a ship that could
take multiples

00:27:48.670 --> 00:27:51.210
of seven generations
to get anywhere.

00:27:51.210 --> 00:27:55.870
So, then again, physicists have
often been wrong in the past

00:27:55.870 --> 00:27:57.200
about what is possible
so I always

00:27:57.200 --> 00:27:59.730
like to include this caveat, so
maybe we will be wrong again.

00:27:59.730 --> 00:28:02.090
So as I was thinking about
coming to this event,

00:28:02.090 --> 00:28:03.670
I reached out to Connor Trinneer

00:28:03.670 --> 00:28:05.900
who played the engineer
Trip Trucker

00:28:05.900 --> 00:28:08.240
on the penultimate Star
Trek series, Enterprise.

00:28:08.240 --> 00:28:10.130
I don't know if anybody
else is a Trip fan.

00:28:10.130 --> 00:28:13.280
I was. And I was especially
keen to hear from Connor

00:28:13.280 --> 00:28:15.230
because Enterprise is
the series that deals

00:28:15.230 --> 00:28:17.660
with Earth's first forays
from the solar system

00:28:17.660 --> 00:28:20.790
and how humans go on to
form the storied federation

00:28:20.790 --> 00:28:23.030
of the Vulcans, so this is
kind of the origin story.

00:28:23.030 --> 00:28:26.060
So, he had to deal
with things like what

00:28:26.060 --> 00:28:28.430
if a planet didn't have
animals but the air was filled

00:28:28.430 --> 00:28:29.730
with psychedelic Pollan,

00:28:29.730 --> 00:28:31.720
that was a great
acting episode for him.

00:28:31.720 --> 00:28:35.400
What if having sex with an
alien woman got a human cis

00:28:35.400 --> 00:28:36.700
man pregnant?

00:28:36.700 --> 00:28:38.360
These were just some of the
scenarios that he had to get

00:28:38.360 --> 00:28:41.690
into character for so that
Trip could grapple with them.

00:28:41.690 --> 00:28:45.210
So, I expected Connor to
tell me to mention something

00:28:45.210 --> 00:28:47.990
about the Prime Directive, the
Vulcan rule which is adapted

00:28:47.990 --> 00:28:50.950
by the federation and
teaches us not to interfere

00:28:50.950 --> 00:28:53.690
with the internal
development of other species.

00:28:53.690 --> 00:28:55.570
But instead, he said
something to me

00:28:55.570 --> 00:28:58.830
that perhaps reflects his
childhood in a community

00:28:58.830 --> 00:29:02.460
that had a strong presence of
both native and white people.

00:29:02.460 --> 00:29:05.740
He always thought that if
we did meet another species,

00:29:05.740 --> 00:29:08.660
it would be because they wanted
something from us and that

00:29:08.660 --> 00:29:10.720
that could get uncomfortable
pretty quickly.

00:29:10.720 --> 00:29:14.050
So I hadn't really thought
about that going into this sort

00:29:14.050 --> 00:29:15.980
of ironically because I
guess it's the storyline

00:29:15.980 --> 00:29:17.570
from pretty much
every alien film.

00:29:17.570 --> 00:29:20.990
You can tell I don't really
actually watch alien films.

00:29:20.990 --> 00:29:23.060
They always want something
from us and it's never good

00:29:23.060 --> 00:29:25.570
and much has been written
by indigenous scholars,

00:29:25.570 --> 00:29:28.190
both here in the Americas and
elsewhere, about how the style

00:29:28.190 --> 00:29:31.410
of storytelling reflects
the kind of white anxiety

00:29:31.410 --> 00:29:34.050
that one day they might
become the victims of the kind

00:29:34.050 --> 00:29:37.800
of colonial apocalypse they
visited on indigenous people

00:29:37.800 --> 00:29:41.670
in Africa, the Americas, the
Pacific islands, Australia

00:29:41.670 --> 00:29:44.100
and New Zealand and
Asia, even sometimes

00:29:44.100 --> 00:29:47.670
on their own European
Peninsula of Asia.

00:29:47.670 --> 00:29:50.870
But what struck me in
thinking about Connor's framing

00:29:50.870 --> 00:29:53.390
of it was, in fact, how
we could be the ones

00:29:53.390 --> 00:29:56.680
who want something
so it could be us.

00:29:56.680 --> 00:29:59.190
We could be the ones who
want something from Mars

00:29:59.190 --> 00:30:03.620
and from the moon, perhaps to
buy time by extracting resources

00:30:03.620 --> 00:30:05.680
that we learn-- we
refuse to learn how

00:30:05.680 --> 00:30:07.750
to conserve here
on planet Earth.

00:30:07.750 --> 00:30:11.050
So a question that I think
we should ask ourselves is,

00:30:11.050 --> 00:30:13.370
in wanting something,
do we eclipse futures

00:30:13.370 --> 00:30:16.060
that we are not confident
to imagine,

00:30:16.060 --> 00:30:18.670
do we violate the Prime
Directive before there is a

00:30:18.670 --> 00:30:20.710
civilization to even disrupt.

00:30:20.710 --> 00:30:24.950
So some of you may be aware
that I became a bit notorious

00:30:24.950 --> 00:30:28.640
in the astronomy community
for supporting Kanaka Maoli,

00:30:28.640 --> 00:30:30.890
Native Hawaiians who
oppose the building

00:30:30.890 --> 00:30:33.780
of the Thirty Meter Telescope
on the Mauna Kea volcano.

00:30:33.780 --> 00:30:38.310
I have an undergraduate degree
in physics and astrophysics

00:30:38.310 --> 00:30:40.670
and astronomy, it's actually
grammatically incorrect

00:30:40.670 --> 00:30:43.660
on my diploma and a master's in
astronomy and a PhD in a field

00:30:43.660 --> 00:30:46.080
that blends astronomy
and physics, cosmology.

00:30:46.080 --> 00:30:49.150
So I got a lot of accusations
that I just hate science

00:30:49.150 --> 00:30:52.650
and that's why I was doing this,
but my support for them was not

00:30:52.650 --> 00:30:55.270
because I hate science,
not because I don't

00:30:55.270 --> 00:30:56.800
like pretty pictures of galaxies

00:30:56.800 --> 00:31:00.110
or think Kanaka Maoli shouldn't
be allowed to participate

00:31:00.110 --> 00:31:01.750
in the kind of scientific
work that I do.

00:31:01.750 --> 00:31:04.310
I actually get an
extensive amount of hate mail

00:31:04.310 --> 00:31:05.770
with that particular accusation.

00:31:05.770 --> 00:31:09.410
I was accused of these things by
people who were more interested

00:31:09.410 --> 00:31:12.090
in character assassination
than dialogue, I think.

00:31:12.090 --> 00:31:15.510
But the truth is as a
descendant of slaves and a child

00:31:15.510 --> 00:31:18.580
of a small tropical
island, Barbados,

00:31:18.580 --> 00:31:21.360
I understood the terrible
entanglement between science

00:31:21.360 --> 00:31:23.550
and a failure to imagine
other ways of being

00:31:23.550 --> 00:31:24.890
and other ways of knowing.

00:31:24.890 --> 00:31:29.120
So much of-- as my research is
about curiosity and imagination,

00:31:29.120 --> 00:31:33.580
my day-to-day realities as
a scientist are deeply tied

00:31:33.580 --> 00:31:36.040
to science as a tool that
enhances colonialism,

00:31:36.040 --> 00:31:38.710
and that has been one of
my struggles as a student

00:31:38.710 --> 00:31:40.920
and practitioner of science.

00:31:40.920 --> 00:31:44.150
So to give some examples,
astronomers were once funded

00:31:44.150 --> 00:31:46.800
to watch an eclipse
from Haiti in order

00:31:46.800 --> 00:31:49.350
to enhance our ability
to measure distances.

00:31:49.350 --> 00:31:51.610
And this was to ensure
that slaves

00:31:51.610 --> 00:31:55.600
and goods would move
faster across the Atlantic.

00:31:55.600 --> 00:31:58.740
Today, they are funded to
help develop adaptive optics

00:31:58.740 --> 00:32:00.100
and military technology

00:32:00.100 --> 00:32:02.220
that makes our beautiful
pictures clearer.

00:32:02.220 --> 00:32:04.450
All of the telescopes on
Mauna Kea have been fitted

00:32:04.450 --> 00:32:06.650
with adaptive optics technology.

00:32:06.650 --> 00:32:09.130
But they make their pictures
clearer whether they are spy

00:32:09.130 --> 00:32:11.870
images or galaxy images.

00:32:11.870 --> 00:32:14.640
We are only a few years out from
an award-winning white woman

00:32:14.640 --> 00:32:16.140
astronomer, Sandy Faber,

00:32:16.140 --> 00:32:19.540
referring to Kanaka Maoli
protectors as they are known

00:32:19.540 --> 00:32:24.340
of Mauna Kea as a "horde of
natives" attacking astronomy.

00:32:24.340 --> 00:32:27.240
Her words were recirculated
uncritically by leaders

00:32:27.240 --> 00:32:29.840
in our field such as the chair
of the astronomy department

00:32:29.840 --> 00:32:31.750
at UC Berkeley, until
students some

00:32:31.750 --> 00:32:35.270
of them Native American sounded
the alarm to the rest of us.

00:32:35.270 --> 00:32:39.010
So it is in this context I
ask about human travel to Mars

00:32:39.010 --> 00:32:43.990
or really anywhere, even
across the Atlantic, why now?

00:32:43.990 --> 00:32:47.310
Do we have the right stuff
to connect with other lands,

00:32:47.310 --> 00:32:49.490
when the most powerful
among us refuse

00:32:49.490 --> 00:32:53.040
to acknowledge our relationship
to the lands that we know

00:32:53.040 --> 00:32:55.110
or the lands that we knew?

00:32:55.110 --> 00:32:58.260
Do we have the right time in
human history for this new way

00:32:58.260 --> 00:33:00.470
of being in the solar system?

00:33:00.470 --> 00:33:02.450
What meaning does a
mission to Mars have

00:33:02.450 --> 00:33:06.660
for making black lives
matter, for being idle no more?

00:33:06.660 --> 00:33:08.970
Will it keep our waters safe?

00:33:08.970 --> 00:33:11.080
The promise of technological
advancement

00:33:11.080 --> 00:33:14.860
that will improve lives
and enhance exploration

00:33:14.860 --> 00:33:18.690
as tantalizing, but then what
of Ferguson, is a pipeline

00:33:18.690 --> 00:33:21.690
through standing rock progress
for the people of that land?

00:33:21.690 --> 00:33:25.780
Is the global warming we have
achieved through technology?

00:33:25.780 --> 00:33:28.410
And this can be read as
an achievement of a kind

00:33:28.410 --> 00:33:31.140
that we know how to
warm an entire planet.

00:33:31.140 --> 00:33:32.950
Is that progress?

00:33:32.950 --> 00:33:35.310
And in relation to that,
is our relationship

00:33:35.310 --> 00:33:36.920
to progress catastrophic?

00:33:36.920 --> 00:33:39.240
So these are the
questions that I have

00:33:39.240 --> 00:33:41.520
when we consider what is
the right stuff for us

00:33:41.520 --> 00:33:46.570
and what is the right stuff
for the solar system around us.

00:33:48.110 --> 00:33:50.160
&gt;&gt; Ashley Shew: Well, if she
had a hard job I have even more

00:33:50.160 --> 00:33:51.460
difficult one.

00:33:51.460 --> 00:33:55.230
It's hard to go last
after a panel like this.

00:33:55.230 --> 00:33:58.760
So I work on disability
narratives.

00:33:58.760 --> 00:34:00.650
So what would I be doing here?

00:34:00.650 --> 00:34:02.400
The assumption with
the right stuff is

00:34:02.400 --> 00:34:08.840
that disabled people aren't,
they don't have the right stuff.

00:34:08.840 --> 00:34:11.970
My particular work
is on technoableism,

00:34:11.970 --> 00:34:15.410
meaning I think a lot about how
the narratives of technology

00:34:15.410 --> 00:34:18.730
that we have often
reinforce ableism.

00:34:18.730 --> 00:34:24.980
And, sometimes do this by using
the language of empowerment

00:34:24.980 --> 00:34:28.290
to cover up an ableist
narrative about disabled lives

00:34:28.290 --> 00:34:31.100
that would see us as defective
and needing to be fixed.

00:34:31.100 --> 00:34:32.810
But oh, yay, technology.

00:34:32.810 --> 00:34:35.020
So a lot of the ways
in which I think

00:34:35.020 --> 00:34:38.850
about how disabled people
have or have not been included

00:34:38.850 --> 00:34:41.260
in what counts is
having the right stuff,

00:34:41.260 --> 00:34:43.250
it takes three different veins.

00:34:43.250 --> 00:34:46.910
So, the first is, I've been
thinking about how everyone

00:34:46.910 --> 00:34:49.100
in space is going
to disabled anyway.

00:34:49.100 --> 00:34:51.470
So we don't recruit people with
disabilities, but if you go

00:34:51.470 --> 00:34:54.380
up in space, the changes
to your body will mean

00:34:54.380 --> 00:34:58.360
that you come back
with some sort

00:34:58.360 --> 00:35:00.770
of disability whether it's
a temporary disability

00:35:00.770 --> 00:35:03.880
or more long term if we're
talking about changes to vision,

00:35:03.880 --> 00:35:06.670
if we're talking about
things like osteoporosis.

00:35:06.670 --> 00:35:11.510
I'm also thinking in this vein
that everyone who goes to space,

00:35:11.510 --> 00:35:13.850
if we're talking about
becoming interplanetary,

00:35:13.850 --> 00:35:19.060
might want to make themselves
more like disabled people.

00:35:19.060 --> 00:35:25.880
So when I think about how we
address different disabilities

00:35:25.880 --> 00:35:28.460
and the technologies of
those involved, my friend,

00:35:28.460 --> 00:35:30.410
Mallory Kay Nelson [assumed
spelling], when I started,

00:35:30.410 --> 00:35:32.090
we were having a
conversation about space poop

00:35:32.090 --> 00:35:33.390
because it's my favorite.

00:35:33.390 --> 00:35:34.850
And, sorry, Lucianne.

00:35:34.850 --> 00:35:40.230
And, she-- we were talking about
how hard it is to poop in space

00:35:40.230 --> 00:35:42.890
and all the different like
attempts to make good toilets

00:35:42.890 --> 00:35:44.910
in space, it's really
hard, y'all.

00:35:44.910 --> 00:35:46.840
And, she was like, you know,

00:35:46.840 --> 00:35:49.960
astronauts should
just have ostomy bags.

00:35:49.960 --> 00:35:53.480
We should change their digestive
tracts, such that instead

00:35:53.480 --> 00:35:56.190
of taping a bag to your anus,

00:35:56.190 --> 00:35:58.600
you already have a
bag system worked out

00:35:58.600 --> 00:36:01.410
and all the equipment that's
involved and that sort of thing.

00:36:01.410 --> 00:36:05.850
And it's not-- it's going be a
lot less gross actually in terms

00:36:05.850 --> 00:36:08.450
of the accidents that
happen with space poop.

00:36:08.450 --> 00:36:12.040
So just to think about
cyborgyzing ourselves to think

00:36:12.040 --> 00:36:15.630
about both being and
becoming disabled in space,

00:36:15.630 --> 00:36:17.620
it's one of the lines
through which I think

00:36:17.620 --> 00:36:18.920
about these things.

00:36:18.920 --> 00:36:21.660
The second has to
do with recent work

00:36:21.660 --> 00:36:25.160
from disabled and deaf artists.

00:36:25.160 --> 00:36:29.450
So if you follow the
#CripsInSpace on Twitter,

00:36:29.450 --> 00:36:33.460
there was a recent issue of the
Deaf Poets Society that focused

00:36:33.460 --> 00:36:38.750
on space narratives from
people with disabilities.

00:36:38.750 --> 00:36:43.240
And asked about what bodies
were actually best to send up

00:36:43.240 --> 00:36:46.120
and about the narratives
they've heard about space life.

00:36:46.120 --> 00:36:50.900
So part of it is, you know,
feeling as if when you're told

00:36:50.900 --> 00:36:54.370
as a child you could do
anything, that's not true a lot

00:36:54.370 --> 00:36:55.670
of times for disabled people.

00:36:55.670 --> 00:36:58.480
We know who gets recruited
for things, who can serve

00:36:58.480 --> 00:37:02.130
in military and space context,
and it's not disabled people.

00:37:02.130 --> 00:37:03.430
But also in terms

00:37:03.430 --> 00:37:07.210
of how disabled people might
be better at going to space.

00:37:07.210 --> 00:37:08.840
So some of these
artist narratives,

00:37:08.840 --> 00:37:11.240
Sam de Leve [assumed spelling],
one of the co-editors,

00:37:11.240 --> 00:37:14.590
they talk about how navigating
the world on a wheelchair,

00:37:14.590 --> 00:37:16.880
they're always pushing
off of other surfaces.

00:37:16.880 --> 00:37:20.410
Like this looks a lot
more like lower gravity.

00:37:20.410 --> 00:37:23.430
When you think about how
bodies move in space, in fact,

00:37:23.430 --> 00:37:27.600
physically disabled people might
be much more adept at movement

00:37:27.600 --> 00:37:29.670
in lower gravity just from all

00:37:29.670 --> 00:37:31.360
of the training they've
been doing on Earth

00:37:31.360 --> 00:37:37.060
on navigating surfaces in ways
that people who ambulate do not.

00:37:37.060 --> 00:37:38.830
The third way in which
I'm thinking about some

00:37:38.830 --> 00:37:41.720
of these things is
about how disabled

00:37:41.720 --> 00:37:44.490
and deaf people have been
included in space research

00:37:44.490 --> 00:37:46.970
but never considered
candidates for going.

00:37:46.970 --> 00:37:50.130
So during the 1950s and '60s,
you have the Gallaudet Eleven,

00:37:50.130 --> 00:37:54.810
which it consisted of 11 people
who were deaf from Gallaudet.

00:37:54.810 --> 00:37:56.670
Yeah, I guess you guys just
could have filled that in

00:37:56.670 --> 00:37:58.570
from your prior knowledge.

00:37:58.570 --> 00:38:02.640
But, there were all these tests
about motion sickness, right?

00:38:02.640 --> 00:38:09.380
So, the people they recruited,
because of hearing loss that had

00:38:09.380 --> 00:38:13.760
to do with inner ear conditions,
they don't get motion sick.

00:38:13.760 --> 00:38:16.260
So, in testing for how
people might go to space,

00:38:16.260 --> 00:38:19.700
they use deaf bodies
to figure out things

00:38:19.700 --> 00:38:21.560
about motion sickness
instead of saying, "Hey,

00:38:21.560 --> 00:38:25.250
maybe we should recruit deaf
people to actually be part

00:38:25.250 --> 00:38:27.710
of this test because they don't
experience motion sickness

00:38:27.710 --> 00:38:30.750
in this way", but they were used
as a test ground to help figure

00:38:30.750 --> 00:38:33.610
out how able-bodied people could
go space instead of saying,

00:38:33.610 --> 00:38:35.930
maybe these people
ought to be considered

00:38:35.930 --> 00:38:37.230
as candidates as well.

00:38:37.230 --> 00:38:38.720
So I think throughout in
these three different lenses

00:38:38.720 --> 00:38:40.580
when I'm thinking
about the relationship

00:38:40.580 --> 00:38:45.160
of disability narrative and
becoming interplanetary.

00:38:45.160 --> 00:38:48.800
And I think about the
discriminatory like things

00:38:48.800 --> 00:38:50.330
that are already built
in to what's going

00:38:50.330 --> 00:38:53.610
to be the right stuff
that there is right stuff.

00:38:53.610 --> 00:38:56.280
And that someone can have it
at all and that we don't need

00:38:56.280 --> 00:38:58.450
like a variety of
people with lots

00:38:58.450 --> 00:39:00.650
of different types of stuff.

00:39:00.650 --> 00:39:01.970
I'll turn it over
to you, Lucianne.

00:39:01.970 --> 00:39:03.270
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: OK.

00:39:03.270 --> 00:39:04.700
Thank you to all the panelists

00:39:04.700 --> 00:39:08.770
for these wonderful
provocative opening statements.

00:39:08.770 --> 00:39:14.180
I promise we will return to
space poop later in the panel.

00:39:14.180 --> 00:39:19.270
I'd like to return momentarily
for our first question

00:39:19.270 --> 00:39:24.450
to really the central theme
of this particular panel.

00:39:24.450 --> 00:39:25.800
And that we've talked a lot

00:39:25.800 --> 00:39:28.600
about making science
more inclusive

00:39:28.600 --> 00:39:31.200
or space exploration
more diverse,

00:39:31.200 --> 00:39:35.720
or broadening the definition
of who can be an explorer.

00:39:35.720 --> 00:39:39.730
And I-- One of the-- And I
should mention also that in each

00:39:39.730 --> 00:39:41.430
of the panels that
you'll see today,

00:39:41.430 --> 00:39:44.480
the panels have all
participated in pre-event calls,

00:39:44.480 --> 00:39:47.530
so I want to thank them for
being the co-creators of some

00:39:47.530 --> 00:39:51.300
of the questions that
we'll be talking about.

00:39:51.300 --> 00:39:55.700
But I'd like to start with
what is diversity for,

00:39:55.700 --> 00:40:00.540
and maybe I can prompt
Chanda to do,

00:40:00.540 --> 00:40:04.730
as she is already
doing, reach of the mic.

00:40:04.730 --> 00:40:06.030
&gt;&gt; Chanda Prescod-Weinstein:
Yeah.

00:40:06.030 --> 00:40:07.330
So I think that this was
one of the things that came

00:40:07.330 --> 00:40:12.120
up in our pre-call and if
I were to do a little bit

00:40:12.120 --> 00:40:15.150
of self-advertising, I
have an article coming our

00:40:15.150 --> 00:40:16.670
in the science journal

00:40:16.670 --> 00:40:22.210
of feminism next year called
Making Black Women Scientists

00:40:22.210 --> 00:40:23.620
Under a White Empiricism.

00:40:23.620 --> 00:40:26.410
And one of the things that
I talk about is that all

00:40:26.410 --> 00:40:29.960
of our arguments for
diversity at the funding level,

00:40:29.960 --> 00:40:33.810
at the federal level, and this
is encoded in our documentation,

00:40:33.810 --> 00:40:37.620
is that it's-- diversity is
necessary for national security

00:40:37.620 --> 00:40:40.360
and it's necessary for
workforce purposes.

00:40:40.360 --> 00:40:44.360
And so, this rubs me the wrong
way as an African American,

00:40:44.360 --> 00:40:47.760
as an Afro-Caribbean
person, because it returns us

00:40:47.760 --> 00:40:50.930
to black people being
necessary for labor purposes.

00:40:50.930 --> 00:40:53.600
I mean, at least this time,
the plan is to pay people

00:40:53.600 --> 00:40:56.450
so that's good and to
sort of allow them to live

00:40:56.450 --> 00:41:00.480
where they want to,
redlining is still a thing.

00:41:00.480 --> 00:41:03.430
So, I think that when
we talk about diversity,

00:41:03.430 --> 00:41:06.200
somehow white people
continue to get to be curious

00:41:06.200 --> 00:41:10.410
and black people continue
to be there for the sake

00:41:10.410 --> 00:41:12.980
of supporting white
curiosity, in some sense.

00:41:12.980 --> 00:41:15.560
And so we're still kind
of the support stuff.

00:41:15.560 --> 00:41:19.940
And so I'm very troubled by
that, and I think really want

00:41:19.940 --> 00:41:24.040
to turn towards an
intersectional post-colonial

00:41:24.040 --> 00:41:26.730
analysis rather than analyzing

00:41:26.730 --> 00:41:29.010
from a diverse--
diversity standpoint.

00:41:29.010 --> 00:41:32.010
I actually think that
diversity can be quite dangerous

00:41:32.010 --> 00:41:34.810
because it allows us to
sidestep these conversations

00:41:34.810 --> 00:41:39.020
about colonialism and about
having equal access to rights.

00:41:39.020 --> 00:41:42.240
So, we're not talking about
the privilege of going to Mars

00:41:42.240 --> 00:41:46.380
or whatever, we're talking
about having the same ability

00:41:46.380 --> 00:41:49.440
to access your right
to participate

00:41:49.440 --> 00:41:53.350
in whatever human society
has decided to do with itself

00:41:53.350 --> 00:41:55.670
that these are rights
that people are prevented

00:41:55.670 --> 00:41:57.550
from accessing rather
than privileges

00:41:57.550 --> 00:41:59.850
that are granted to some.

00:42:01.060 --> 00:42:02.740
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz:
Anyone else?

00:42:02.740 --> 00:42:09.020
I think I'd like to hear from
you, Brian, about how you think

00:42:09.020 --> 00:42:13.510
about inclusion in this
particular context given your

00:42:13.510 --> 00:42:15.810
work with space explorers.

00:42:18.460 --> 00:42:21.620
&gt;&gt; Brian Nord: It's hard-- yeah,
so, echoing everything that is--

00:42:21.620 --> 00:42:25.060
that what you just said.

00:42:25.060 --> 00:42:29.910
When-- So I'll start with how
our academic institutions tend

00:42:29.910 --> 00:42:33.730
to train us for changing
our inclusive practices

00:42:33.730 --> 00:42:35.030
and diversity.

00:42:35.030 --> 00:42:38.890
They tend to say,
hey, let's just--

00:42:38.890 --> 00:42:41.210
as Chanda said, let's
side step this and talk

00:42:41.210 --> 00:42:46.060
about maybe your implicit
bias or maybe what it means

00:42:46.060 --> 00:42:48.710
for these additional
human bodies to come

00:42:48.710 --> 00:42:50.920
and provide this
commodity of knowledge.

00:42:50.920 --> 00:42:52.530
And that's the only
way that we talk

00:42:52.530 --> 00:42:54.040
about in these academic
institutions.

00:42:54.040 --> 00:42:58.350
So, in spaces explorers,
we don't do that at all.

00:42:58.350 --> 00:43:02.000
We ignore that entire
conversation and we go

00:43:02.000 --> 00:43:05.670
for the key deeper
questions, I think, which are,

00:43:05.670 --> 00:43:13.260
how do humans think about--

00:43:13.260 --> 00:43:15.840
how do humans approach
ideas of justice?

00:43:15.840 --> 00:43:17.980
How do we think about how
we just treat each other

00:43:17.980 --> 00:43:19.280
on a one-on-one level?

00:43:19.280 --> 00:43:21.470
So, in the Space
Explorers Program this year,

00:43:21.470 --> 00:43:26.440
when we're in this building
for six or seven days,

00:43:26.440 --> 00:43:28.930
10 hours a day and the
sophomores are thinking

00:43:28.930 --> 00:43:35.440
about these questions, they
end up approaching it by having

00:43:35.440 --> 00:43:37.020
to get along with each other.

00:43:37.020 --> 00:43:41.600
Yeah-- Or in a context where
they are diverse group.

00:43:41.600 --> 00:43:48.000
And, the nuance comes in, in
the one-on-one conversations.

00:43:48.000 --> 00:43:52.580
And so we're there to ask them
questions to-- as they stumble,

00:43:52.580 --> 00:43:55.990
we're there to ask them
questions to answer

00:43:55.990 --> 00:43:57.670
for themselves and
approach them--

00:43:57.670 --> 00:44:00.360
approach the difficulties
head on.

00:44:00.360 --> 00:44:03.900
And so, I look at it and
our program looks at it

00:44:03.900 --> 00:44:10.090
as justice first and none
of these other aspects.

00:44:10.090 --> 00:44:11.390
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: Yeah.

00:44:11.390 --> 00:44:14.260
I had the great honor
of being a panelist

00:44:14.260 --> 00:44:17.700
on the Space Explorers Program
and I was really impressed

00:44:17.700 --> 00:44:19.930
with the depth of
thought and the centrality

00:44:19.930 --> 00:44:23.200
of the distribution
and ethics questions.

00:44:23.200 --> 00:44:27.050
Not just in the way it was
post to the students but also

00:44:27.050 --> 00:44:29.180
in the way that the
students dealt

00:44:29.180 --> 00:44:31.180
with those topics
first, I think.

00:44:31.180 --> 00:44:34.860
&gt;&gt; Brian Nord: They
were very honest.

00:44:34.860 --> 00:44:36.350
They didn't hold anything back.

00:44:36.350 --> 00:44:39.920
They asked some very challenging
questions especially in one

00:44:39.920 --> 00:44:43.550
of the contexts for these
100,000 person civilizations is

00:44:43.550 --> 00:44:44.850
the spaceships

00:44:44.850 --> 00:44:47.740
or multigenerational
spaceship Earth.

00:44:47.740 --> 00:44:52.170
And, they came up with
some pretty crazy answers,

00:44:52.170 --> 00:44:55.570
I won't go into them,
but there are things

00:44:55.570 --> 00:45:02.240
that we see our societies
using here that are not good.

00:45:02.240 --> 00:45:05.900
The control over the human
body was one of the ways

00:45:05.900 --> 00:45:07.880
that they were trying
to manage how do you--

00:45:07.880 --> 00:45:12.200
how you maintain this one
population on a spaceship.

00:45:12.200 --> 00:45:16.580
And so they answered those
questions in that, I think,

00:45:16.580 --> 00:45:20.420
negative way because they hadn't
been exposed to real way--

00:45:20.420 --> 00:45:23.900
or other ways of thinking
about it that are-- that--

00:45:24.910 --> 00:45:28.650
or thinking about humans as
humans and not as machines.

00:45:28.650 --> 00:45:29.950
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz:
Interesting.

00:45:29.950 --> 00:45:35.920
You know, when we talk about the
commodification of people for,

00:45:35.920 --> 00:45:40.000
you know, some purpose being
used as tools, you know,

00:45:40.000 --> 00:45:43.590
this larger enterprise, one
of the things that you raised,

00:45:43.590 --> 00:45:47.770
Brenda, during our call is that
there have often been cases

00:45:47.770 --> 00:45:49.920
in history and you
brought up American Indians

00:45:49.920 --> 00:45:53.690
in the military, where
something was considered

00:45:53.690 --> 00:45:55.970
to be a good thing
about a stereotype

00:45:55.970 --> 00:45:58.390
that ultimately was
harmful to the person.

00:45:58.390 --> 00:46:00.120
So maybe you could
speak to that.

00:46:00.120 --> 00:46:01.800
&gt;&gt; Brenda J. Child: Yeah.

00:46:01.800 --> 00:46:05.700
So, as I was thinking about
these questions in terms

00:46:05.700 --> 00:46:10.610
of American Indian history, I
kind of was reflecting on some

00:46:10.610 --> 00:46:14.470
of my early work which was about
the history of Indian education

00:46:14.470 --> 00:46:16.840
and how native people
were thought of,

00:46:16.840 --> 00:46:20.970
I'll get into the
military but, of course,

00:46:20.970 --> 00:46:24.870
when the federal government
was putting native people

00:46:24.870 --> 00:46:28.930
on reservations and wanted to
move to kind of privatization

00:46:28.930 --> 00:46:31.930
of land because Indians still
had a lot of real estate.

00:46:31.930 --> 00:46:36.770
They decided a companion
program would be to put children

00:46:36.770 --> 00:46:39.210
in off-reservation
boarding schools.

00:46:39.210 --> 00:46:42.380
And at that time, one of
the arguments for this

00:46:42.380 --> 00:46:44.870
in the late 19th century, I
mean, there were all sorts

00:46:44.870 --> 00:46:47.910
of reasons for doing it,
but one of the arguments

00:46:47.910 --> 00:46:50.720
from the perspective of
Washington and policymakers

00:46:50.720 --> 00:46:54.020
and people who kind of
thought about native issues is

00:46:54.020 --> 00:46:59.180
that native people seem to be
dying a lot in the 19th century

00:46:59.180 --> 00:47:03.170
or the late 19th century was our
kind of all-time population low

00:47:03.170 --> 00:47:06.740
and we're very vulnerable to
problems like tuberculosis.

00:47:06.740 --> 00:47:12.890
And, so, the boarding schools
were argued for as, you know,

00:47:12.890 --> 00:47:16.780
a way to help native people who
had kind of inferior bodies.

00:47:16.780 --> 00:47:21.660
And so they could enter into
athletic programs and things

00:47:21.660 --> 00:47:29.320
that would help them because
of their, you know, the poor--

00:47:29.320 --> 00:47:30.810
you know, what had
happened to them

00:47:30.810 --> 00:47:33.300
because of their
hereditary-- heredity.

00:47:33.300 --> 00:47:37.810
And so, that's interesting
that that's kind of one side

00:47:37.810 --> 00:47:41.340
of how people have
looked at and policymakers

00:47:41.340 --> 00:47:43.040
and reformers native bodies.

00:47:43.040 --> 00:47:47.490
And then, some-- at some point,
things changed, and maybe it had

00:47:47.490 --> 00:47:49.050
to do with kind of high rates

00:47:49.050 --> 00:47:52.480
of native people's
military participation

00:47:52.480 --> 00:47:54.720
in the 20th century, where
they were then thought

00:47:54.720 --> 00:47:56.980
of as having desirable bodies

00:47:56.980 --> 00:48:00.070
because they were
so good at hunting.

00:48:00.070 --> 00:48:02.470
They were so good at gathering.

00:48:02.470 --> 00:48:04.490
They were so good scouts.

00:48:04.490 --> 00:48:07.260
And so, to the detriment,
I think, of native people,

00:48:07.260 --> 00:48:10.620
they were often put on
the kind of frontlines

00:48:10.620 --> 00:48:13.180
in military conflict
since World War I.

00:48:13.180 --> 00:48:17.200
So, native people-- the
ideas about native people

00:48:17.200 --> 00:48:21.040
and whether they have the right
stuff or not, has kind of comes

00:48:21.040 --> 00:48:24.880
and goes with federal policies.

00:48:24.880 --> 00:48:26.180
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: Yeah.

00:48:26.180 --> 00:48:29.450
And I'm struck at how this
parallels the disability

00:48:29.450 --> 00:48:33.020
narratives that you brought
up in your opening comments

00:48:33.020 --> 00:48:36.760
about like the Gallaudet Eleven.

00:48:36.760 --> 00:48:39.210
What do you think
the underlying--

00:48:39.210 --> 00:48:42.450
well, I think I know the
answer to this question,

00:48:42.450 --> 00:48:47.070
but what is the underlying
pushback against people

00:48:47.070 --> 00:48:50.740
who are disabled here on Earth
having active participation?

00:48:50.740 --> 00:48:53.800
What do you hear most
often in response?

00:48:53.800 --> 00:48:56.200
&gt;&gt; Ashley Shew: If you
know the answer, no.

00:48:56.200 --> 00:49:01.390
Well, I mean, we have a
pervasive culture of ableism

00:49:01.390 --> 00:49:04.130
that almost everyone
participates in.

00:49:04.130 --> 00:49:05.430
You know, I'm disabled,

00:49:05.430 --> 00:49:08.250
I'm still on learning
ableism every day, right?

00:49:08.250 --> 00:49:11.620
The assumption that disabled
people are enable to do things

00:49:11.620 --> 00:49:15.100
in history that undergirds that,

00:49:15.100 --> 00:49:17.270
history that includes
institutionalization,

00:49:17.270 --> 00:49:21.140
push people out of sight,
right, if they don't behave

00:49:21.140 --> 00:49:24.080
in the ways you hope they will.

00:49:24.080 --> 00:49:27.490
And often, that just
means they target people

00:49:27.490 --> 00:49:28.790
who are poor, right?

00:49:28.790 --> 00:49:32.220
We also have a history
of sheltered workshops.

00:49:32.220 --> 00:49:34.210
So when you talk about the
commodification of people,

00:49:34.210 --> 00:49:38.550
you can still pay disabled
people subminimum wage, right,

00:49:38.550 --> 00:49:40.550
in segregated workplaces.

00:49:40.550 --> 00:49:44.630
Those are beginning to
become undone, there's a push

00:49:44.630 --> 00:49:48.010
to eliminate these things and
a push to get subminimum wages

00:49:48.010 --> 00:49:54.340
to not have that anymore,
but it's also still there.

00:49:54.340 --> 00:49:56.500
You know, we're still closing

00:49:56.500 --> 00:49:58.400
down institutions
in Virginia, right?

00:49:58.400 --> 00:50:04.610
We're close to Virginia
that-- what was the--

00:50:04.610 --> 00:50:07.980
Virginia, I think, Colony for
the Epileptics and Feebleminded,

00:50:07.980 --> 00:50:10.330
it has a new name since the '80s

00:50:10.330 --> 00:50:12.830
but it won't be shutdown
until 2020.

00:50:12.830 --> 00:50:15.910
Like we're still in a history
that we're dealing with,

00:50:15.910 --> 00:50:17.520
the legacies of ableism.

00:50:17.520 --> 00:50:20.490
Disabled people are--
have much higher rates

00:50:20.490 --> 00:50:23.580
of underemployment even under
good employment conditions.

00:50:23.580 --> 00:50:26.670
The idea that you have to
hide if you're disabled

00:50:26.670 --> 00:50:29.350
if you're going to go in for a
job interview is very common.

00:50:29.350 --> 00:50:32.010
I'm an amputee and my
amputee groups, they say,

00:50:32.010 --> 00:50:35.270
wear pants to an interview,
don't wear a skirt.

00:50:35.270 --> 00:50:38.760
Don't wear, you know, shoes
that'll reveal in any way

00:50:38.760 --> 00:50:40.730
that you're disabled because
they'll think you can't do

00:50:40.730 --> 00:50:42.030
things, right?

00:50:42.030 --> 00:50:44.510
Even when we have
technologized bodies

00:50:44.510 --> 00:50:48.140
that sometimes allow
different functionalities

00:50:48.140 --> 00:50:52.320
that people might expect,
it's still the case that a lot

00:50:52.320 --> 00:50:54.850
of people hide they're
disabled and they do

00:50:54.850 --> 00:50:56.470
that for military
service too, right,

00:50:56.470 --> 00:51:00.860
if you have any mental
health issue raised,

00:51:00.860 --> 00:51:02.300
you're not getting
into the military.

00:51:02.300 --> 00:51:06.210
It's not just about
physical disabilities here,

00:51:06.210 --> 00:51:08.520
the doubts people have
about whether you'll be able

00:51:08.520 --> 00:51:11.750
to do things are huge.

00:51:11.750 --> 00:51:15.170
And I think that exists for a
lot of different populations

00:51:15.170 --> 00:51:20.630
but it's one that, in terms of
recruitment for space, right,

00:51:20.630 --> 00:51:23.770
there's a compulsory able
bodiedness to a lot of things

00:51:23.770 --> 00:51:27.150
that we do, but it's much
more intensified when we talk

00:51:27.150 --> 00:51:32.110
about recruitment programs
for space exploration

00:51:32.110 --> 00:51:34.380
or for the military
or for anything

00:51:34.380 --> 00:51:38.070
where physical prowess is
valued, maybe mistakenly

00:51:38.070 --> 00:51:40.900
at times, right, because I can
think about different types

00:51:40.900 --> 00:51:44.770
of disabled bodies that might
navigate surfaces much better

00:51:44.770 --> 00:51:46.760
in space than actually
able-bodied people.

00:51:46.760 --> 00:51:48.610
But we're not often
very creative

00:51:48.610 --> 00:51:50.780
about thinking about
bodies at all.

00:51:50.780 --> 00:51:53.780
Like one thing you find out when
you become disabled is you have

00:51:53.780 --> 00:51:56.110
to adapt every day and
work around surfaces

00:51:56.110 --> 00:51:57.730
in a way you never expected.

00:51:57.730 --> 00:51:59.390
That's a lot like when
astronauts will go

00:51:59.390 --> 00:52:00.690
to space, right?

00:52:00.690 --> 00:52:01.990
You have then to
think creatively

00:52:01.990 --> 00:52:04.530
about the spaces you're in
and how you'll move in them

00:52:04.530 --> 00:52:08.770
and think ahead and plan
ahead or planning ahead.

00:52:08.770 --> 00:52:12.980
And, you know, there's
this whole different world

00:52:12.980 --> 00:52:15.080
that you have to adapt to.

00:52:15.080 --> 00:52:19.610
And I think most humans don't
necessarily think about that,

00:52:19.610 --> 00:52:22.490
because a lot of the
spaces are already made

00:52:22.490 --> 00:52:27.310
to suit people who
are non-disabled.

00:52:27.310 --> 00:52:29.950
So, you know, when I think

00:52:29.950 --> 00:52:32.940
about how we creatively
address spaces,

00:52:32.940 --> 00:52:35.800
thinking about disabled
bodies, I think, provides a lot

00:52:35.800 --> 00:52:39.290
of excitement for me about
what could be done differently

00:52:39.290 --> 00:52:41.380
in this vein by this
commodification,

00:52:41.380 --> 00:52:42.680
I think, underlies it all.

00:52:42.680 --> 00:52:44.070
I think you hit it in
your first comment, Brian,

00:52:44.070 --> 00:52:46.840
this commodification
bodies, whose bodies

00:52:46.840 --> 00:52:50.830
and minds do we value
is central here.

00:52:51.880 --> 00:52:54.960
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz:
Yeah, go on, please.

00:52:54.960 --> 00:52:57.640
&gt;&gt; Brian Nord: So, I'm wondering
if I can ask a question

00:52:57.640 --> 00:53:00.690
of some panelists if they
have some thoughts about this.

00:53:00.690 --> 00:53:02.530
Over the weekend,
I was thinking,

00:53:02.530 --> 00:53:07.230
do we think that it would be
possible if one of the ideas

00:53:07.230 --> 00:53:09.080
of going into space,
one of the reasons,

00:53:09.080 --> 00:53:13.670
could it be to take everything
that we've learned about this

00:53:13.670 --> 00:53:14.970
and in a sense start over?

00:53:14.970 --> 00:53:20.990
Do you see that as a
reasonable reason to go?

00:53:20.990 --> 00:53:23.320
&gt;&gt; Chanda Prescod-Weinstein:
So, I guess--

00:53:23.320 --> 00:53:26.260
you know, I think the first
question I would ask is,

00:53:26.260 --> 00:53:29.040
how can we get out of a
conversation where we're talking

00:53:29.040 --> 00:53:32.200
about value and bodies at all.

00:53:32.200 --> 00:53:36.160
I-- And I think partly
because in--

00:53:36.160 --> 00:53:39.430
you know, from a philosophical
standpoint, I'm in a history

00:53:39.430 --> 00:53:41.740
of knowledge, that's
one knowledge system

00:53:41.740 --> 00:53:45.180
that we continue to operate in
that we never really get out of.

00:53:45.180 --> 00:53:48.520
And if we can't get
out of assuming

00:53:48.520 --> 00:53:51.790
that that axiomatic
starting point, that bodies

00:53:51.790 --> 00:53:54.780
and objects are things to be
valued and that land is a thing

00:53:54.780 --> 00:53:57.750
to be valued, then if we take
that as our starting point,

00:53:57.750 --> 00:54:00.740
it follows us into space.

00:54:00.740 --> 00:54:07.430
So, I think we can't
escape from ourselves.

00:54:07.430 --> 00:54:09.290
We always go with us.

00:54:09.290 --> 00:54:13.600
And, so, wherever we take the
experiment, we are running

00:54:13.600 --> 00:54:15.890
that experiment on,
can we be better,

00:54:15.890 --> 00:54:18.740
can we address knowledge
systems where--

00:54:18.740 --> 00:54:21.710
you know, to contextualize
for some people, some--

00:54:21.710 --> 00:54:24.130
one of the issues with Mauna
Kea because they didn't talk

00:54:24.130 --> 00:54:29.730
about this at all, is that Mauna
Kea is a traditionally sacred

00:54:29.730 --> 00:54:33.510
space for not all Kanaka Maoli
because there's quite a bit

00:54:33.510 --> 00:54:37.230
of diversity, but for people
who are spiritual practitioners,

00:54:37.230 --> 00:54:39.200
it was a burial ground.

00:54:39.200 --> 00:54:42.830
They don't use European
style markers that this is

00:54:42.830 --> 00:54:45.560
where the bodies are, so in
fact, you dig up a telescope

00:54:45.560 --> 00:54:48.950
and you're digging up
somebody's grave essentially.

00:54:48.950 --> 00:54:52.110
And in-- Not just
in native Hawaiian

00:54:52.110 --> 00:54:56.930
but several Pacific communities,
the land is a family member.

00:54:56.930 --> 00:55:00.780
So this is a violation
of a family member.

00:55:00.780 --> 00:55:04.310
And I think that when a
lot of people heard that,

00:55:04.310 --> 00:55:06.910
it can be read very
superficially, like, yeah, yeah,

00:55:06.910 --> 00:55:08.380
you think of the land as part

00:55:08.380 --> 00:55:10.820
of your culture,
part of your family.

00:55:10.820 --> 00:55:12.930
But I really think that the
challenge for those of us

00:55:12.930 --> 00:55:16.910
who did not grow up in that
knowledge system context is

00:55:16.910 --> 00:55:20.570
to sit with the idea, what
if this was my mother,

00:55:20.570 --> 00:55:22.650
what if this was my sister.

00:55:22.650 --> 00:55:23.960
And just to say to yourself,

00:55:23.960 --> 00:55:26.440
it doesn't matter whether
that's not intuitive for me,

00:55:26.440 --> 00:55:29.070
it is now my task to
make that intuitive.

00:55:29.070 --> 00:55:31.400
And I actually think as a
physicist, this is not hard

00:55:31.400 --> 00:55:34.530
because people come to me and
say, oh, quantum field theory,

00:55:34.530 --> 00:55:36.870
I'll never got it, or
general relativity, how did--

00:55:36.870 --> 00:55:39.760
I'm a relativist by
background and by training,

00:55:39.760 --> 00:55:42.560
how did you get used to the
idea of curve space time instead

00:55:42.560 --> 00:55:44.290
of thinking of gravity
as a force.

00:55:44.290 --> 00:55:46.950
And I told students that if
you sit with it long enough,

00:55:46.950 --> 00:55:49.350
eventually it becomes
intuitive to you.

00:55:49.350 --> 00:55:52.180
Curve space time is much more
intuitive to me than gravity

00:55:52.180 --> 00:55:55.300
as a force is, which is
maybe why I'm a relativist,

00:55:55.300 --> 00:55:57.480
maybe there's a-- how my
brain works type thing

00:55:57.480 --> 00:55:58.780
happening there.

00:55:58.780 --> 00:56:00.080
But the point is, is
that you sit with it.

00:56:00.080 --> 00:56:03.400
And so, I don't know if it
matters where we do the sitting

00:56:03.400 --> 00:56:04.990
but I think that we
have to do the sitting.

00:56:04.990 --> 00:56:07.300
And that's one of the reasons
the why now question is

00:56:07.300 --> 00:56:09.350
so important, and it
was the question I asked

00:56:09.350 --> 00:56:11.110
for the Thirty Meter Telescope.

00:56:11.110 --> 00:56:13.670
I love the idea of
having something

00:56:13.670 --> 00:56:15.190
like the Thirty Meter Telescope.

00:56:15.190 --> 00:56:18.880
I think I might be interested
in the idea of, for example,

00:56:18.880 --> 00:56:23.070
nuclear power as an
alternative energy source.

00:56:23.070 --> 00:56:25.530
But I want us to
do it in a moment

00:56:25.530 --> 00:56:27.870
where we can do it responsibly.

00:56:27.870 --> 00:56:30.420
And I don't know what
responsibly means,

00:56:30.420 --> 00:56:33.050
but I know that I don't
think that we are there yet,

00:56:33.050 --> 00:56:34.860
particularly with the
Thirty Meter Telescope.

00:56:34.860 --> 00:56:38.200
And I actually think that there
would have been a possibility

00:56:38.200 --> 00:56:40.900
that had the TMT
Corporation gone about things

00:56:40.900 --> 00:56:44.560
in a different way, the outcome
now might have been different.

00:56:44.560 --> 00:56:47.200
But they never actually
tried to get the by-end

00:56:47.200 --> 00:56:49.860
from the community and
have the conversation.

00:56:49.860 --> 00:56:52.460
And so in fact, I spent a
lot of time during the height

00:56:52.460 --> 00:56:53.760
of those protests, nobody

00:56:53.760 --> 00:56:55.550
in the astronomy community
ever asked me about this

00:56:55.550 --> 00:56:57.100
because they were too
busy pillaring me.

00:56:57.100 --> 00:56:59.790
I spent a lot of time explaining

00:56:59.790 --> 00:57:01.910
to people what the Thirty
Meter Telescope would do

00:57:01.910 --> 00:57:06.510
and why it mattered so much
to astronomers, and realizing

00:57:06.510 --> 00:57:08.850
that a lot of the protectors,
nobody had bothered to have

00:57:08.850 --> 00:57:12.310
that basic conversation
with them.

00:57:12.310 --> 00:57:14.050
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz:
Brenda, you wanted to--

00:57:14.050 --> 00:57:16.310
Just put it here, either way.

00:57:16.310 --> 00:57:18.050
&gt;&gt; Brenda J. Child:
Yeah, just in--

00:57:18.050 --> 00:57:19.950
I like your comments
very much, Chanda.

00:57:19.950 --> 00:57:25.400
I was thinking how another
sort of kind of a stereotype

00:57:25.400 --> 00:57:28.110
in another sort of
barrier to thinking

00:57:28.110 --> 00:57:30.800
about indigenous people
is having the right stuff,

00:57:30.800 --> 00:57:33.520
is that often we are not
thought of, I noticed,

00:57:33.520 --> 00:57:35.540
and even in the university
context,

00:57:35.540 --> 00:57:37.790
as not being modern people.

00:57:37.790 --> 00:57:41.320
And so, when you have something
like the telescope project

00:57:41.320 --> 00:57:44.760
and you have indigenous
people making, you know,

00:57:44.760 --> 00:57:50.050
an argument that this land is
sacred, it's like our mother.

00:57:50.050 --> 00:57:52.290
People are thought of as, well,

00:57:52.290 --> 00:57:55.620
you don't like science,
you're not modern.

00:57:55.620 --> 00:57:58.610
Well-- And in fact, indigenous
people just like they conceive

00:57:58.610 --> 00:58:01.830
of themselves as travelers
and explorers also think

00:58:01.830 --> 00:58:03.970
of themselves as scientist but

00:58:03.970 --> 00:58:06.310
yet respect is a
really important part

00:58:06.310 --> 00:58:11.040
of how native people
conceptualize their science.

00:58:11.040 --> 00:58:13.720
And sometimes I noticed in
the university that we get

00:58:13.720 --> 00:58:16.400
into conflicts at
my university, we--

00:58:16.400 --> 00:58:18.600
the Department of American
Indian Studies has gotten

00:58:18.600 --> 00:58:22.070
into conflicts with--
over telescope projects,

00:58:22.070 --> 00:58:24.820
the one in Arizona
at Mount Graham.

00:58:24.820 --> 00:58:28.370
And the argument was just,
you know, you don't--

00:58:28.370 --> 00:58:30.420
why are you oppose to
this, this is science

00:58:30.420 --> 00:58:32.070
and we have the right
to go in and do this.

00:58:32.070 --> 00:58:34.980
And it's like, we're not talking
about rights, we're talking

00:58:34.980 --> 00:58:37.370
about our responsibilities.

00:58:39.220 --> 00:58:40.520
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: Yeah.

00:58:40.520 --> 00:58:44.570
Yeah, certainly, it reminds
me also of some of the reading

00:58:44.570 --> 00:58:49.480
that I've been doing about like
the creation of national parks

00:58:49.480 --> 00:58:51.560
and the way that the
wilderness was thought

00:58:51.560 --> 00:58:54.010
about by settlers coming
in and thinking, well,

00:58:54.010 --> 00:58:59.750
like a wilderness is where
people aren't and not caring

00:58:59.750 --> 00:59:03.010
for the fact that it was, you
know, used by multiple nations

00:59:03.010 --> 00:59:05.950
that there had been
longstanding, you know,

00:59:05.950 --> 00:59:10.560
habitation there and the way
that those two things, you know,

00:59:10.560 --> 00:59:12.540
national parks which
people now think

00:59:12.540 --> 00:59:16.480
of as these wonderful treasures
was actually really tied,

00:59:16.480 --> 00:59:20.410
I think, to Native American
reservation creation as well

00:59:20.410 --> 00:59:22.990
and the dispossession of lands.

00:59:22.990 --> 00:59:27.580
And I had a question
that's totally gone now.

00:59:27.580 --> 00:59:30.900
So hopefully, it'll come back.

00:59:30.900 --> 00:59:34.590
You know, I think one of the
things that comes up again

00:59:34.590 --> 00:59:40.820
and again also is just access
to education and to information.

00:59:40.820 --> 00:59:44.940
And, the narratives that exist

00:59:44.940 --> 00:59:50.250
about having either specialized
knowledge or being allowed

00:59:50.250 --> 00:59:52.190
in a particular space.

00:59:52.190 --> 00:59:58.040
And I think also a commonality
that I hear throughout some

00:59:58.040 --> 01:00:00.840
of the things that we've been
talking about is the ways

01:00:00.840 --> 01:00:04.420
in which access is often
offered at the expense

01:00:04.420 --> 01:00:07.620
of a person's existing identity.

01:00:07.620 --> 01:00:10.260
And maybe, Ashley, you
could speak to this

01:00:10.260 --> 01:00:13.000
from the standpoint of the--

01:00:13.000 --> 01:00:16.010
one of the most dominant ableist
narratives which, of course,

01:00:16.010 --> 01:00:19.820
is that, you know, all of this
technology development will

01:00:19.820 --> 01:00:22.470
create people who are, you know,

01:00:22.470 --> 01:00:29.460
able-bodied in the
sort of typical sense.

01:00:29.460 --> 01:00:30.760
&gt;&gt; Ashley Shew: So, yeah.

01:00:30.760 --> 01:00:34.070
So, when we think about who
can go to a space, right,

01:00:34.070 --> 01:00:38.100
not just who can go to space,
but a lot of this is intention

01:00:38.100 --> 01:00:40.290
with people's comfort, right?

01:00:40.290 --> 01:00:44.380
So to have bodies that could be
in comfortable spaces to be able

01:00:44.380 --> 01:00:48.550
to be comfortable as
someone who's neurodivergent,

01:00:48.550 --> 01:00:50.090
for instance.

01:00:50.090 --> 01:00:55.850
The spaces are going to be
different or planned ahead

01:00:55.850 --> 01:00:59.930
in ways that we can plan
ahead for space, right?

01:00:59.930 --> 01:01:03.710
So when I think about creating
environments that are good,

01:01:03.710 --> 01:01:07.090
right, I think a lot
about, you know, curve cuts

01:01:07.090 --> 01:01:08.510
and things like that, too.

01:01:08.510 --> 01:01:13.060
But, who has to be uncomfortable
to be in a space often,

01:01:13.060 --> 01:01:15.930
and habits of my mind and
I'm sure it's the same

01:01:15.930 --> 01:01:19.460
for my fellow panelists here
in thinking through their work,

01:01:19.460 --> 01:01:22.580
and what sort of compromises
must be made in terms

01:01:22.580 --> 01:01:24.660
of how you identify and
whether you identify

01:01:24.660 --> 01:01:27.130
and whether you care
to tell anyone.

01:01:27.130 --> 01:01:31.170
It's why I actually am
pretty excited about the idea

01:01:31.170 --> 01:01:34.160
about thinking about how we'll
be all the disabled in space.

01:01:34.160 --> 01:01:38.990
So, there's this idea-- it's
gone on a favor in some ways,

01:01:38.990 --> 01:01:41.070
but people used to talk about--

01:01:41.070 --> 01:01:44.780
non-disabled people call
them TABs, which stands

01:01:44.780 --> 01:01:46.460
for temporarily able-bodied.

01:01:46.460 --> 01:01:48.710
I think there are all sorts of
problems with that narrative

01:01:48.710 --> 01:01:50.490
because you shouldn't just
care about disabled people

01:01:50.490 --> 01:01:52.280
because you might be
one one day, right?

01:01:52.280 --> 01:01:54.580
That shouldn't be-- like I
shouldn't have to make it like,

01:01:54.580 --> 01:01:56.360
you'll be disabled too,
but I think because--

01:01:56.360 --> 01:01:58.940
and when we think about what
space we mean for our bodies,

01:01:58.940 --> 01:02:01.270
we're already like
organisms that grew

01:02:01.270 --> 01:02:04.140
up in a particular niche
in the world, right?

01:02:04.140 --> 01:02:06.000
So, we're animal type.

01:02:06.000 --> 01:02:10.330
And, already parts of the world
are not particularly accessible

01:02:10.330 --> 01:02:13.040
to us that are unfriendly to
our bodies in particular ways,

01:02:13.040 --> 01:02:16.270
and we're going to be taking
that to even greater extremes.

01:02:16.270 --> 01:02:20.250
So to think about what that
looks like for moving bodies

01:02:20.250 --> 01:02:24.050
in places and how our
bodies will be compromised

01:02:24.050 --> 01:02:26.760
in different ways, and what
that will mean for thinking

01:02:26.760 --> 01:02:30.700
about all bodies if we
expect, especially even

01:02:30.700 --> 01:02:33.710
if we don't leave this planet.

01:02:33.710 --> 01:02:38.420
Our success with global
warming, as Chanda pointed out,

01:02:38.420 --> 01:02:42.810
means that all of our bodies
are not going to be fit

01:02:42.810 --> 01:02:46.760
to the environmental niche that
is coming for us in the future.

01:02:46.760 --> 01:02:50.440
So to think about
disability as a category

01:02:50.440 --> 01:02:54.230
in which that's permeable
for a lot of people,

01:02:54.230 --> 01:02:56.460
a lot of people don't imagine
themselves becoming disabled

01:02:56.460 --> 01:02:57.850
in the future, they should.

01:02:57.850 --> 01:03:01.810
But that is not often
part of how anyone plans.

01:03:01.810 --> 01:03:04.820
I mean, that's why we have sort
of a housing crisis for elderly

01:03:04.820 --> 01:03:08.540
and disabled folks and why--

01:03:08.540 --> 01:03:11.310
I don't understand why
we keep building houses

01:03:11.310 --> 01:03:12.610
with stairs, right?

01:03:12.610 --> 01:03:16.510
There are just some basic things
about how we failed a plan,

01:03:16.510 --> 01:03:23.270
not just for space, but
for age and for our--

01:03:23.270 --> 01:03:25.980
what we've done to the planet,

01:03:25.980 --> 01:03:27.670
all of those things
in it together.

01:03:27.670 --> 01:03:28.970
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: Yeah.

01:03:28.970 --> 01:03:30.270
&gt;&gt; Chanda Prescod-Weinstein:
I just kind of want

01:03:30.270 --> 01:03:31.930
to add something to this,
and I know I keep coming back

01:03:31.930 --> 01:03:36.040
to Mauna Kea, but I think for
me, it was a seminal point

01:03:36.040 --> 01:03:40.200
of having to evaluate what am I
still doing here and am I going

01:03:40.200 --> 01:03:42.550
to stay in the scientific
community.

01:03:42.550 --> 01:03:46.390
And coming back to the question
of modernity and who gets

01:03:46.390 --> 01:03:50.380
to be modern, one of
the protector science

01:03:50.380 --> 01:03:53.980
that was my favorite was
pono science is possible.

01:03:53.980 --> 01:03:58.210
And I'm not going to pretend
to explain what pono means

01:03:58.210 --> 01:04:01.290
to people, but essentially the
idea was that there is a way

01:04:01.290 --> 01:04:03.660
of doing science that
is ethical and keeping

01:04:03.660 --> 01:04:05.830
with Kanaka Maoli values.

01:04:05.830 --> 01:04:09.830
And, I think the second thing
that really stood out to me,

01:04:09.830 --> 01:04:12.100
there was a beautiful
essay by Bryan Kuwada,

01:04:12.100 --> 01:04:14.650
who's one of the
people I got to know

01:04:14.650 --> 01:04:16.620
and someone I would
consider a friend, called,

01:04:16.620 --> 01:04:19.150
"We Come from the
Future, Join Us",

01:04:19.150 --> 01:04:20.680
that he wrote in
response to this.

01:04:20.680 --> 01:04:23.960
And I would encourage everyone
to go and read his words.

01:04:23.960 --> 01:04:26.260
But in fact, you know, I meet--

01:04:26.260 --> 01:04:28.830
I drew the parallel between
general relativity and thinking

01:04:28.830 --> 01:04:31.680
about the land as a family
member for very specific reasons

01:04:31.680 --> 01:04:36.290
because GR is considered
advanced techno knowledge.

01:04:36.290 --> 01:04:39.270
And I think that having to
sit with this idea of land

01:04:39.270 --> 01:04:42.450
as family is equally, if not,

01:04:42.450 --> 01:04:45.510
more difficult material
to think through.

01:04:45.510 --> 01:04:49.020
And so maybe the difficulty
that scientists had

01:04:49.020 --> 01:04:53.080
with understanding that Kanaka
Maoli position was because it is

01:04:53.080 --> 01:04:56.000
so advanced if we
were to use that word.

01:04:56.000 --> 01:04:58.640
And I think that that's a really
important thing to think about,

01:04:58.640 --> 01:05:01.360
which is, could our
science even be better?

01:05:01.360 --> 01:05:03.510
I don't think that that
should be the reason to think

01:05:03.510 --> 01:05:06.330
about respect, but I think
that that's certainly a feature

01:05:06.330 --> 01:05:10.280
in the same way that Ashley
is thinking about, I think.

01:05:10.280 --> 01:05:12.250
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: Yeah.

01:05:12.250 --> 01:05:14.070
Sure.

01:05:14.070 --> 01:05:16.420
&gt;&gt; Brian Nord: So, my brief
thought is that, you know,

01:05:16.420 --> 01:05:21.380
centering the ableist
perspective and centering--

01:05:21.380 --> 01:05:28.120
or not even thinking about
indigenous people's perspectives

01:05:28.120 --> 01:05:30.820
in how they live their
lives, not thinking

01:05:30.820 --> 01:05:32.120
about that is almost

01:05:32.120 --> 01:05:34.360
as willfully not
centering innovation.

01:05:34.360 --> 01:05:40.760
We're saying we want to live
in an unimaginative way.

01:05:43.000 --> 01:05:44.310
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: Yeah.

01:05:44.310 --> 01:05:48.680
And to build off of imagination,
one of the things that came

01:05:48.680 --> 01:05:50.070
up in our discussion, of course,

01:05:50.070 --> 01:05:53.100
is how we imagine
the scientists.

01:05:53.100 --> 01:05:58.420
So, pop culture depictions
of scientists and how they do

01:05:58.420 --> 01:06:00.270
or don't describe what we do

01:06:00.270 --> 01:06:02.910
and how they also
influence the way we think

01:06:02.910 --> 01:06:04.880
of who is an explorer.

01:06:04.880 --> 01:06:10.520
So-- And I'll throw that out
to anyone who wants to take it.

01:06:10.520 --> 01:06:12.190
&gt;&gt; Ashley Shew: Disabled
explorers

01:06:12.190 --> 01:06:15.550
and scientists are always
depicted as evil, right?

01:06:15.550 --> 01:06:18.400
So as you were saying
that it was like, well,

01:06:18.400 --> 01:06:21.890
where does this intersection
happen when you have--

01:06:21.890 --> 01:06:24.880
when disabled people have
representation in some way?

01:06:24.880 --> 01:06:29.250
I mean, we have like Captain
Hook, you know, evil scientist,

01:06:29.250 --> 01:06:35.350
mad scientist, right, a
neurodivergent scientist

01:06:35.350 --> 01:06:37.390
that populate our
stories like even

01:06:37.390 --> 01:06:40.600
when we're imaging how disabled
people when it's possible

01:06:40.600 --> 01:06:42.370
to insert them in the
narratives we have

01:06:42.370 --> 01:06:44.590
with the narratives we're given.

01:06:44.590 --> 01:06:47.420
It's never on a positive light.

01:06:47.420 --> 01:06:51.150
It's kind of-- it
just prick me to think

01:06:51.150 --> 01:06:52.450
about that as you've said it.

01:06:52.450 --> 01:06:57.740
We don't imagine good scientists
who have the right stuff perhaps

01:06:57.740 --> 01:06:59.770
as disabled people ever.

01:06:59.770 --> 01:07:01.070
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: Yeah.

01:07:01.070 --> 01:07:03.070
Or we imagine them as
having a special skill.

01:07:03.070 --> 01:07:06.010
So I'm thinking about the
movie "Contact" where there's--

01:07:06.010 --> 01:07:07.310
&gt;&gt; Ashley Shew: Oh, yeah.

01:07:07.310 --> 01:07:08.610
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: -- you
