01:07:10.280 --> 01:07:13.020
the movie is not about him.

01:07:13.020 --> 01:07:14.320
You know, they just
sort of come in

01:07:14.320 --> 01:07:18.790
and like serve a special
place and then are jettisoned

01:07:18.790 --> 01:07:20.200
for the rest of the movie.

01:07:20.200 --> 01:07:21.500
&gt;&gt; Ashley Shew: Yeah.

01:07:21.500 --> 01:07:22.800
Yeah, the sidekick.

01:07:22.800 --> 01:07:24.100
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: Yeah.

01:07:24.100 --> 01:07:25.400
&gt;&gt; Chanda Prescod-Weinstein:
I guess--

01:07:25.400 --> 01:07:29.470
I think about the film
"Hidden Figures" and I'm going

01:07:29.470 --> 01:07:32.900
to assume everyone in the room
knows what that film is about.

01:07:32.900 --> 01:07:35.670
And, maybe ironically,
something that really bugged me

01:07:35.670 --> 01:07:38.950
about the movie was-- or
I shouldn't say bugged me,

01:07:38.950 --> 01:07:40.250
but something I struggled

01:07:40.250 --> 01:07:44.300
with during the movie
was skin color because--

01:07:44.300 --> 01:07:45.600
well, a couple of things.

01:07:45.600 --> 01:07:48.090
So, first of all, the actual
hidden figures were paid

01:07:48.090 --> 01:07:50.810
so well, that with two
years of their salary,

01:07:50.810 --> 01:07:52.280
they could buy a house.

01:07:52.280 --> 01:07:55.340
And so actually sort of the
socioeconomic representation

01:07:55.340 --> 01:07:56.850
in the film is not accurate,

01:07:56.850 --> 01:07:59.720
and we all know Hollywood
likes to dramatize things.

01:07:59.720 --> 01:08:02.670
But I thought a lot about,
you know, what is the message

01:08:02.670 --> 01:08:05.060
that gets sent about who the
hidden figures are, if that's--

01:08:05.060 --> 01:08:07.720
if you only watch the movie
and you don't read the book.

01:08:07.720 --> 01:08:10.300
The other thing is, is that
they were light-skinned.

01:08:10.300 --> 01:08:13.270
And I want to highlight that
because as everyone can tell,

01:08:13.270 --> 01:08:15.500
Brian and I are fairly
light-skinned people.

01:08:15.500 --> 01:08:23.350
And we are two of really
three maybe black cosmologists

01:08:23.350 --> 01:08:27.610
in the United States
who hold PhDs right now.

01:08:27.610 --> 01:08:30.620
And so I think the other thing
that we have to think carefully

01:08:30.620 --> 01:08:34.310
about is even within our
narratives of diversity

01:08:34.310 --> 01:08:37.460
and inclusion that certain
people are more likely

01:08:37.460 --> 01:08:38.820
to get through the door.

01:08:38.820 --> 01:08:42.480
And I really struggled
with that dimension

01:08:42.480 --> 01:08:45.180
of hidden figures being
missing, the discourse

01:08:45.180 --> 01:08:47.150
that it was really only
light-skinned women

01:08:47.150 --> 01:08:49.360
of a certain socioeconomic class

01:08:49.360 --> 01:08:51.300
who were actually getting
those opportunities

01:08:51.300 --> 01:08:54.170
and it wasn't working
class darker-skinned women

01:08:54.170 --> 01:08:56.370
who were getting
those opportunities.

01:08:56.370 --> 01:09:00.310
And I think that that needs to
be part of the conversation,

01:09:00.310 --> 01:09:04.040
even in the culture today,
that certainly I continue

01:09:04.040 --> 01:09:07.360
to experience racism, and
I'm occasionally very shocked

01:09:07.360 --> 01:09:10.250
by this because I'm like
I'm so pale, are you really

01:09:10.250 --> 01:09:12.590
like that invested in it.

01:09:12.590 --> 01:09:14.760
And not that I think it
shouldn't happen to me,

01:09:14.760 --> 01:09:17.310
I'm just even because
people don't always know

01:09:17.310 --> 01:09:19.350
that I'm black, I
continue to be impressed

01:09:19.350 --> 01:09:21.210
that like it finds me anyway

01:09:21.210 --> 01:09:25.980
in our one-drop deeply
committed anti-black culture.

01:09:25.980 --> 01:09:29.860
But I think that that is
really a feature that we have

01:09:29.860 --> 01:09:32.920
to think carefully
about how skin colorism.

01:09:32.920 --> 01:09:35.670
And I think, again, this
is written on the body,

01:09:35.670 --> 01:09:38.750
is maybe another way of putting
it, that all of these ways

01:09:38.750 --> 01:09:41.460
of how our bodies are perceived
and which ones are perceived

01:09:41.460 --> 01:09:45.270
as being closer to the
ideal, even if nonideal,

01:09:45.270 --> 01:09:47.840
become part of the conversation.

01:09:47.840 --> 01:09:49.140
&gt;&gt; Ashley Shew: No,
and this picks

01:09:49.140 --> 01:09:50.440
up on how we design things.

01:09:50.440 --> 01:09:52.750
So if we want inclusion
and diversity,

01:09:52.750 --> 01:09:55.250
sort of design team
is we need to have.

01:09:55.250 --> 01:09:57.520
There are so many good
examples of failures,

01:09:57.520 --> 01:09:59.530
of planning like the soap
dispensers, you know,

01:09:59.530 --> 01:10:02.120
automatic soap dispensers
and sinks

01:10:02.120 --> 01:10:04.090
that can't see black
people, right?

01:10:04.090 --> 01:10:07.190
Because who is on that
design team testing that out?

01:10:07.190 --> 01:10:09.640
Yeah. And there's the-- if you--

01:10:09.640 --> 01:10:12.350
on YouTube, it's
a wonderful video,

01:10:12.350 --> 01:10:14.360
it's called, the HP is racist.

01:10:14.360 --> 01:10:18.890
And it has two best buy
employees who discovered

01:10:18.890 --> 01:10:22.890
that the HP cameras could not--
they were doing facial detection

01:10:22.890 --> 01:10:27.240
and following faces, but
only for people of skin

01:10:27.240 --> 01:10:31.060
of a certain lightness, and
it's also a very funny video.

01:10:31.060 --> 01:10:34.070
But just in how we're
programming things

01:10:34.070 --> 01:10:36.340
and how we're attending the
things we're already building

01:10:36.340 --> 01:10:39.640
with the people we already
have, what we're failing

01:10:39.640 --> 01:10:44.480
in engineering teams on a
regular basis in those ways.

01:10:44.480 --> 01:10:46.390
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: And
this goes back to your point

01:10:46.390 --> 01:10:51.720
at the beginning, Brian,
about the increasing use of AI

01:10:51.720 --> 01:10:56.820
and machine learning in really
every aspect of our daily lives.

01:10:56.820 --> 01:10:59.940
If you're not familiar
with machine learning,

01:10:59.940 --> 01:11:04.420
this a major part of how
your choices are given to you

01:11:04.420 --> 01:11:07.430
in terms of like its
probably greatest use,

01:11:07.430 --> 01:11:10.320
beside from the military,
is marketing.

01:11:10.320 --> 01:11:13.040
But when we think about, you
know, the design of algorithms,

01:11:13.040 --> 01:11:17.270
for example, a lot of the,
you know, skin detection

01:11:17.270 --> 01:11:20.780
or facial recognition, a
lot of that is used already

01:11:20.780 --> 01:11:25.520
in policing often without
the consent of the community

01:11:25.520 --> 01:11:27.680
that it's deployed on.

01:11:27.680 --> 01:11:32.160
And, you know, all of the facial
recognition algorithms perform

01:11:32.160 --> 01:11:35.980
more poorly on people who
are darker skinned and women.

01:11:35.980 --> 01:11:38.440
And so, again, women
who are black

01:11:38.440 --> 01:11:41.460
and darker skin fear the worst

01:11:41.460 --> 01:11:44.180
in the technology
that we design.

01:11:44.180 --> 01:11:48.320
And a lot of those are
inseparable from science

01:11:48.320 --> 01:11:51.350
as an enterprise because
those are the same algorithms

01:11:51.350 --> 01:11:55.420
in many cases that we use on
pretty pictures of galaxies.

01:11:55.420 --> 01:11:59.180
Yeah. Did you have
another comment?

01:11:59.180 --> 01:12:00.480
&gt;&gt; Chanda Prescod-Weinstein:
Yeah.

01:12:00.480 --> 01:12:05.520
I think-- I just want to make
sure that I-- I think the--

01:12:05.520 --> 01:12:10.220
there's a debate
within, I guess,

01:12:10.220 --> 01:12:14.870
I'll vaguely term it ethnic
studies about where we are

01:12:14.870 --> 01:12:18.340
in terms of how racial
identification works in society.

01:12:18.340 --> 01:12:20.690
So there are some
people who think we are

01:12:20.690 --> 01:12:23.110
in a black, not black society.

01:12:23.110 --> 01:12:26.000
And so you're either black or
you're not black and that's kind

01:12:26.000 --> 01:12:28.140
of where the default
lines exist.

01:12:28.140 --> 01:12:29.570
And then there are other people

01:12:29.570 --> 01:12:32.710
who think it really falls
along skin color lines.

01:12:32.710 --> 01:12:36.400
And so, if you are
of African heritage

01:12:36.400 --> 01:12:41.750
but if you're lady enough, then
it's no longer kind of a factor.

01:12:41.750 --> 01:12:47.640
And I think of as-- of
racist as social technology

01:12:47.640 --> 01:12:51.750
that was developed, and
I've written about this,

01:12:51.750 --> 01:12:54.840
so I wrote an essay
called "Physics of Melanin"

01:12:54.840 --> 01:12:56.920
where I talk about how
we could have used earwax

01:12:56.920 --> 01:12:59.000
to divide people because
some people have hard earwax

01:12:59.000 --> 01:13:01.310
and some people have
soft earwax.

01:13:01.310 --> 01:13:05.750
And instead-- And it was
a technology that was kind

01:13:05.750 --> 01:13:07.380
of developed in hindsight,
well, oh now,

01:13:07.380 --> 01:13:09.310
we have all these
dark-skinned slaves,

01:13:09.310 --> 01:13:12.110
so how do we separate them and
make sure the Irish don't think

01:13:12.110 --> 01:13:14.790
that they're on the
same side with them?

01:13:14.790 --> 01:13:17.740
And also-- And there's a
complicated conversation

01:13:17.740 --> 01:13:20.590
about how indigenous people
were sort of fitted into that.

01:13:20.590 --> 01:13:23.980
But, again, I think that when
we talk about technology,

01:13:23.980 --> 01:13:27.490
I guess we have to think
about these concepts

01:13:27.490 --> 01:13:31.000
as social technologies
because race was really made

01:13:31.000 --> 01:13:35.490
into a scientific concept even
though it is a social concept.

01:13:35.490 --> 01:13:38.970
And, again, that's something
that follows us into space.

01:13:38.970 --> 01:13:43.010
But coming back to Brian's
question about, you know,

01:13:43.010 --> 01:13:45.680
what if we use space
as kind of a laboratory

01:13:45.680 --> 01:13:48.090
for experimenting
on these things.

01:13:48.090 --> 01:13:50.670
I think we do in the
sense that, you know,

01:13:50.670 --> 01:13:53.140
I scour the new astronaut class

01:13:53.140 --> 01:13:55.410
for where-- how dark
is everyone.

01:13:55.410 --> 01:13:57.720
That's always my first
question when I look at--

01:13:57.720 --> 01:14:00.270
when scientists are
selected, myself included.

01:14:00.270 --> 01:14:02.220
If I'm the only black
person in the room,

01:14:02.220 --> 01:14:04.230
I knew I'm the only
black person in the room

01:14:04.230 --> 01:14:05.530
and I am light-skinned.

01:14:05.530 --> 01:14:07.530
That's part of the conversation.

01:14:07.530 --> 01:14:09.850
And so that would be
part of our conversation

01:14:09.850 --> 01:14:12.300
of who do we even send
up in that laboratory,

01:14:12.300 --> 01:14:14.940
and I'm sure Black Twitter
would have a lot to say about,

01:14:14.940 --> 01:14:18.670
are those people dark enough,
are there enough women, oh,

01:14:18.670 --> 01:14:20.640
that person is not cess.

01:14:20.640 --> 01:14:24.710
And I love that Black Twitter
has those conversations most

01:14:24.710 --> 01:14:26.010
of the time.

01:14:26.010 --> 01:14:29.260
But I think that in some sense,

01:14:29.260 --> 01:14:31.560
we can escape our social
technologies and we need

01:14:31.560 --> 01:14:34.580
to acknowledge that our
social technologies are fused

01:14:34.580 --> 01:14:39.190
with our physical technologies,
including who bears the brunt

01:14:39.190 --> 01:14:41.600
of our global warming that
it is the global south

01:14:41.600 --> 01:14:45.020
that felt it first and only
now are we really starting

01:14:45.020 --> 01:14:46.320
to feel it further up north.

01:14:46.320 --> 01:14:48.150
And so, I like to remind people

01:14:48.150 --> 01:14:50.520
that hurricanes have been
killing people in the Caribbean

01:14:50.520 --> 01:14:52.000
for a long, long time,

01:14:52.000 --> 01:14:54.490
and typhoons have been killing
people in Southeast Asia

01:14:54.490 --> 01:14:57.040
and South Asia for
a long, long time.

01:14:57.040 --> 01:14:58.990
But it's only now that
people are like, oh,

01:14:58.990 --> 01:15:00.460
maybe we should really
do something

01:15:00.460 --> 01:15:01.790
about that, I mean, some people.

01:15:01.790 --> 01:15:05.790
So I think that we need
to not think of technology

01:15:05.790 --> 01:15:11.180
as a physical thing,
and I think race is kind

01:15:11.180 --> 01:15:15.110
of a central point for that.

01:15:15.110 --> 01:15:17.230
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: And
since I promised we would return

01:15:17.230 --> 01:15:20.960
to space poop, I will
use that to branch off

01:15:20.960 --> 01:15:27.970
into the physicality of us all
as human beings and the fact

01:15:27.970 --> 01:15:30.230
that we have these social
contracts that are on top

01:15:30.230 --> 01:15:32.030
of actual human bodies.

01:15:32.030 --> 01:15:34.340
And I think my-- from
our pre-event call,

01:15:34.340 --> 01:15:36.720
my favorite quote was Chanda
saying there's no freedom

01:15:36.720 --> 01:15:38.020
in poop.

01:15:38.020 --> 01:15:42.390
And that we have this
like wonderful noble image

01:15:42.390 --> 01:15:46.330
of the astronaut
out there exploring,

01:15:46.330 --> 01:15:49.770
being the representative,
and also having to deal

01:15:49.770 --> 01:15:51.070
with all of these things.

01:15:51.070 --> 01:15:52.490
I see you're already
holding the mic, Ashley.

01:15:52.490 --> 01:15:56.230
&gt;&gt; Ashley Shew: You're
explaining it well, yes,

01:15:56.230 --> 01:15:58.570
I mean managing bodies, right?

01:15:58.570 --> 01:16:01.340
I mean, what we've learned from
the history of space and pooping

01:16:01.340 --> 01:16:03.600
in space and peeing in space,

01:16:03.600 --> 01:16:07.530
like it's been messy
and awkward.

01:16:07.530 --> 01:16:11.770
The image of the astronaut as
being like a buff white dude

01:16:11.770 --> 01:16:16.080
who is somehow a cut above
the rest, who have made it

01:16:16.080 --> 01:16:21.590
on the space program, but in the
end, he's either strapping a bag

01:16:21.590 --> 01:16:25.910
to his anus or wearing a diaper
and like it just gets as patched

01:16:25.910 --> 01:16:28.820
like realizing that we're
like meat bags all the time

01:16:28.820 --> 01:16:34.670
and managing these meat bags,
is a real, real challenge.

01:16:34.670 --> 01:16:35.970
Yeah.

01:16:35.970 --> 01:16:37.270
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: Yeah.

01:16:37.270 --> 01:16:38.570
Anyone else?

01:16:38.570 --> 01:16:39.870
&gt;&gt; Chanda Prescod-Weinstein:

01:16:39.870 --> 01:16:43.580
I think I should
clarify my comment.

01:16:43.580 --> 01:16:46.230
[Laughter] I'm going to-- Oh,
I'll just say that I think the--

01:16:46.230 --> 01:16:48.410
one of the things we
talked about is how it came

01:16:48.410 --> 01:16:51.350
into the popular consciousness
that astronauts had

01:16:51.350 --> 01:16:55.550
to wear diapers or bags, which
was that there was a conflict

01:16:55.550 --> 01:16:58.240
between astronauts
who were a couple

01:16:58.240 --> 01:17:00.390
and I forget exactly what--

01:17:00.390 --> 01:17:01.690
&gt;&gt; Ashley Shew: Texas de Flores.

01:17:01.690 --> 01:17:03.190
&gt;&gt; Chanda Prescod-Weinstein:
Texas de Flores, the woman put

01:17:03.190 --> 01:17:06.640
on a diaper and drove
continuously.

01:17:06.640 --> 01:17:08.610
And she wore a diaper so
that she wouldn't have

01:17:08.610 --> 01:17:09.910
to get out of the car.

01:17:09.910 --> 01:17:11.220
And I think I must
have been a first

01:17:11.220 --> 01:17:14.520
or second year graduate student
in astronomy and I had no idea

01:17:14.520 --> 01:17:19.710
that this was how
astronauts dealt with poop.

01:17:19.710 --> 01:17:22.150
But that, you know, even
when you go into space,

01:17:22.150 --> 01:17:25.700
you cannot escape your poop.

01:17:25.700 --> 01:17:27.450
&gt;&gt; Ashley Shew: Sometimes
you literally can't.

01:17:27.450 --> 01:17:30.950
I mean, the backup of the one
toilet that sent like bits

01:17:30.950 --> 01:17:37.770
of fecal matter around the cabin
before they landed, like it's--

01:17:37.770 --> 01:17:39.740
like we don't think
about our bodies

01:17:39.740 --> 01:17:41.640
as engineering challenges
generally every day,

01:17:41.640 --> 01:17:43.190
especially if we're able-bodied.

01:17:43.190 --> 01:17:44.490
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: Yeah.

01:17:44.490 --> 01:17:45.790
&gt;&gt; Ashley Shew: Right?

01:17:45.790 --> 01:17:48.610
But these-- The mechanics
of these things that a lot

01:17:48.610 --> 01:17:50.890
of disabled people have to
think about every day, right,

01:17:50.890 --> 01:17:53.820
thinking about the
mechanics of using a restroom

01:17:53.820 --> 01:17:55.880
under particular
conditions, for instance,

01:17:55.880 --> 01:17:59.750
or even how close a restroom is.

01:18:00.870 --> 01:18:04.280
You have to, if we're going
to make these huge plans,

01:18:04.280 --> 01:18:06.430
like most people just
take toilet thing

01:18:06.430 --> 01:18:09.680
as a given, and they shouldn't.

01:18:09.680 --> 01:18:13.280
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: You
know, I think interestingly,

01:18:13.280 --> 01:18:16.730
even though we-- you know, aside
from this news story bringing it

01:18:16.730 --> 01:18:20.900
into the public consciousness,
we often hide that aspect

01:18:20.900 --> 01:18:23.350
of the realities
of going to space.

01:18:23.350 --> 01:18:25.230
But when I worked with
students, for example,

01:18:25.230 --> 01:18:28.640
so we have a Gemini capsule
at the other planetarium

01:18:28.640 --> 01:18:32.090
and right next to it in the
display case is the poop bag.

01:18:32.090 --> 01:18:37.150
And it is the thing
that students are like,

01:18:37.150 --> 01:18:40.430
I had a couple of interns
who were working with me

01:18:40.430 --> 01:18:43.630
to write poetry during
part of their time to go

01:18:43.630 --> 01:18:46.440
around through the
museum and speak

01:18:46.440 --> 01:18:48.560
to different artifacts
in the museum.

01:18:48.560 --> 01:18:50.730
And one of them wrote an ode

01:18:50.730 --> 01:18:53.760
to the poop bag and
I was like, yeah.

01:18:53.760 --> 01:18:58.990
So, we're coming to the
end of our time here.

01:18:58.990 --> 01:19:00.680
We're going to have
some time for Q&amp;A.

01:19:00.680 --> 01:19:04.550
But maybe if I could ask
all of the panelists,

01:19:04.550 --> 01:19:06.890
I'd love to return
to this concept

01:19:06.890 --> 01:19:09.820
of not just the right
stuff but the right time

01:19:09.820 --> 01:19:13.310
since we have people who
think about time in a variety

01:19:13.310 --> 01:19:14.610
of different ways here.

01:19:14.610 --> 01:19:17.360
And maybe if you can each
offer a closing remark

01:19:17.360 --> 01:19:21.020
if it moves you.

01:19:21.020 --> 01:19:24.870
Whoever wants to go first.

01:19:24.870 --> 01:19:28.980
&gt;&gt; Brian Nord: So, I'm not
sure I have a comment on time,

01:19:28.980 --> 01:19:33.820
but I think the thing that is
clarified for me at least sort

01:19:33.820 --> 01:19:37.680
of verbally in my head during
our discussions is, as you said,

01:19:37.680 --> 01:19:40.710
social technology, and if I can
turn that around a little bit

01:19:40.710 --> 01:19:42.460
and say that all
technology is social.

01:19:42.460 --> 01:19:46.700
And when we say the right
stuff, there's this implication

01:19:46.700 --> 01:19:50.180
that there's an objectivity
to these technologies

01:19:50.180 --> 01:19:52.490
or objectivity to the
scientific perspective.

01:19:52.490 --> 01:19:55.300
And there's an objectivity to
what a scientist or someone

01:19:55.300 --> 01:19:57.440
who goes into space
looks like and that--

01:19:57.440 --> 01:20:01.190
but that objectivity is false
and that objectivity is just set

01:20:01.190 --> 01:20:03.600
up by the people who have
accumulated enough power

01:20:03.600 --> 01:20:06.920
to define that as the
objective perspective.

01:20:06.920 --> 01:20:10.960
And maybe that means that--
and maybe since, you know,

01:20:10.960 --> 01:20:14.790
living with that idea for so
long myself that our destiny is

01:20:14.790 --> 01:20:17.420
to be in space, maybe
that objective perspective

01:20:17.420 --> 01:20:20.990
that I thought I had is that
the time is always now to go.

01:20:20.990 --> 01:20:24.220
And we need-- and maybe that
default, maybe that idea

01:20:24.220 --> 01:20:27.480
of objectivity as we
always progress outward

01:20:27.480 --> 01:20:33.220
and we always progress to expand
may be turning that around

01:20:33.220 --> 01:20:37.340
and saying-- and just
continually asking maybe

01:20:37.340 --> 01:20:38.750
Chanda's question of why now.

01:20:38.750 --> 01:20:40.300
Maybe that's where
we need to just--

01:20:40.300 --> 01:20:42.610
we need to keep going
instead of always saying,

01:20:42.610 --> 01:20:45.970
yes now, yes next, yes next.

01:20:45.970 --> 01:20:47.740
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: And I'd
love to hear from you, Brenda,

01:20:47.740 --> 01:20:51.340
also from the standpoint of
somebody being deeply embedded

01:20:51.340 --> 01:20:53.800
in the history and not just
solely the young history

01:20:53.800 --> 01:20:56.100
of space exploration.

01:20:57.650 --> 01:21:00.020
&gt;&gt; Brenda J. Child: I'm afraid
