01:21:00.020 --> 01:21:05.010
I keep thinking about jokes
and since we were talking

01:21:05.010 --> 01:21:08.030
about poop, we can
talk about jokes, too.

01:21:08.030 --> 01:21:11.450
So, I think about
different variations

01:21:11.450 --> 01:21:16.260
on Native American jokes about--

01:21:16.260 --> 01:21:19.940
that I'm reminding often
with the kind of debate

01:21:19.940 --> 01:21:22.050
on immigration to
the United States

01:21:22.050 --> 01:21:25.590
and native people always having
to remind folks that, you know,

01:21:25.590 --> 01:21:28.460
we're the ones from here
and you folks are all

01:21:28.460 --> 01:21:31.400
from some place else and you're
the settlers, and we always joke

01:21:31.400 --> 01:21:32.860
about what if the
settlers leave.

01:21:32.860 --> 01:21:37.620
So I'm thinking about kind
of a future where a fantasy

01:21:37.620 --> 01:21:40.610
for native people where, what
if the settlers leave and go

01:21:40.610 --> 01:21:42.260
to other planets, in Mars,

01:21:42.260 --> 01:21:45.500
and we get to stay here
with our ancestors?

01:21:47.150 --> 01:21:49.850
&gt;&gt; Ashley Shew: So the question
of when is the right time,

01:21:49.850 --> 01:21:52.360
you know, I don't--
just as I don't think

01:21:52.360 --> 01:21:56.110
that there is a good answer to
who has the right stuff, right,

01:21:56.110 --> 01:22:00.380
I don't think the answer
should be linear or clear.

01:22:00.380 --> 01:22:02.260
I don't think we're ever
going to have an answer

01:22:02.260 --> 01:22:04.220
to what the right time might be.

01:22:04.220 --> 01:22:07.760
A mass of an asteroid is coming
that'll really put a time clock

01:22:07.760 --> 01:22:09.600
on things, right?

01:22:09.600 --> 01:22:12.870
But, you know, I think it's good

01:22:12.870 --> 01:22:17.070
to consider multiple
perspectives as we think

01:22:17.070 --> 01:22:21.930
about who belongs in space and
what the timeline is going to be

01:22:21.930 --> 01:22:25.920
for what that looks like and
who the stakeholders are.

01:22:25.920 --> 01:22:31.010
And, I mean, these things are--
there will be no right time.

01:22:31.010 --> 01:22:36.090
There is no right stuff
but there's stuff and time.

01:22:36.090 --> 01:22:37.780
I'll turn it over
to a physicist now.

01:22:37.780 --> 01:22:39.080
&gt;&gt; Chanda Prescod-Weinstein:

01:22:39.080 --> 01:22:41.720
That's actually a
really good lead

01:22:41.720 --> 01:22:43.020
in to what I was going to say.

01:22:43.020 --> 01:22:45.320
So thank you for the setup.

01:22:46.340 --> 01:22:49.320
So, the key insight
of Einstein's theory

01:22:49.320 --> 01:22:52.260
of general relativity,
I think, is that there--

01:22:52.260 --> 01:22:55.140
and really the key insight
of special relativity is

01:22:55.140 --> 01:22:58.830
that there is no such thing
as an objective observer.

01:22:58.830 --> 01:23:03.080
And I went through a
PhD, two qualifying exams

01:23:03.080 --> 01:23:04.380
that cover this topic.

01:23:04.380 --> 01:23:08.820
I took GR, I taught GR
before I really realized

01:23:08.820 --> 01:23:10.120
that this was the key insight.

01:23:10.120 --> 01:23:15.310
And, I highlight this
because it came out in-- I--

01:23:15.310 --> 01:23:17.800
my mom is a radio host
on the Pacific Network

01:23:17.800 --> 01:23:20.640
and she sent me a bunch of
archival material, and in there,

01:23:20.640 --> 01:23:23.420
buried, was a session from
the American Association

01:23:23.420 --> 01:23:26.390
for the Advancement of
Science 1983 meeting

01:23:26.390 --> 01:23:30.000
where the late Joseph
Johnson, a black physicist

01:23:30.000 --> 01:23:34.560
from Florida A&amp;M University, who
had actually played a major role

01:23:34.560 --> 01:23:40.480
in my life much later, talked
about this insight and realizing

01:23:40.480 --> 01:23:44.140
that it took a black physicist
who doesn't work on relativity

01:23:44.140 --> 01:23:48.410
to reframe the area that I
was a specialist in for me.

01:23:48.410 --> 01:23:50.720
And this was really--
it wasn't--

01:23:50.720 --> 01:23:52.680
I heard the recording for
the first time last year

01:23:52.680 --> 01:23:56.040
and actually just wept through
it because I was so stunned

01:23:56.040 --> 01:24:00.860
to hear this recording of a
man that I'd admired so much.

01:24:00.860 --> 01:24:04.880
And so, in connection to
this question of, you know,

01:24:04.880 --> 01:24:08.680
what is the right time and
what is the right space

01:24:08.680 --> 01:24:13.850
and where bodies inhabit space
and are part of space time,

01:24:13.850 --> 01:24:18.490
I think about the Palikir
people who live in a region

01:24:18.490 --> 01:24:21.010
that we would, I guess, roughly
call the Peruvian Amazon.

01:24:21.010 --> 01:24:25.760
And they have a completely
different astronomical system

01:24:25.760 --> 01:24:31.870
than we do in, I guess, what you
call institutional astronomy.

01:24:31.870 --> 01:24:35.160
And, what's interesting is
because-- maybe because--

01:24:35.160 --> 01:24:39.510
I shouldn't speak on this as
a big-time expert or anything,

01:24:39.510 --> 01:24:41.950
there are a lot of snakes in
the Amazon, there are a lot

01:24:41.950 --> 01:24:43.630
of big snakes in the Amazon.

01:24:43.630 --> 01:24:48.400
And this way of thinking of the
Palikir people reflects this.

01:24:48.400 --> 01:24:51.310
And so, in fact, instead of
using a Cartesian geometry,

01:24:51.310 --> 01:24:54.370
so a Cartesian, everything
is boxy and squary,

01:24:54.370 --> 01:24:57.880
they use what we would call a
curvilinear system that is built

01:24:57.880 --> 01:25:05.710
around snakes in the sky
and their spiritual system.

01:25:05.710 --> 01:25:07.470
And what's interesting
about this is

01:25:07.470 --> 01:25:09.930
that they can actually account
for the movement of the stars

01:25:09.930 --> 01:25:12.170
across the night sky
through the seasons better

01:25:12.170 --> 01:25:14.820
than we can using their
geometrical system

01:25:14.820 --> 01:25:18.670
because their geometrical system
allows for things to be curved.

01:25:18.670 --> 01:25:20.900
And they also have five seasons.

01:25:20.900 --> 01:25:22.200
They don't have four.

01:25:22.200 --> 01:25:25.220
And they can predict from
looking at the sky to the day

01:25:25.220 --> 01:25:26.790
when the rains are
going to change

01:25:26.790 --> 01:25:28.380
into a different rain season.

01:25:28.380 --> 01:25:32.180
So coming back to our
question of who is modern,

01:25:32.180 --> 01:25:38.030
we can't do weather prediction
for crop, but they can.

01:25:38.030 --> 01:25:41.470
And so when I think about time,

01:25:41.470 --> 01:25:42.980
we have a particular
relationship

01:25:42.980 --> 01:25:45.590
to the Thirty Meter Telescope
timeline of when we need

01:25:45.590 --> 01:25:48.070
to see galaxies now because
careers need to evolve

01:25:48.070 --> 01:25:50.240
in a certain way in
the astronomy community

01:25:50.240 --> 01:25:53.230
because there's a new
generation coming up.

01:25:53.230 --> 01:25:57.430
But I'm guessing that people
who are feeling the impact

01:25:57.430 --> 01:26:00.760
of global warming on their
systems, their technologies

01:26:00.760 --> 01:26:04.290
of knowing the weather,
for example, are thinking

01:26:04.290 --> 01:26:08.640
that now is the time to figure
out how to deal with the fact

01:26:08.640 --> 01:26:10.830
that these established
technologies are now being

01:26:10.830 --> 01:26:12.810
shifted by things that
people on the other side

01:26:12.810 --> 01:26:16.330
of the planet are doing
with their technologies.

01:26:16.330 --> 01:26:18.630
And so I can imagine that
people have very different

01:26:18.630 --> 01:26:21.490
relationships to what is
significant in this moment

01:26:21.490 --> 01:26:25.630
and in this time, and that
there's no objective observer,

01:26:25.630 --> 01:26:26.930
that's the thing we
have to sit with,

01:26:26.930 --> 01:26:30.900
is that astronomers are not
more objective about this.

01:26:30.900 --> 01:26:33.410
Astronomers who are for the
TMT are not more objective

01:26:33.410 --> 01:26:37.410
about this than astronomers who
were not for the TMT, et cetera.

01:26:37.410 --> 01:26:40.460
But I think that when we think
about now, we need to recognize

01:26:40.460 --> 01:26:42.590
that there are many
different nows

01:26:42.590 --> 01:26:46.070
and that our now may not be--

01:26:46.070 --> 01:26:49.780
comes with it in a position
of power perhaps or a position

01:26:49.780 --> 01:26:53.080
of disempowerment or a
sense of disempowerment,

01:26:53.080 --> 01:26:57.410
and that that is always tied
to our social technologies.

