01:29:32.300 --> 01:29:36.620
But just the underlying
assumption, right, that, first,

01:29:36.620 --> 01:29:43.120
you will part with your worldly
possessions in order to, what,

01:29:43.120 --> 01:29:45.820
live on Mars and be at
the behest of the company

01:29:45.820 --> 01:29:47.120
that brought you there?

01:29:47.120 --> 01:29:50.400
You know, I think we have
many examples of company towns

01:29:50.400 --> 01:29:53.090
and exploitation here
on Earth that inform us

01:29:53.090 --> 01:29:56.630
that that is not a good
premise to be starting with.

01:29:56.630 --> 01:30:03.140
Oh, we have a question there.

01:30:03.140 --> 01:30:06.520
&gt;&gt; So, I think that a
key question for any sort

01:30:06.520 --> 01:30:09.730
of exploration is always how
do we prepare for something

01:30:09.730 --> 01:30:11.520
that we've never seen.

01:30:11.520 --> 01:30:16.600
So my question is practically,
how do you think that we as kind

01:30:16.600 --> 01:30:21.140
of a society at large prepare
to build a future for something

01:30:21.140 --> 01:30:22.910
that we have never experienced?

01:30:22.910 --> 01:30:26.220
So thinking that, it's easy
to view astronauts as cowboys

01:30:26.220 --> 01:30:27.580
because we've seen cowboys.

01:30:27.580 --> 01:30:30.400
It's easy to say that
we're meant to go out

01:30:30.400 --> 01:30:34.460
and explore space because we've
experienced Manifest Destiny.

01:30:34.460 --> 01:30:37.990
So how do we build
visions for something

01:30:37.990 --> 01:30:40.840
that doesn't exist
in a practical way?

01:30:40.840 --> 01:30:44.480
&gt;&gt; Chanda Prescod-Weinstein: So,
oh gosh, this is being recorded.

01:30:44.480 --> 01:30:45.790
I'm going to be nice about it.

