So, I love the new Star
Trek series, I really do.

01:30:48.500 --> 01:30:53.690
But I want to say that
actually, I think this connects

01:30:53.690 --> 01:30:57.190
to the last question,
which is that they went

01:30:57.190 --> 01:30:59.880
out in the Star Trek
universe anyway.

01:30:59.880 --> 01:31:02.370
They go out with a very
clear ethical guide.

01:31:02.370 --> 01:31:05.060
I actually think that the Prime
Directive is a pretty important

01:31:05.060 --> 01:31:08.320
one, and actually of the
problem of the first episode,

01:31:08.320 --> 01:31:10.210
I'm not really giving
it away for anyone

01:31:10.210 --> 01:31:11.870
who hasn't watched
the series yet,

01:31:11.870 --> 01:31:14.550
but really the first 10
minutes is not really thinking

01:31:14.550 --> 01:31:18.540
through what happens if you
don't hold the Prime Directive

01:31:18.540 --> 01:31:22.230
around you as a barrier to
choices that might violate it.

01:31:22.230 --> 01:31:25.430
And it comes up a lot
because they do violate it

01:31:25.430 --> 01:31:26.730
like all the time.

01:31:26.730 --> 01:31:29.440
Usually it's not so catastrophic
as it is in this new series,

01:31:29.440 --> 01:31:31.690
but I think it really
does come down to,

01:31:31.690 --> 01:31:34.800
we have to prepare ourselves
ethically and morally

01:31:34.800 --> 01:31:37.180
and in terms of our
thinking about respect

01:31:37.180 --> 01:31:42.880
as Professor Child was saying
that you were never going

01:31:42.880 --> 01:31:44.950
to be able to prepare
for every scenario

01:31:44.950 --> 01:31:48.270
but you can prepare yourself
to be a decision maker

01:31:48.270 --> 01:31:51.700
in situations that
are unfamiliar to you.

01:31:53.070 --> 01:31:54.640
&gt;&gt; Brian Nord: Riffing off
that just a little bit,

01:31:54.640 --> 01:31:58.590
I think that some of the failure
of our educational system is

01:31:58.590 --> 01:32:02.600
that we prepare for tasks of the
past, because people are setting

01:32:02.600 --> 01:32:07.050
up the jobs of the future
for the people that they want

01:32:07.050 --> 01:32:08.350
to be in those positions.

01:32:08.350 --> 01:32:13.780
And so, I'm-- I think we need to
rethink how we approach training

01:32:13.780 --> 01:32:15.250
in technological tasks

01:32:15.250 --> 01:32:17.730
and I would include
social technology in that.

01:32:17.730 --> 01:32:22.380
And so, why don't we-- why
aren't we training folks

01:32:22.380 --> 01:32:27.160
for solving problems
that they care about

01:32:27.160 --> 01:32:29.950
and then learning all the pieces
to get to that as they need

01:32:29.950 --> 01:32:32.970
to instead of saying, hey,
just go through all these steps

01:32:32.970 --> 01:32:35.970
and then, oh, eventually, you'll
figure how to do research.

01:32:35.970 --> 01:32:38.390
So, in a sort of-- in a
specific context like that,

01:32:38.390 --> 01:32:43.240
I think we need to innovate how
we're educating each generation.

01:32:44.860 --> 01:32:46.360
&gt;&gt; Brenda J. Child: And I
guess I would just add to that

01:32:46.360 --> 01:32:48.820
to think about the history
