01:32:48.820 --> 01:32:52.110
around the world, and there's
been so much fantastic work

01:32:52.110 --> 01:32:55.370
in that area in the last
decade or so but a lot

01:32:55.370 --> 01:32:56.750
of it doesn't make our--

01:32:56.750 --> 01:32:59.150
it's way into public
school education.

01:32:59.150 --> 01:33:02.700
Just a few years ago,
there was a-- we did a--

01:33:02.700 --> 01:33:06.130
we're working on a grant, the
historians at the University

01:33:06.130 --> 01:33:10.970
of Minnesota was-- teachers in
the Minneapolis-Saint Paul area

01:33:10.970 --> 01:33:14.610
and when they were
writing the grant,

01:33:14.610 --> 01:33:17.920
they asked how much history
education the teachers had

01:33:17.920 --> 01:33:21.540
and they discovered that the
average high school social

01:33:21.540 --> 01:33:27.160
studies history teacher, it had
1.5 history courses in college.

01:33:30.170 --> 01:33:34.760
&gt;&gt; So, going back both to the
there's no objective observer

01:33:34.760 --> 01:33:37.080
and there's no good time.

01:33:37.080 --> 01:33:40.760
A lot of what we-- what a lot
of us think about when we think

01:33:40.760 --> 01:33:42.910
about colonizing Mars is,
oh, it's a blank slate

01:33:42.910 --> 01:33:44.990
because nobody is
living there right now.

01:33:44.990 --> 01:33:47.880
But it's not like we're
only going to there once.

01:33:47.880 --> 01:33:50.800
How do we envision a way

01:33:50.800 --> 01:33:54.350
of sustaining whatever
structures we put

01:33:54.350 --> 01:33:57.910
up when people are going to be
going back and forth presumably

01:33:57.910 --> 01:34:02.440
to Mars and to other places?

