01:34:17.680 --> 01:34:21.300
if the Vulcans had come to Earth
before humanity had a chance

01:34:21.300 --> 01:34:23.550
to develop?

01:34:23.550 --> 01:34:27.320
And, so there are lots
of scientific reasons

01:34:27.320 --> 01:34:28.830
that you might argue
that the probability

01:34:28.830 --> 01:34:33.150
of this being an actual
issue for Mars are small,

01:34:33.150 --> 01:34:36.540
but we also have often been
wrong like, for example,

01:34:36.540 --> 01:34:39.690
about the speed of light
about 140 years ago, right?

01:34:39.690 --> 01:34:43.640
So, we don't actually know
what could happen on Mars

01:34:43.640 --> 01:34:46.140
if we didn't mess with it.

01:34:46.140 --> 01:34:49.870
And, so that's actually
before you even get to the--

01:34:49.870 --> 01:34:52.950
I mean, maybe the gentrification
metaphor here is maybe an

01:34:52.950 --> 01:34:55.920
interesting one and that like,
you know, maybe there are things

01:34:55.920 --> 01:34:57.860
that were going to
happen in that community

01:34:57.860 --> 01:35:00.250
and this actually stands
out to me in Washington D.C.

01:35:00.250 --> 01:35:02.230
as someone who's been
part of her childhood

01:35:02.230 --> 01:35:06.590
and to come a perk, that
coming through the city now,

01:35:06.590 --> 01:35:08.950
it's like it's a
completely different city.

01:35:08.950 --> 01:35:11.590
And, one wonders, what are the
things that might have happened

01:35:11.590 --> 01:35:15.910
on U Street, if U Street had
been allowed to remain U Street,

01:35:15.910 --> 01:35:18.490
instead of so many businesses

01:35:18.490 --> 01:35:22.140
and black people
being forced to leave?

01:35:22.140 --> 01:35:23.440
And I actually think
that that has

01:35:23.440 --> 01:35:24.990
to be our question
before we even think

01:35:24.990 --> 01:35:29.330
about sustaining ourselves
there, is really sitting openly

01:35:29.330 --> 01:35:32.660
with the ethical question if
we have now made a decision

01:35:32.660 --> 01:35:38.610
about the future of Mars
and nothing will happen

01:35:38.610 --> 01:35:43.570
in a non-anthroposcenic
way on Mars ever again.

01:35:45.870 --> 01:35:48.200
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: Also
point out that it's true

01:35:48.200 --> 01:35:50.430
that we don't, you know,
see like space giraffes

01:35:50.430 --> 01:35:53.100
or human beings walking
around in the surface of Mars.

01:35:53.100 --> 01:35:57.100
But, in many ways, we have often
quite literally only scratched

01:35:57.100 --> 01:36:00.540
the surface and we don't know
what history might be there,

01:36:00.540 --> 01:36:02.710
we don't know whether
there are microbial

01:36:02.710 --> 01:36:07.420
or even more complex communities
of life under the surface.

01:36:07.420 --> 01:36:10.490
You know, the results
of methane on Mars is--

01:36:10.490 --> 01:36:12.840
are very, very tantalizing.

01:36:12.840 --> 01:36:14.290
They could be geological.

01:36:14.290 --> 01:36:16.940
They could be-- you
know, it could be oil,

01:36:16.940 --> 01:36:21.480
like there's any number of
possible outcomes for that.

01:36:21.480 --> 01:36:24.620
And so I think-- And we'll
