02:00:51.160 --> 02:00:54.380
that we've had here
on our own planet.

02:00:54.380 --> 02:00:57.470
So, without further ado, I
will introduce our panelists

02:00:57.470 --> 02:01:01.590
and if I can ask you to walk
up as you saw this morning.

02:01:01.590 --> 02:01:03.590
Dana Burton is a PhD student

02:01:03.590 --> 02:01:05.140
at George Washington
University's

02:01:05.140 --> 02:01:07.030
Anthropology Department.

02:01:07.030 --> 02:01:09.830
Her research follows the search
for life on Mars and seeks

02:01:09.830 --> 02:01:13.060
to understand the epistemologies
of value and order which come

02:01:13.060 --> 02:01:17.000
to be applied to Martian life by
various policymakers, scientists

02:01:17.000 --> 02:01:18.960
and private entrepreneurs.

02:01:18.960 --> 02:01:22.460
With attention to feminist
and multispecies literature,

02:01:22.460 --> 02:01:25.770
her work explorer visions
of life and living in space

02:01:25.770 --> 02:01:28.260
and how it shapes our
conceptions of the environment,

02:01:28.260 --> 02:01:30.950
sociality, and governance.

02:01:30.950 --> 02:01:34.360
Thus far, her work has taken her
to myriad conferences, lectures

02:01:34.360 --> 02:01:37.830
and laboratories, in D.C.,
Texas, and California.

02:01:37.830 --> 02:01:40.100
She plans to be a part of
projects further a-field,

02:01:40.100 --> 02:01:41.730
whether they be space
analog sites

02:01:41.730 --> 02:01:44.780
in Iceland or Chile or beyond.

02:01:44.780 --> 02:01:48.360
Dana is also an avid fiction
reader and enjoys blues dancing.

02:01:48.360 --> 02:01:50.360
And above all, she loves
drinking tea and getting

02:01:50.360 --> 02:01:52.890
into conversations
about affect, presence,

02:01:52.890 --> 02:01:55.510
and the intricacies
of everyday life.

02:02:00.210 --> 02:02:03.880
Nathalie Cabrol is the director
of the Carl Sagan Center

02:02:03.880 --> 02:02:06.070
for Research at the
SETI Institute,

02:02:06.070 --> 02:02:07.850
where she leads the
strategic vision

02:02:07.850 --> 02:02:09.960
for science and exploration.

02:02:09.960 --> 02:02:13.980
She heads projects in planetary
science and astrobiology,

02:02:13.980 --> 02:02:16.920
develops science exploration
strategies for Mars, Titan,

02:02:16.920 --> 02:02:19.310
and the Outer Solar
System icy moons,

02:02:19.310 --> 02:02:21.850
and designs robotic
field experiments.

02:02:21.850 --> 02:02:25.640
She's a member of the NASA Mars
Exploration Rover science team.

02:02:25.640 --> 02:02:28.040
Nathalie explores high
altitude lakes in the Andes

02:02:28.040 --> 02:02:30.210
as analogs to early Mars.

02:02:30.210 --> 02:02:33.200
She documents life's adaptation
to extreme environments,

02:02:33.200 --> 02:02:36.090
the effect of rapid climate
change on lake ecosystems

02:02:36.090 --> 02:02:40.300
and habitats, its geobiological
signatures, and relevance

02:02:40.300 --> 02:02:42.340
to planetary exploration.

02:02:42.340 --> 02:02:45.730
Nathalie counts over 410
peer-reviewed publications

02:02:45.730 --> 02:02:48.110
and proceedings of
professional conferences.

02:02:48.110 --> 02:02:50.470
She's authored three books
and 10 chapters of books

02:02:50.470 --> 02:02:53.170
on the subject of planetary
science and exploration,

02:02:53.170 --> 02:02:56.230
astrobiology, and terrestrial
extreme environments.

02:02:56.230 --> 02:02:59.400
Her work is featured on US--
in US and international media

02:02:59.400 --> 02:03:09.980
as well as in popular books.

02:03:11.750 --> 02:03:14.990
Bobak Ferdowsi is known for
such things as Battlebots,

02:03:14.990 --> 02:03:17.930
Cupcake Wars, and Sharknado 3.

02:03:17.930 --> 02:03:19.830
But by day, he's the
Fault Protection lead

02:03:19.830 --> 02:03:21.720
for the joint NASA-ISRO mission,

02:03:21.720 --> 02:03:25.110
an Earth-observing satellite
evaluating global environmental

02:03:25.110 --> 02:03:26.700
change and hazards.

02:03:26.700 --> 02:03:29.580
His prior positions have
included the Europa Clipper

02:03:29.580 --> 02:03:32.030
flight system engineer,
Integrated Launch

02:03:32.030 --> 02:03:35.530
and Cruise Engineer on Mars
Science Laboratory Curiosity,

02:03:35.530 --> 02:03:37.900
and Science Planner on
the Cassini mission.

02:03:37.900 --> 02:03:40.480
In addition, he served
as flight director during

02:03:40.480 --> 02:03:42.550
Curiosity operations.

02:03:42.550 --> 02:03:45.290
Bobak earned his Bachelor of
Science degree in Aeronautics

02:03:45.290 --> 02:03:48.960
and Astronautics in 2001 from
the University of Washington

02:03:48.960 --> 02:03:51.590
and subsequently his Master
of Science in the same area

02:03:51.590 --> 02:03:54.650
from Massachusetts
Institute of Technology.

02:03:54.650 --> 02:03:56.700
Bobak has always wanted
to explore the universe.

02:03:56.700 --> 02:03:59.340
He plays shortstop in the Jet
Propulsion Laboratory softball

02:03:59.340 --> 02:04:02.990
league, with a career
0.817 batting average

02:04:02.990 --> 02:04:05.330
and usually rides
his bike to work.

02:04:09.670 --> 02:04:13.590
Margaret Huettl is a descendant
of Lac Courte Oreilles Ojibweg,

02:04:13.590 --> 02:04:19.850
Assyrian-- well, let me just
try that entire thing again.

02:04:19.850 --> 02:04:24.300
Margaret Huettl, a descendant
of Lac Courte Oreilles Ojibweg--

02:04:24.300 --> 02:04:29.080
I practiced this and I apologize
for what I'm currently doing,

02:04:29.080 --> 02:04:32.560
Ojibweg, Assyrian
refugees, European settlers,

02:04:32.560 --> 02:04:35.270
is assistant professor
in History and Ethic--

02:04:35.270 --> 02:04:37.090
History and Ethnic Studies

02:04:37.090 --> 02:04:39.750
at the University
of Nebraska-Lincoln.

02:04:39.750 --> 02:04:43.060
She earned her PhD in History
from the University of Nevada,

02:04:43.060 --> 02:04:45.870
Las Vegas, her M.A. in
Native American History

02:04:45.870 --> 02:04:48.520
from the University of
Oklahoma, and her B.A.

02:04:48.520 --> 02:04:50.690
from the University
of Rochester.

02:04:50.690 --> 02:04:52.970
She's a scholar of
Native American history

02:04:52.970 --> 02:04:54.530
and North American Wests,

02:04:54.530 --> 02:04:57.030
and her research examines
indigenous sovereignty

02:04:57.030 --> 02:05:00.890
and settler colonialism in
a transnational context.

02:05:00.890 --> 02:05:03.040
Her current project,
"Ojibwe Peoplehood

02:05:03.040 --> 02:05:07.960
in the North American West,
1854-1954", explores Ojibwe

02:05:07.960 --> 02:05:10.870
and Anishinaabe sovereignty
in the United States

02:05:10.870 --> 02:05:13.880
and Canada during the
19th and 20th centuries,

02:05:13.880 --> 02:05:18.720
centering her research on
Anishinaabe ways of knowing.

02:05:25.240 --> 02:05:28.240
Thank you so much, the
panelists, for joining us today.

02:05:28.240 --> 02:05:32.440
In this panel, we'll
be directing questions

02:05:32.440 --> 02:05:35.540
to specific folks here on
the panel, but I hope to hear

02:05:35.540 --> 02:05:39.170
from each one of you in
turn about your thoughts.

02:05:39.170 --> 02:05:43.750
So, the very first thing that
I'd like to talk about, again,

02:05:43.750 --> 02:05:45.290
goes back to this
theme of narratives

02:05:45.290 --> 02:05:48.160
that we have been
revisiting here today.

02:05:48.160 --> 02:05:51.320
And, my first question
is for you, Margaret.

02:05:51.320 --> 02:05:54.670
So one of the things that
often comes up in space is

02:05:54.670 --> 02:05:58.540
that we often use a
comparison to the frontier.

02:05:58.540 --> 02:06:02.670
And I think often times,
that's invoked in a way

02:06:02.670 --> 02:06:06.340
that is not particularly
critical that invokes frontiers

02:06:06.340 --> 02:06:11.250
and the American West in a very
positive sense when, in fact,

02:06:11.250 --> 02:06:14.850
the exploration of the American
West was harmful to many people.

02:06:14.850 --> 02:06:17.780
And, given your scholarship,
you know,

02:06:17.780 --> 02:06:19.530
how do you think the narratives

02:06:19.530 --> 02:06:22.450
that we use shape our
understanding of history

02:06:22.450 --> 02:06:25.330
and the way that we
envision the future?

02:06:25.330 --> 02:06:27.700
&gt;&gt; Margaret Huettl: I
think talking about space

02:06:27.700 --> 02:06:30.490
in that language of the
frontier, one of the things

02:06:30.490 --> 02:06:34.770
that it does is it goes back
to these settler fantasies

02:06:34.770 --> 02:06:39.070
about what the West was, what
North America was, right,

02:06:39.070 --> 02:06:41.180
the language of the
new world, the language

02:06:41.180 --> 02:06:44.960
of this virgin wilderness
that is untouched

02:06:44.960 --> 02:06:48.220
by any real habitation
despite the fact, of course,

02:06:48.220 --> 02:06:52.360
that there's, you know,
millions, maybe even tens

02:06:52.360 --> 02:06:56.690
of millions of Native Americans
living in North America,

02:06:56.690 --> 02:07:01.220
not to mention South America,
but the language of the frontier

02:07:01.220 --> 02:07:06.610
of discovery imagines virgin
wilderness, untouched space

02:07:06.610 --> 02:07:10.120
that exists for one
purpose and that purpose is

02:07:10.120 --> 02:07:15.430
for the exploitation of the
new commerce, the exploitation

02:07:15.430 --> 02:07:17.750
of the settlers rather than as

02:07:17.750 --> 02:07:23.660
like a fully developed
space place on its own.

02:07:23.660 --> 02:07:25.080
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: And
do you see parallels to that

02:07:25.080 --> 02:07:27.420
in the way that we
talk about space?

02:07:27.420 --> 02:07:28.720
&gt;&gt; Margaret Huettl: I do.

02:07:28.720 --> 02:07:31.130
And the language comes up
a lot like when various--

02:07:31.130 --> 02:07:36.190
I know there is-- I don't
remember who it was from SpaceX

02:07:36.190 --> 02:07:40.460
that was talking about not
wanting space to be a wild west.

02:07:40.460 --> 02:07:46.490
There's lots of language about,
you know, going out and carrying

02:07:46.490 --> 02:07:49.500
on this narrative
of exploration.

02:07:49.500 --> 02:07:52.990
When people talk about
exploring space, the language

02:07:52.990 --> 02:07:57.340
that they use often references
the past using the language

02:07:57.340 --> 02:08:00.190
like frontier.

02:08:00.190 --> 02:08:03.130
I mean, that's inherently
invoking the story

02:08:03.130 --> 02:08:07.850
about the exploration of
North America, the settling

02:08:07.850 --> 02:08:10.940
of North America that doesn't
actually match the reality

02:08:10.940 --> 02:08:14.620
of what happened, but
instead puts, you know,

02:08:14.620 --> 02:08:18.770
these fictional explorers
in kind of, you know,

02:08:18.770 --> 02:08:21.630
glowing lights where
they're, you know,

02:08:21.630 --> 02:08:24.990
doing good for the
rest of humanity.

02:08:24.990 --> 02:08:26.290
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: Yeah.

02:08:26.290 --> 02:08:29.550
So-- And if I can broaden this
to the entire panel, you know,

02:08:29.550 --> 02:08:33.930
the use even of the word
colonization was very heavily

02:08:33.930 --> 02:08:35.750
debated back in the '70s.

02:08:35.750 --> 02:08:38.020
There were all these
meetings at NASA EMS

02:08:38.020 --> 02:08:42.500
about imagining life human
beings living off world

02:08:42.500 --> 02:08:46.050
with one camp sort
of exemplified

02:08:46.050 --> 02:08:49.440
by Stewart Brand being that, you
know, we should use colonization

02:08:49.440 --> 02:08:52.840
because it would help us
remember, in his words,

02:08:52.840 --> 02:08:56.720
I think it was, what was good
and bad about colonization,

02:08:56.720 --> 02:08:59.740
which we could take
into in and of itself.

02:08:59.740 --> 02:09:01.990
And then folks like
Carl Sagan saying

02:09:01.990 --> 02:09:04.650
that we should use
something like space cities

02:09:04.650 --> 02:09:07.550
because cities have a lot of
different kinds of people.

02:09:07.550 --> 02:09:10.470
But one of the things that I've
really been wondering about is

02:09:10.470 --> 02:09:14.390
to what extent does our
choice of wording matter.

02:09:14.390 --> 02:09:18.200
You know, many of the
things that I think a lot

02:09:18.200 --> 02:09:20.110
of scientists even who shy away

02:09:20.110 --> 02:09:23.160
from saying colonization
will use like discovery

02:09:23.160 --> 02:09:27.500
or exploration as sort of
neutral words, and I'd love

02:09:27.500 --> 02:09:30.300
to hear from the panel
how you choose your words

02:09:30.300 --> 02:09:31.630
when you talk about
these things.

02:09:31.630 --> 02:09:34.550
I see now that you're
reaching for the--

02:09:34.550 --> 02:09:35.850
&gt;&gt; Nathalie Cabrol:
Yes, no, just--

02:09:35.850 --> 02:09:40.940
it reminds me, and Bobak might
be also sensitive to that.

02:09:40.940 --> 02:09:45.560
Words are, you know, very
important, but engineers

02:09:45.560 --> 02:09:48.250
and scientists, when they're
preparing mission to Mars

02:09:48.250 --> 02:09:51.540
on where they have to operate
the mission in Mars, well,

02:09:51.540 --> 02:09:53.790
for the Mars Exploration
Rover team, we had to work

02:09:53.790 --> 02:09:57.790
on a dictionary, because
I was saying something

02:09:57.790 --> 02:10:01.470
and I had somebody right
next to me who was nodding

02:10:01.470 --> 02:10:03.850
and hearing the words
but we realize

02:10:03.850 --> 02:10:07.300
that sometimes we're not
saying the same thing at all.

02:10:07.300 --> 02:10:09.860
So, there is a perception.

02:10:09.860 --> 02:10:13.140
As an environmental scientist,
I can tell you that, for me,

02:10:13.140 --> 02:10:15.650
there is no negative
connotation to say

02:10:15.650 --> 02:10:19.020
that bacteria colonize a rock.

02:10:19.020 --> 02:10:20.320
They do what they do.

02:10:20.320 --> 02:10:23.520
They are just expanding their
territory, but for them,

02:10:23.520 --> 02:10:25.560
there is no negative
connotation.

02:10:25.560 --> 02:10:27.990
I think that the
negative connotation comes

02:10:27.990 --> 02:10:31.280
from the interaction of--

02:10:31.280 --> 02:10:34.670
in human history when people
actually did nasty things

02:10:34.670 --> 02:10:35.970
to each other.

02:10:35.970 --> 02:10:39.100
But, I think that this
is the weight of history

02:10:39.100 --> 02:10:42.780
that we put behind the
words, and we have to be,

02:10:42.780 --> 02:10:45.320
you know, acknowledging this.

02:10:45.320 --> 02:10:49.110
But you can also say, well,
OK, we are colonizing Mars

02:10:49.110 --> 02:10:54.060
as the bacteria is
colonizing the next rock

02:10:54.060 --> 02:10:56.650
because this is what they
do, they need to grow

02:10:56.650 --> 02:10:59.320
and they are going
to this other space.

02:10:59.320 --> 02:11:04.430
So, I would say, yes, we need
to be very sensitive to history,

02:11:04.430 --> 02:11:05.800
but we also have to understand

02:11:05.800 --> 02:11:09.550
that sometimes we could go
beyond the words themselves.

02:11:09.550 --> 02:11:16.180
&gt;&gt; Dana Burton: Just to quickly
follow up with that as well

02:11:16.180 --> 02:11:19.750
as also, you know, along
the line of being sensitive

02:11:19.750 --> 02:11:22.000
to words is also
not hiding the fact

02:11:22.000 --> 02:11:24.080
that those histories
happened either, right?

02:11:24.080 --> 02:11:28.630
Exactly. So, like the
idea that if we're going

02:11:28.630 --> 02:11:31.710
to replace the word colonization
with something else,

02:11:31.710 --> 02:11:34.780
is it actually changing the
actions that are happening

02:11:34.780 --> 02:11:37.660
or is it just invoking a
different kind of mask?

02:11:37.660 --> 02:11:41.570
And then what would get smuggled
in with those different types

02:11:41.570 --> 02:11:48.010
of activities if we call it
habitation or something else?

02:11:49.690 --> 02:11:52.380
&gt;&gt; Bobak Ferdowsi: So I also
find it rather interesting

02:11:52.380 --> 02:11:55.950
because 10 years ago, I'm
sure I was guilty of some

02:11:55.950 --> 02:12:00.340
of the Manifest Destiny sort of
things as well and, you know,

02:12:00.340 --> 02:12:02.810
trying to be more
aware of the situation

02:12:02.810 --> 02:12:06.360
as a representative of NASA.

02:12:06.360 --> 02:12:08.920
I think one of the things
that's interesting is a lot

02:12:08.920 --> 02:12:11.640
of this comes up from
an American dominance

02:12:11.640 --> 02:12:12.940
in the space exploration field.

02:12:12.940 --> 02:12:16.700
You don't necessarily hear the
same words, in my experience,

02:12:16.700 --> 02:12:18.460
with some of the
other space agencies

02:12:18.460 --> 02:12:20.910
that I've had the
opportunity to work with.

02:12:20.910 --> 02:12:26.750
And so, as kind of the de
facto owners of sort of this,

02:12:26.750 --> 02:12:29.340
you know, whether it's
NASA, whether it's SpaceX,

02:12:29.340 --> 02:12:33.000
whether it's, you know, kind
of industry, going to Mars,

02:12:33.000 --> 02:12:36.430
that certainly does mean
that we sort of tend

02:12:36.430 --> 02:12:38.130
to the familiar terms.

02:12:38.130 --> 02:12:40.970
And you see even in the
current administration, right,

02:12:40.970 --> 02:12:44.390
there's sometimes some almost
a religious-like aspect

02:12:44.390 --> 02:12:47.400
of divinity, of a sort of
amount of-- you know, again,

02:12:47.400 --> 02:12:50.230
a Manifest Destiny,
but as imparted to us

02:12:50.230 --> 02:12:54.410
by a supreme being version
of that in our conversations.

02:12:54.410 --> 02:12:57.100
But I think also to your point
is we definitely do strive,

02:12:57.100 --> 02:12:59.450
right, in engineering even and
we're very technical people,

02:12:59.450 --> 02:13:02.910
but we also work very hard
to define the semantics

02:13:02.910 --> 02:13:04.380
of what we're talking about.

02:13:04.380 --> 02:13:06.900
And that those things
really do matter in our--

02:13:06.900 --> 02:13:08.310
you know, in our case
often times is just

02:13:08.310 --> 02:13:11.170
because if I make the
wrong choice based

02:13:11.170 --> 02:13:13.100
on an interpretation of what
you're doing, we've lost,

02:13:13.100 --> 02:13:16.840
you know, a billion dollar
mission but also because it's--

02:13:16.840 --> 02:13:19.640
you know, it's the way that
we come to a common framework.

02:13:19.640 --> 02:13:21.980
So I'm willing to accept,
of course, any term,

02:13:21.980 --> 02:13:24.880
but I think we also have
to, you know, as a society,

02:13:24.880 --> 02:13:26.200
agree on what the
meaning of that term

02:13:26.200 --> 02:13:29.730
as in what the connotations are.

02:13:29.730 --> 02:13:32.370
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz:
So, if we can explore some

02:13:32.370 --> 02:13:35.070
of these narratives
a little bit more.

02:13:35.070 --> 02:13:39.060
Dana, I wanted to particularly
ask you, given your background

02:13:39.060 --> 02:13:42.420
in anthropology and your work.

02:13:42.420 --> 02:13:45.980
Another thing that I hear a lot,
when we talk about this stuff,

02:13:45.980 --> 02:13:49.650
is not just necessarily
references specifically

02:13:49.650 --> 02:13:53.380
to the American west or the
frontier, but we also hear a lot

02:13:53.380 --> 02:13:57.120
about like what humans do
and don't do, and I wonder

02:13:57.120 --> 02:14:01.980
if you could speak to that.

02:14:01.980 --> 02:14:05.240
&gt;&gt; Dana Burton: So, I guess one
of the first things you learn

02:14:05.240 --> 02:14:09.080
as an anthropologist is that
people are very different

02:14:09.080 --> 02:14:15.460
and it's very difficult to wrap
your head around difference

02:14:15.460 --> 02:14:18.650
because often in so much of our
everyday lives, we're trying

02:14:18.650 --> 02:14:21.970
to relate to each other, we're
trying to find similarities.

02:14:21.970 --> 02:14:25.050
Society and institutions are
all about making categories

02:14:25.050 --> 02:14:28.770
and then fitting people or
objects or beings into them.

02:14:28.770 --> 02:14:31.200
So, particularly with
space exploration,

02:14:31.200 --> 02:14:33.620
you have to be very
careful about the ways

02:14:33.620 --> 02:14:38.370
in which the human or
personhood is evoked

02:14:38.370 --> 02:14:42.810
because it can also not
give enough attention

02:14:42.810 --> 02:14:46.630
to the myriad different types
of experiences that people have.

02:14:46.630 --> 02:14:50.120
So, I think a really
good example would be

02:14:50.120 --> 02:14:53.560
from what we talked about in the
first panel, which is, you know,

02:14:53.560 --> 02:14:57.390
how people relate
to their bodies.

02:14:57.390 --> 02:15:01.170
Humanity has multiple
different types of ways

02:15:01.170 --> 02:15:05.920
in which we understand
privacy or intimacy

02:15:05.920 --> 02:15:10.100
and the ways bodies
get visualized

02:15:10.100 --> 02:15:11.750
or recognized or acknowledged.

02:15:11.750 --> 02:15:16.470
And so, it will be interesting
to see how these projects

02:15:16.470 --> 02:15:19.770
that push people
outside of known

02:15:19.770 --> 02:15:23.610
and recognizable environments
will shift how we understand

02:15:23.610 --> 02:15:27.540
bodies and people and humanity
in relation with each other

02:15:27.540 --> 02:15:30.470
as well as relationship
with the environment.

02:15:32.160 --> 02:15:35.210
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: What do
you think-- if there exists one,

02:15:35.210 --> 02:15:37.580
do you think that
there's a concrete effect

02:15:37.580 --> 02:15:41.500
to making statements
about what humans do?

02:15:41.500 --> 02:15:49.330
&gt;&gt; Dana Burton: A concrete
statement to what humans do?

02:15:49.330 --> 02:15:51.670
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: Yeah,
so I'm asking specifically

02:15:51.670 --> 02:15:55.560
about how these shape
or ideas of--

02:15:55.560 --> 02:15:59.080
you know, to return to actually
to that first panel of like

02:15:59.080 --> 02:16:03.000
who is an explorer or how we
include or disinclude people.

02:16:03.000 --> 02:16:07.930
You know, I think often times
when that phrase of like it's--

02:16:07.930 --> 02:16:10.690
it is in human's
nature to explore,

02:16:10.690 --> 02:16:14.130
I think that often shapes
the way that we think

02:16:14.130 --> 02:16:16.060
about who an explorer is.

02:16:16.060 --> 02:16:18.050
So I wonder if anyone
wants to speak to that.

02:16:18.050 --> 02:16:21.230
And I throw it out, not only
to you, but to the whole panel.

02:16:21.230 --> 02:16:23.360
&gt;&gt; Dana Burton: I
can start at least.

02:16:23.360 --> 02:16:27.830
It's-- I've also heard that
a lot in terms of, you know,

02:16:27.830 --> 02:16:31.410
people want to explore its
human's destiny to go forth

02:16:31.410 --> 02:16:36.580
and know and-- know
the universe.

02:16:36.580 --> 02:16:39.840
But, I think that
something that we could say

02:16:39.840 --> 02:16:44.980
with the humans are is,
we relate to each other,

02:16:44.980 --> 02:16:49.110
we interact with each other, and
we have these common experiences

02:16:49.110 --> 02:16:52.630
that deeply affect
who we are and it's

02:16:52.630 --> 02:16:58.400
through these different
experiences that we are able

02:16:58.400 --> 02:17:03.940
to comprehend a lot of the
narratives around space.

02:17:03.940 --> 02:17:07.990
And so, you know, the
idea that even thinking

02:17:07.990 --> 02:17:10.720
of the word exploration is going
to have different resonances

02:17:10.720 --> 02:17:13.560
with a lot of different people
and yet at the same time,

02:17:13.560 --> 02:17:16.870
we may be able to understand
what those resonances are

02:17:16.870 --> 02:17:20.160
and where those common grounds
are and have conversations

02:17:20.160 --> 02:17:27.570
that would promote in theory
of respectful or a type

02:17:27.570 --> 02:17:31.190
of exploration hopefully
that isn't all exploitative.

02:17:32.470 --> 02:17:37.620
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: Anyone
else want to comment on that?

02:17:37.620 --> 02:17:39.340
&gt;&gt; Nathalie Cabrol:
Obviously, you know,

02:17:39.340 --> 02:17:42.300
this aspect of anthropology
and relationship, et cetera,

02:17:42.300 --> 02:17:44.460
isn't on my expertise.

02:17:44.460 --> 02:17:48.360
What I can relate to is, once
again, going back to looking

02:17:48.360 --> 02:17:51.710
at life on this planet, we
say humans are explorer,

02:17:51.710 --> 02:17:55.260
you can take this statement
and take life as an explorer.

02:17:55.260 --> 02:17:57.310
And the reason why we're
still here today is

02:17:57.310 --> 02:18:01.450
because life has given itself
a chance to adapt and evolve

02:18:01.450 --> 02:18:04.410
and survive by multiplying
its environment

02:18:04.410 --> 02:18:07.320
and the habitat it has been
colonizing for 4 billion years.

02:18:07.320 --> 02:18:10.680
So it's not just human, this is
not something that is specific

02:18:10.680 --> 02:18:13.460
to us, what is specific to us is

02:18:13.460 --> 02:18:16.380
that now we have the
technology to take it farther.

02:18:16.380 --> 02:18:19.610
We also have a society
that allows human to relate

02:18:19.610 --> 02:18:23.200
to each other, but it's
not specific to human,

02:18:23.200 --> 02:18:24.980
it's specific to life.

02:18:24.980 --> 02:18:28.200
So, if you want to take the
interaction between humans

02:18:28.200 --> 02:18:31.920
and how it's going
to color exploration,

02:18:31.920 --> 02:18:36.780
you can say this also of
symbiotic systems of life.

02:18:36.780 --> 02:18:38.940
How you're successful
or less successful

02:18:38.940 --> 02:18:42.090
in an extreme environment
is who you are going

02:18:42.090 --> 02:18:46.120
to associate yourself
with and use the strength

02:18:46.120 --> 02:18:49.290
of the next body of yours,
the next microorganism

02:18:49.290 --> 02:18:51.220
to make the system function.

02:18:51.220 --> 02:18:56.320
As a human, we can see this
this way, and it is that--

02:18:56.320 --> 02:18:59.710
and when we're having this
discussion just before the panel

02:18:59.710 --> 02:19:03.310
and we had it even, you know,
a few days prior to that.

02:19:03.310 --> 02:19:12.230
For me, I see all of you in
this room not as gender or races

02:19:12.230 --> 02:19:14.660
or as an environmental
scientist,

02:19:14.660 --> 02:19:16.990
I see you as the product

02:19:16.990 --> 02:19:21.070
of environment, climate
and history.

02:19:21.070 --> 02:19:22.560
The differences in our bodies,

02:19:22.560 --> 02:19:25.120
difference in our
culture reflect

02:19:25.120 --> 02:19:28.430
where we have been evolving,
where our history reside,

02:19:28.430 --> 02:19:31.300
what kind of climate
we have been under.

02:19:31.300 --> 02:19:33.500
How we have perceived
the environment

02:19:33.500 --> 02:19:36.530
and how we relate
it structurally

02:19:36.530 --> 02:19:38.960
as organism, we are
all the same.

02:19:38.960 --> 02:19:43.830
The difference we are showing
here is really about that.

02:19:43.830 --> 02:19:46.010
And it's true for all system.

02:19:46.010 --> 02:19:49.150
What is really interesting
is how are we going

02:19:49.150 --> 02:19:52.390
to use this reflection of who
we are which is a reflection

02:19:52.390 --> 02:19:58.650
of biodiversity and adaptation
into the next exploration.

02:19:58.650 --> 02:20:02.790
The same-- that is true
for microorganic colonies,

02:20:02.790 --> 02:20:05.010
it's true for us as well.

02:20:05.010 --> 02:20:07.530
But on top of this, we
have brought what we call

02:20:07.530 --> 02:20:10.410
intelligence and, again, as
an environmental scientist,

02:20:10.410 --> 02:20:14.130
I would say that, you know,
anybody will make it this far,

02:20:14.130 --> 02:20:17.630
you know, on our planet has to
be intelligent in some ways.

02:20:17.630 --> 02:20:22.290
But we brought a society and
we brought an interaction

02:20:22.290 --> 02:20:27.130
which is negative or positive
but we all have strength.

02:20:27.130 --> 02:20:29.350
Beyond our diversity,
we are here,

02:20:29.350 --> 02:20:32.590
we are survivors,
we're adaptable.

02:20:32.590 --> 02:20:35.360
And I think that this is what
is going to take us next,

02:20:35.360 --> 02:20:37.350
this is what we need
to use beyond the terms

02:20:37.350 --> 02:20:40.560
of colonization, between
the-- beyond the terms of,

02:20:40.560 --> 02:20:43.530
you know, cultures, et cetera.

02:20:43.530 --> 02:20:48.140
We need to bring our
strength like symbiotic system

02:20:48.140 --> 02:20:49.690
if we want to make it.

02:20:49.690 --> 02:20:52.340
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: Yeah.

02:20:52.340 --> 02:20:53.640
&gt;&gt; Margaret Huettl:
One of the things

02:20:53.640 --> 02:20:57.340
that this conversation makes
me think about and, I'm sorry,

02:20:57.340 --> 02:20:59.360
I guess today finds
me in a little bit

02:20:59.360 --> 02:21:04.280
of a pessimistic mood,
is the way that appeals

02:21:04.280 --> 02:21:09.940
to the public good or
universal truce have been used

02:21:09.940 --> 02:21:12.890
to violate the rights

02:21:12.890 --> 02:21:15.970
of minority peoples
throughout history.

02:21:15.970 --> 02:21:20.190
I think maybe an example that
fits this space is, I mean,

02:21:20.190 --> 02:21:23.120
not too far from here,
there have been drawers full

02:21:23.120 --> 02:21:27.390
of native people's bodies,
ancestor's bodies in drawers

02:21:27.390 --> 02:21:31.670
for decades, right, stolen
from graves, heads cut off

02:21:31.670 --> 02:21:35.540
by US military generals
and reduced

02:21:35.540 --> 02:21:38.180
to data for the public good.

02:21:38.180 --> 02:21:41.890
And when native people asked to
have their ancestors returned

02:21:41.890 --> 02:21:43.470
to them, they were said,
well, you're standing

02:21:43.470 --> 02:21:44.890
in the way of science.

02:21:44.890 --> 02:21:48.570
We all need this knowledge,
this is something that--

02:21:48.570 --> 02:21:50.670
you know, that is
for everybody's good

02:21:50.670 --> 02:21:53.130
and your objection
doesn't, you know,

02:21:53.130 --> 02:21:55.060
carry as much weight
in this conversation.

02:21:55.060 --> 02:22:00.370
And so, I have questions
about how this--

02:22:00.370 --> 02:22:02.000
you know, this appeal

02:22:02.000 --> 02:22:05.470
to a common humanity could
potentially, not necessarily,

02:22:05.470 --> 02:22:08.240
but potentially be
used in a similar way

02:22:08.240 --> 02:22:11.100
to override the perspectives
of people

02:22:11.100 --> 02:22:16.810
who don't necessarily
agree with, you know, yes,

02:22:16.810 --> 02:22:19.780
with people who are
making decisions.

02:22:22.850 --> 02:22:25.130
&gt;&gt; Bobak Ferdowsi: I think you
are right, we are talking kind

02:22:25.130 --> 02:22:26.590
of similar theme to
climate change, right,

02:22:26.590 --> 02:22:28.910
where we are making
decisions on behalf

02:22:28.910 --> 02:22:31.720
of everybody whether
we like it or not.

02:22:31.720 --> 02:22:35.380
I think you hit an interesting
point of technology because,

02:22:35.380 --> 02:22:37.550
you know, the technology allows
us to explore is also some

02:22:37.550 --> 02:22:40.090
of the technology that allows
us to survive and thrive

02:22:40.090 --> 02:22:43.250
in our environments, right, the
fact that we can get crop yields

02:22:43.250 --> 02:22:46.150
that are, you know, hundreds
of times what they were

02:22:46.150 --> 02:22:49.210
and also can, you know, the
[inaudible] the extract oil

02:22:49.210 --> 02:22:53.740
from sand essentially and make
our cars go for years to come.

02:22:53.740 --> 02:22:56.860
It is an interesting dilemma,
though, because, right,

02:22:56.860 --> 02:22:59.090
those are things
that both have the--

02:22:59.090 --> 02:23:00.540
you know, the benefits
to some of us

02:23:00.540 --> 02:23:03.540
and not necessarily equal
benefits to all people.

02:23:03.540 --> 02:23:05.470
And it's a really difficult
challenge, and I was thinking

02:23:05.470 --> 02:23:07.150
about the earlier panelists,

02:23:07.150 --> 02:23:08.990
it's from a narrative
perspective, it's very easy

02:23:08.990 --> 02:23:11.000
for me to be like-- ask all
of you to close your eyes

02:23:11.000 --> 02:23:14.820
and imagine, for example, a
world without homelessness.

02:23:14.820 --> 02:23:16.230
And for most of us in this room,

02:23:16.230 --> 02:23:18.520
it really doesn't change our
life in a significant way.

02:23:18.520 --> 02:23:20.210
But if I ask you to close your
eyes and imagine you're living

02:23:20.210 --> 02:23:25.400
on Mars, the life story is a
very dramatically different one.

02:23:25.400 --> 02:23:27.720
And I think that's one of the
problems that we sort of have,

02:23:27.720 --> 02:23:30.170
is the sort of the
ability to put ourselves

02:23:30.170 --> 02:23:31.470
in these other perspective

02:23:31.470 --> 02:23:33.390
and how do you tell the
narrative of, well, obviously,

02:23:33.390 --> 02:23:34.920
if I was a homeless person--

02:23:34.920 --> 02:23:37.470
the life that I'm not homeless
is a significant difference

02:23:37.470 --> 02:23:38.770
to me.

02:23:38.770 --> 02:23:41.470
So how do I then put
myself into that perspective

02:23:41.470 --> 02:23:43.030
and I think that's
the challenge that,

02:23:43.030 --> 02:23:44.630
you know, each of us faces.

02:23:44.630 --> 02:23:48.240
I think, you know, the way
that I'm slowly learning

02:23:48.240 --> 02:23:50.170
to do this is, right, through
conversations like this

02:23:50.170 --> 02:23:52.960
and to kind of think
about, OK, what is it not

02:23:52.960 --> 02:23:54.660
like to have my own experience

02:23:54.660 --> 02:23:56.580
but to have other
people's experiences.

02:23:56.580 --> 02:24:00.390
And amazingly, right, we slowly
see, I think, overtime that some

02:24:00.390 --> 02:24:03.590
of these differences
come full circle, right?

02:24:03.590 --> 02:24:05.250
I think of L.A., for
example, where we used

02:24:05.250 --> 02:24:08.640
to have bike paths throughout
the city that were torn out for,

02:24:08.640 --> 02:24:10.920
you know, freeways to be made

02:24:10.920 --> 02:24:14.020
and now we're going back
to bike paths, right?

02:24:14.020 --> 02:24:16.310
So what's-- you know,
what's old becomes new again

02:24:16.310 --> 02:24:17.610
and it is an interesting thing.

02:24:17.610 --> 02:24:19.240
So, to start thinking
about some of that like,

02:24:19.240 --> 02:24:21.330
what are the things that
we are missing out on

02:24:21.330 --> 02:24:25.290
because of so-called progress
but as in return like sort

02:24:25.290 --> 02:24:28.980
of cyclical process, you know,
not that we can cut corners

02:24:28.980 --> 02:24:34.010
but maybe there is a way for us
to sort of think in those terms.

02:24:34.010 --> 02:24:35.310
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: Yeah.

02:24:35.310 --> 02:24:38.170
You know, the point that
you both have brought

02:24:38.170 --> 02:24:43.010
up about not everyone
necessarily agreeing

02:24:43.010 --> 02:24:48.940
with space exploration, I guess,
I would say as an enterprise

02:24:48.940 --> 02:24:51.800
or even the language that
we use around it, right?

02:24:51.800 --> 02:24:54.760
I-- It makes me think actually
of some of the questions

02:24:54.760 --> 02:24:59.080
that exist about
astronaut health and, again,

02:24:59.080 --> 02:25:02.450
returning to this idea of
bodies in space, right?

02:25:02.450 --> 02:25:05.620
That essentially for
long duration missions,

02:25:05.620 --> 02:25:08.580
if we were to go to Mars
or something like that,

02:25:08.580 --> 02:25:11.960
there's no way for those health
standards to actually be met.

02:25:11.960 --> 02:25:14.750
So the way that it's
currently done is that NASA has

02:25:14.750 --> 02:25:18.360
to evaluate whether they
will violate the standards

02:25:18.360 --> 02:25:21.610
for astronaut health in
every single mission case.

02:25:21.610 --> 02:25:26.790
And so, there's also this
slightly more subtle issue,

02:25:26.790 --> 02:25:28.740
right, of informed consent.

02:25:28.740 --> 02:25:33.020
So you can say with astronauts
individually could, you know,

02:25:33.020 --> 02:25:34.860
we love thinking about
the individual here

02:25:34.860 --> 02:25:38.590
in the United States,
a lot of [inaudible].

02:25:38.590 --> 02:25:41.710
And so you could say, well,
an astronaut can choose

02:25:41.710 --> 02:25:46.770
to undertake a mission that
might create damage to them.

02:25:46.770 --> 02:25:50.790
However, when we think about
things like Mars sample return,

02:25:50.790 --> 02:25:54.500
you-- or even just private
space industry being in charge

02:25:54.500 --> 02:25:57.110
of flight, you know, when you
launch something into space,

02:25:57.110 --> 02:25:59.930
you launch over other people.

02:25:59.930 --> 02:26:04.630
You have the potential for risk
in which people are not able

02:26:04.630 --> 02:26:07.990
to actually consent
to being part of that,

02:26:07.990 --> 02:26:10.240
either because they don't
know what's going to happen

02:26:10.240 --> 02:26:11.950
or because they are-- you know,

02:26:11.950 --> 02:26:14.860
space doesn't obey
national boundaries.

02:26:14.860 --> 02:26:17.230
And then you also have things
like planetary protection

02:26:17.230 --> 02:26:20.560
which is this series of
policies which we'll get

02:26:20.560 --> 02:26:24.560
into momentarily, where you
could bring something back

02:26:24.560 --> 02:26:28.710
into the Earth environment that
would compromise us in some way.

02:26:28.710 --> 02:26:31.770
I wonder if we can
turn to thinking

02:26:31.770 --> 02:26:34.210
about policy and treaties.

02:26:34.210 --> 02:26:38.460
So, the Outer Space
Treaty which dates

02:26:38.460 --> 02:26:42.700
from 1967 is this governing
document of all of the things

02:26:42.700 --> 02:26:45.520
that one can and
can't do in space.

02:26:45.520 --> 02:26:48.760
I think my-- well,
prior to this year,

02:26:48.760 --> 02:26:53.040
myself and my fellow scientists
have a pretty warm fuzzy feeling

02:26:53.040 --> 02:26:54.340
towards the Outer Space Treaty

02:26:54.340 --> 02:26:57.700
that it's this very aspirational
document, and we'll dig

02:26:57.700 --> 02:26:59.000
into that in a moment.

02:26:59.000 --> 02:27:00.670
But first, I wanted
to look specifically

02:27:00.670 --> 02:27:01.970
at planetary protection.

02:27:01.970 --> 02:27:06.160
So, maybe I'll throw this
to Bobak, can you talk

02:27:06.160 --> 02:27:09.980
about planetary protection,
probably what it is

02:27:09.980 --> 02:27:12.470
and then how it's
implemented in missions?

02:27:12.470 --> 02:27:13.770
&gt;&gt; Bobak Ferdowsi: Yeah.

02:27:13.770 --> 02:27:15.070
So for those of you
who don't know, right,

02:27:15.070 --> 02:27:19.000
we do also have essentially
kind of our own Prime Directive

02:27:19.000 --> 02:27:23.330
when it comes to exploring other
places which is as we go there,

02:27:23.330 --> 02:27:27.090
we are-- for-- largely for--
honestly, for selfish reasons,

02:27:27.090 --> 02:27:29.740
which is we are trying to
preserve the environment as is.

02:27:29.740 --> 02:27:31.850
So that if we ask additional
scientific questions

02:27:31.850 --> 02:27:33.180
about those environments,

02:27:33.180 --> 02:27:34.810
then we haven't compromised
the readings.

02:27:34.810 --> 02:27:36.110
So, what that boils doubting

02:27:36.110 --> 02:27:38.540
for our missions is
essentially places

02:27:38.540 --> 02:27:40.980
where we think there's a
credible chance of habitability

02:27:40.980 --> 02:27:44.990
like Mars, like the moons
of Jupiter and Saturn.

02:27:44.990 --> 02:27:48.920
We deliberately clean
our traveling spacecraft

02:27:48.920 --> 02:27:51.380
and make an assessment
of how dirty they are

02:27:51.380 --> 02:27:53.260
from a biological perspective.

02:27:53.260 --> 02:27:56.220
And the probability that
they reach an environment

02:27:56.220 --> 02:27:58.890
where they could contaminate
that environment and say,

02:27:58.890 --> 02:28:02.250
you know, it has to be less in a
certain combined chance, right?

02:28:02.250 --> 02:28:05.140
So, I say, there is some
number of spores, you know,

02:28:05.140 --> 02:28:10.240
essentially of various microbial
life on my rover, the likelihood

02:28:10.240 --> 02:28:13.970
that it reaches a place that
has water or something else

02:28:13.970 --> 02:28:16.070
where they can survive, likely
they survive the whole trip

02:28:16.070 --> 02:28:18.740
from Earth to Mars, and then I
multiply that out and I figure,

02:28:18.740 --> 02:28:20.110
OK, it's less than
one in a billion,

02:28:20.110 --> 02:28:22.400
that's an acceptable risk.

02:28:22.400 --> 02:28:25.200
But also of course, as Lucianne
mentioned, it comes back

02:28:25.200 --> 02:28:28.030
to Earth which when we took
a sample and return, well,

02:28:28.030 --> 02:28:30.950
from preserving the
sample as a pure lunar

02:28:30.950 --> 02:28:32.250
or Martian environment.

02:28:32.250 --> 02:28:37.020
And as a preventative measure
for us somehow, you know,

02:28:37.020 --> 02:28:41.460
bringing back Andromeda strain
and like, you know, taking over.

02:28:41.460 --> 02:28:45.180
So, with that regard, it's,
you know, as an engineer,

02:28:45.180 --> 02:28:48.160
it's one of my-- it's
like one of those rules

02:28:48.160 --> 02:28:50.230
that we deal with, right?

02:28:50.230 --> 02:28:51.900
Like an essentially as an
engineer, I don't want to have

02:28:51.900 --> 02:28:53.750
to worry about how
clean my parts are

02:28:53.750 --> 02:28:55.860
because it makes my
job a little harder.

02:28:55.860 --> 02:28:58.800
But as, you know,
as the big picture,

02:28:58.800 --> 02:29:00.780
we're able to understand,
OK, the context of this is

02:29:00.780 --> 02:29:03.360
if we are looking for a life
on Mars, the last thing we want

02:29:03.360 --> 02:29:06.160
to find is life that we
brought with us and be unable

02:29:06.160 --> 02:29:07.460
to answer the question.

02:29:07.460 --> 02:29:10.340
And to me, the question is very
different difficult in part

02:29:10.340 --> 02:29:12.280
because we're not entirely sure

02:29:12.280 --> 02:29:14.010
of whether life could've
originated at Mars

02:29:14.010 --> 02:29:16.860
or the places can [inaudible]
essentially life propagates with

02:29:16.860 --> 02:29:20.870
or without us like through
asteroids and other means,

02:29:20.870 --> 02:29:23.660
and whether life would look
the same in it's origin,

02:29:23.660 --> 02:29:25.490
so meaning that even if
it's independently derived,

02:29:25.490 --> 02:29:27.120
it doesn't have to be
DNA-based, it doesn't have

02:29:27.120 --> 02:29:29.890
to have other similar
trait star life.

02:29:29.890 --> 02:29:32.760
So, we use those rules in
order to protect those kind

02:29:32.760 --> 02:29:35.530
of boundaries and be able
to ask scientific questions.

02:29:35.530 --> 02:29:38.950
But I think it's really selfish,
I don' think we are thinking

02:29:38.950 --> 02:29:41.580
of that, oh, from the good of
Mars perspective that we're in,

02:29:41.580 --> 02:29:45.290
you know, from the good of
the science perspective.

02:29:45.290 --> 02:29:47.730
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: And,
you know, I think currently,

02:29:47.730 --> 02:29:52.040
the current administration
is very pro-relaxation

02:29:52.040 --> 02:29:53.340
of regulation.

02:29:53.340 --> 02:29:55.860
And I know that there
are some people,

02:29:55.860 --> 02:29:59.030
at least within like the
scientific community as well

02:29:59.030 --> 02:30:02.450
as maybe new space companies and
enterprises who don't want have

02:30:02.450 --> 02:30:06.010
to pay for planetary
protection, who have suggested

02:30:06.010 --> 02:30:09.130
that one should relax
planetary protection.

02:30:09.130 --> 02:30:10.600
And you've written
about this, Nathalie.

02:30:10.600 --> 02:30:13.990
Can you speak to what you
think planetary protection

02:30:13.990 --> 02:30:18.000
requirements, how and
if they should evolve

02:30:18.000 --> 02:30:19.300
as we move forward?

02:30:19.300 --> 02:30:21.580
&gt;&gt; Nathalie Cabrol:
Yeah, well, you know,

02:30:21.580 --> 02:30:24.160
I like to flip questions on
their head just to make sure

02:30:24.160 --> 02:30:26.580
that I'm looking at
different perspectives.

02:30:26.580 --> 02:30:29.580
And I think there is a
misperception right now

02:30:29.580 --> 02:30:31.250
about planetary protection.

02:30:31.250 --> 02:30:34.370
And I will go with
Bobak on this.

02:30:34.370 --> 02:30:36.770
It makes his life
very complicated

02:30:36.770 --> 02:30:38.310
but that's a good thing.

02:30:38.310 --> 02:30:43.010
We could discuss scientifically,
you know, would it be difficult

02:30:43.010 --> 02:30:47.130
to recognize terrestrial
life and Mars life?

02:30:47.130 --> 02:30:50.120
You look at coevolution and I
think it would be pretty easy

02:30:50.120 --> 02:30:54.300
to see who is coming from where,
because the evolution of Mars

02:30:54.300 --> 02:30:57.870
and the Earth very early-- even
very early was very different.

02:30:57.870 --> 02:31:02.260
But given that, we still want
to send the cleaner spacecraft.

02:31:02.260 --> 02:31:04.530
On the other hand,
there is this perception

02:31:04.530 --> 02:31:07.270
of planetary protection
as, you know,

02:31:07.270 --> 02:31:09.030
the bad guy who's
preventing you from going

02:31:09.030 --> 02:31:14.600
to the really cool place
where you want to explore.

02:31:14.600 --> 02:31:15.900
See? See this smirk.

02:31:15.900 --> 02:31:19.070
Well, you know, that's
a misperception.

02:31:19.070 --> 02:31:23.270
In fact, what planetary
protection is doing--

02:31:23.270 --> 02:31:26.870
should be doing and should
continue doing is really

02:31:26.870 --> 02:31:30.680
to bring in front of you
the question, what they are,

02:31:30.680 --> 02:31:33.460
what are the potential
issues, but just not

02:31:33.460 --> 02:31:36.220
to let you know that,
no, you cannot go there,

02:31:36.220 --> 02:31:39.010
to put you to work and
say, how I am going

02:31:39.010 --> 02:31:40.490
to be able solve that question.

02:31:40.490 --> 02:31:43.690
In fact, this is a source of
progress for me as somebody

02:31:43.690 --> 02:31:45.860
who was thinking in terms
of exploration strategies.

02:31:45.860 --> 02:31:47.750
Now, I'm just thinking
in terms of what kind

02:31:47.750 --> 02:31:52.150
of technology can I develop to
complete a cleaner spacecraft,

02:31:52.150 --> 02:31:56.580
to do penetration
of the subsurface

02:31:56.580 --> 02:32:00.510
where life actually could
be that is completely clean

02:32:00.510 --> 02:32:03.330
or are there ways from
biological experiment

02:32:03.330 --> 02:32:06.180
that I'm going to able to
recognize that life is coming

02:32:06.180 --> 02:32:07.560
from Mars or the Earth.

02:32:07.560 --> 02:32:11.510
And we are running against
time here because as you said,

02:32:11.510 --> 02:32:16.230
you know, there was a time
where space exploration was NASA

02:32:16.230 --> 02:32:18.780
or ESA or the Russian agencies.

02:32:18.780 --> 02:32:20.080
That's not the case anymore.

02:32:20.080 --> 02:32:21.380
I don't know if you are aware

02:32:21.380 --> 02:32:24.640
of there is a Tesla
going to Mars right now.

02:32:24.640 --> 02:32:30.040
And there are no real policies
in place at this point in time

02:32:30.040 --> 02:32:32.510
and also as for biologists,

02:32:32.510 --> 02:32:37.600
I would like to discover whether
there is life on Mars like not

02:32:37.600 --> 02:32:43.640
if life on Mars before humans
go, because once we're there,

02:32:43.640 --> 02:32:44.940
we will find life on Mars.

02:32:44.940 --> 02:32:46.540
I'm not being fastidious.

02:32:46.540 --> 02:32:48.310
We're just a microbio factory.

02:32:48.310 --> 02:32:49.990
And we already know
that some microbes

02:32:49.990 --> 02:32:52.960
that we are carrying would
survive to some extent

02:32:52.960 --> 02:32:55.170
in some places on Mars.

02:32:55.170 --> 02:32:58.690
So, for me, planetary
protection has

02:32:58.690 --> 02:33:02.930
to become an enabler
of exploration.

02:33:02.930 --> 02:33:05.650
And that's something that
prevents us from exploring.

02:33:05.650 --> 02:33:07.940
And I think that a lot of
good can come out of this

02:33:07.940 --> 02:33:10.570
because as usual, you're
pushing the envelope of thinking

02:33:10.570 --> 02:33:13.920
as exploration does and we
can come back to the question

02:33:13.920 --> 02:33:17.230
of climate change where
technologies we are, you know,

02:33:17.230 --> 02:33:20.010
developing for planetary
exploration are actually helping

02:33:20.010 --> 02:33:24.480
us monitor faster and better
environmental change on Earth.

02:33:24.480 --> 02:33:28.270
But-- So that would be my
viewpoint on these things.

02:33:28.270 --> 02:33:31.870
And right now, it still
fuzzy, a fuzzy discipline

02:33:31.870 --> 02:33:34.160
where we don't have
real policies.

02:33:34.160 --> 02:33:37.010
And we're asking all the
questions and everybody is going

02:33:37.010 --> 02:33:40.380
out there to the "final
frontier of space"

02:33:40.380 --> 02:33:44.910
without real guide lines on
what is harmful, what is not.

02:33:44.910 --> 02:33:46.210
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: Yeah.

02:33:46.210 --> 02:33:50.130
And if we can go to talk about
that policy, you know, Margaret,

02:33:50.130 --> 02:33:53.990
given your scholarship with
a, you know, nation head

02:33:53.990 --> 02:33:58.250
and sovereignty throughout
history for indigenous people,

02:33:58.250 --> 02:34:02.760
I wonder if you could speak
to the outer space treaty as,

02:34:02.760 --> 02:34:05.250
you know, should
scientists be as sanguine

02:34:05.250 --> 02:34:11.450
about its aspirational nature
as they perhaps are sometimes?

02:34:11.450 --> 02:34:13.990
&gt;&gt; Margaret Huetttl: So, I
think one thing that the history

02:34:13.990 --> 02:34:16.990
of treaty-making in the
United States specifically,

02:34:16.990 --> 02:34:20.420
and I think you could expand
this to Canada, Australia,

02:34:20.420 --> 02:34:24.120
and other places where
European nations have colonized,

02:34:24.120 --> 02:34:27.020
I think it teaches
us to be cautious.

02:34:27.020 --> 02:34:30.900
We're in a building that has
hundreds of native treaties,

02:34:30.900 --> 02:34:32.260
treaties with native nations

02:34:32.260 --> 02:34:37.130
and the United States has
broken every single one.

02:34:37.130 --> 02:34:41.620
And it's especially bad when
resources are involved, right?

02:34:41.620 --> 02:34:44.720
I think the good example of this
is the Treaty of Fort Laramie

02:34:44.720 --> 02:34:48.770
from 1868, which was
a treaty primarily

02:34:48.770 --> 02:34:51.130
with the Lakota people.

02:34:51.130 --> 02:34:52.750
And it protected
the Black Hills.

02:34:52.750 --> 02:34:55.400
Inside the Black Hills
are Lakota territory,

02:34:55.400 --> 02:34:58.870
the United States can't go here.

02:34:58.870 --> 02:35:01.860
And the United States'
responsibility is

02:35:01.860 --> 02:35:06.660
to make sure any US citizens
who go into Lakota territory,

02:35:06.660 --> 02:35:09.020
the military will
help remove them.

02:35:09.020 --> 02:35:12.270
But then, some of those white
citizens who weren't supposed

02:35:12.270 --> 02:35:16.180
to be in Lakota territory in
the first place found gold.

02:35:16.180 --> 02:35:20.990
And as has so often
happened in US history,

02:35:20.990 --> 02:35:22.980
it became a free-for-all, right?

02:35:22.980 --> 02:35:24.280
The US military ended

02:35:24.280 --> 02:35:29.200
up actually supporting the
settler miners who were looking

02:35:29.200 --> 02:35:31.310
for resources, violating
the treaties,

02:35:31.310 --> 02:35:34.440
starting a really
terrible genocidal war,

02:35:34.440 --> 02:35:37.890
and completely violating
the terms of the Treaty

02:35:37.890 --> 02:35:42.480
of Fort Laramie, which they
continue to violate to this day.

02:35:42.480 --> 02:35:47.490
The pipeline controversy is
also related to violations

02:35:47.490 --> 02:35:48.790
of the Treaty of Fort Laramie.

02:35:48.790 --> 02:35:51.370
So when there's resources
at stake,

02:35:51.370 --> 02:35:58.650
these kind of really grandiose
treaty terms often are not

02:35:58.650 --> 02:35:59.950
carried through.

02:35:59.950 --> 02:36:03.220
And part of the reason
for that is that baked

02:36:03.220 --> 02:36:08.400
into the United States' legal
system is a legal system

02:36:08.400 --> 02:36:14.620
that privileges private
enterprise and both individuals'

02:36:14.620 --> 02:36:20.030
and incorporations' access
to resources and access--

02:36:20.030 --> 02:36:23.820
and the United States'
right to certain territory,

02:36:23.820 --> 02:36:26.460
going back to the
Doctrine of Discovery,

02:36:26.460 --> 02:36:30.320
which said that it
started out as a papal bull

02:36:30.320 --> 02:36:32.540
in the 15th century and says

02:36:32.540 --> 02:36:37.260
that whatever Christian nation
discovers a territory has the

02:36:37.260 --> 02:36:39.470
rights to the territory
everything

02:36:39.470 --> 02:36:43.190
that is in that territory.

02:36:43.190 --> 02:36:47.150
And this concept is baked
into the US legal system

02:36:47.150 --> 02:36:50.850
and makes it really
easy to defend actions

02:36:50.850 --> 02:36:57.350
that would walk back, you know,
like the Outer Space Treaty.

02:36:57.350 --> 02:37:00.370
And I mean, we saw it under the
previous administration as well

02:37:00.370 --> 02:37:04.490
when they passed-- when
Congress passed a law that said

02:37:04.490 --> 02:37:07.170
that the products of, I
think it was asteroid mining

02:37:07.170 --> 02:37:12.930
and maybe more generally
that whoever is mining

02:37:12.930 --> 02:37:16.640
that has a right to profit
from those resources.

02:37:16.640 --> 02:37:20.830
And so, you know, there's
already been some undermining

02:37:20.830 --> 02:37:23.520
of the principles of
the Outer Space Treaty

02:37:23.520 --> 02:37:25.870
within just the United
States, and that's not talking

02:37:25.870 --> 02:37:29.770
about other nations
around the world as well.

02:37:29.770 --> 02:37:31.310
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: I
think one of the things

02:37:31.310 --> 02:37:35.490
that always strikes me is
that a lot of, you know,

02:37:35.490 --> 02:37:40.430
the move to extract resources,
so for example the Space Act

02:37:40.430 --> 02:37:44.490
from 2015 that you've just
referenced really clears the

02:37:44.490 --> 02:37:48.180
path for, sure, you can't
own a celestial body

02:37:48.180 --> 02:37:50.840
which is what the Outer Space
Treaty says, but you can,

02:37:50.840 --> 02:37:52.310
you know, own its resources.

02:37:52.310 --> 02:37:55.500
And particularly, I
was struck by the fact

02:37:55.500 --> 02:38:00.430
that water was explicitly
included in the Space Act.

02:38:00.430 --> 02:38:04.340
But at the same time,
a lot of the companies

02:38:04.340 --> 02:38:07.290
that are expressly
interested in doing

02:38:07.290 --> 02:38:10.220
that will also use this
rhetoric about how going

02:38:10.220 --> 02:38:11.740
to space will change us.

02:38:11.740 --> 02:38:16.280
And I wonder, Dana, maybe
you can speak to this.

02:38:16.280 --> 02:38:19.700
You know, I think there's
certainly the possibility

02:38:19.700 --> 02:38:22.410
for space to be something
that challenges us

02:38:22.410 --> 02:38:26.500
and perhaps makes us grow
but what do you think

02:38:26.500 --> 02:38:28.250
of that assertion, you know,

02:38:28.250 --> 02:38:34.420
in light of things
humans do and don't do.

02:38:34.420 --> 02:38:38.330
&gt;&gt; Dana Burton: Well,
I guess it depends

02:38:38.330 --> 02:38:41.820
on how people define
being better.

02:38:41.820 --> 02:38:47.340
So, what protections
make me think of is

02:38:47.340 --> 02:38:52.100
that there is a certain
type of valuation being put

02:38:52.100 --> 02:38:53.430
on whatever you're
trying to protect

02:38:53.430 --> 02:38:55.650
and that there are certain
people who are privileged

02:38:55.650 --> 02:38:57.930
to ensure that protection
and are pretty good.

02:38:57.930 --> 02:39:01.970
And particularly in terms of
like resource extraction, right,

02:39:01.970 --> 02:39:04.630
we have to ask the question
of who would be benefiting

02:39:04.630 --> 02:39:07.060
and how those benefits
would be redistributed

02:39:07.060 --> 02:39:08.690
if they are redistributed.

02:39:08.690 --> 02:39:13.250
And it seems as if, and this
is something the first panel

02:39:13.250 --> 02:39:18.010
touched on as well, like if
space is to become a place

02:39:18.010 --> 02:39:21.680
or a space where we can
experiment with different types

02:39:21.680 --> 02:39:27.460
of socialities where we can
finally hopefully acknowledge

02:39:27.460 --> 02:39:30.860
personhood in a different way
or just being in different ways,

02:39:30.860 --> 02:39:35.730
then it's going to also have
to ask questions of like, well,

02:39:35.730 --> 02:39:39.790
how do we value people?

02:39:39.790 --> 02:39:42.640
When people become
objects, then what kind

02:39:42.640 --> 02:39:45.250
of different manners
do we have in relating

02:39:45.250 --> 02:39:47.100
to them and using them?

02:39:47.100 --> 02:39:49.410
Who has all these different
powers and privileges

02:39:49.410 --> 02:39:51.690
that can decide those things?

02:39:51.690 --> 02:39:53.590
So, will space make us better?

02:39:53.590 --> 02:39:56.760
Hopefully, it will make us
actually ask these questions

02:39:56.760 --> 02:40:02.610
and maybe even put into
dialogue with public forums.

02:40:02.610 --> 02:40:05.270
And that's something
that I feel as if I need

02:40:05.270 --> 02:40:09.430
to do more exploration of, which
is like how often do we engage

02:40:09.430 --> 02:40:13.360
in public events like
this on these topics?

02:40:13.360 --> 02:40:16.490
Often, they're held in
either scientific conferences

02:40:16.490 --> 02:40:17.790
or academic conferences

02:40:17.790 --> 02:40:19.600
or at least those
spaces that I've been in.

02:40:19.600 --> 02:40:22.130
So how can we expand
these conversations

02:40:22.130 --> 02:40:24.800
so that it's not just
us talking to each other

02:40:24.800 --> 02:40:29.050
but actually talking about
what we imagine to be--

02:40:29.050 --> 02:40:32.020
space to be, and
how it could help us

02:40:32.020 --> 02:40:36.210
to grow beyond just catalyst

02:40:36.210 --> 02:40:40.010
or extractivist dialogues
and discourses?

02:40:40.010 --> 02:40:41.310
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: Yeah.

02:40:41.310 --> 02:40:43.600
I guess I'd be curious to
hear from the whole panel

02:40:43.600 --> 02:40:46.010
or whoever wants to take it.

02:40:46.010 --> 02:40:49.590
What do you think of the
rhetoric coming out of new space

02:40:49.590 --> 02:40:52.240
or some of the plans
that are thrown out there

02:40:52.240 --> 02:40:55.400
that are sometimes I think
out of the realm of fiction?

02:40:55.400 --> 02:40:59.310
But what do you think the effect
is of those ideas to things

02:40:59.310 --> 02:41:02.010
like the Tesla in space that
you mentioned, Nathalie,

02:41:02.010 --> 02:41:06.420
terraforming some
of these plans/ideas

02:41:06.420 --> 02:41:10.130
for these off-world
environments?

02:41:10.130 --> 02:41:12.380
&gt;&gt; Nathalie Cabrol: Well, you
know, I think at this point

02:41:12.380 --> 02:41:15.610
in time we're confronted
with two things.

02:41:15.610 --> 02:41:21.760
There is the, I do this thing
because I can, you know.

02:41:21.760 --> 02:41:23.750
And there is a little
bit of that

02:41:23.750 --> 02:41:25.440
and what's-- and this is great.

02:41:25.440 --> 02:41:29.190
Don't get me wrong, I
really do appreciate

02:41:29.190 --> 02:41:32.750
and I think this is a
great opportunity for us

02:41:32.750 --> 02:41:36.160
to have other people than
just elite and government.

02:41:36.160 --> 02:41:39.370
We're capable now of putting,
you know, assets in space

02:41:39.370 --> 02:41:43.650
and help the development
of technologies

02:41:43.650 --> 02:41:46.340
and maybe moving humans
around, et cetera.

02:41:46.340 --> 02:41:50.000
On the other hand, there is
also a little bit of catching

02:41:50.000 --> 02:41:54.010
up into, you know, what
it entails really to,

02:41:54.010 --> 02:41:56.170
and sorry to utilize
that word, colonize,

02:41:56.170 --> 02:42:00.720
but right now we are going
with that, to settle Mars

02:42:00.720 --> 02:42:03.650
and really what happens
when you are there.

02:42:03.650 --> 02:42:07.910
There is a little bit a
romantic vision of exploration

02:42:07.910 --> 02:42:11.630
where we are going to land on
Mars and, you know, we are going

02:42:11.630 --> 02:42:15.500
to send 100,000 people and they
will stay there and from there,

02:42:15.500 --> 02:42:18.160
we are going to become an
interplanetary species.

02:42:18.160 --> 02:42:22.340
Ultimately, this is going
to happen but it's not going

02:42:22.340 --> 02:42:25.510
to be easy, it's not--
it's going to be messy,

02:42:25.510 --> 02:42:28.920
and it is going to
humble us very much.

02:42:28.920 --> 02:42:31.080
And I think that there is
an understanding that going

02:42:31.080 --> 02:42:34.140
to Mars is not easy, it's hard.

02:42:34.140 --> 02:42:37.140
It's hard even to
land robots on Mars.

02:42:37.140 --> 02:42:42.730
It's hard to keep people alive
during the flight to Mars.

02:42:42.730 --> 02:42:45.290
The first thing that's going to
happen when they land on Mars,

02:42:45.290 --> 02:42:47.860
they are going to be
weakened by the travel.

02:42:47.860 --> 02:42:49.160
They won't be able to get

02:42:49.160 --> 02:42:51.750
out of the habitat
for at least a month.

02:42:51.750 --> 02:42:54.060
I think that the old studies
were showing something

02:42:54.060 --> 02:42:55.360
like that.

02:42:55.360 --> 02:42:58.800
But when you're an astronaut,
you have plenty of, you know,

02:42:58.800 --> 02:43:04.250
to keep you busy in your
spacecraft before you go out.

02:43:04.250 --> 02:43:07.050
But once you go out and
that's the main difference

02:43:07.050 --> 02:43:10.660
between the romantic
vision that is inherited

02:43:10.660 --> 02:43:14.730
from the exploration on Earth
and the reality of going

02:43:14.730 --> 02:43:18.320
to Mars is not even
being on the moon.

02:43:18.320 --> 02:43:20.920
When you are on the moon,
you look up at the sky

02:43:20.920 --> 02:43:23.450
and you see your planet is
right there, you communicate

02:43:23.450 --> 02:43:25.400
in three seconds, all right?

02:43:25.400 --> 02:43:28.810
And if something goes wrong,
well, you're back pretty fast.

02:43:28.810 --> 02:43:30.390
Once you are on Mars
and especially

02:43:30.390 --> 02:43:32.490
when somebody is going to
tell you, you are going there

02:43:32.490 --> 02:43:35.620
and you are staying there,
there is no ticket back.

02:43:35.620 --> 02:43:37.100
Then what happens?

02:43:37.100 --> 02:43:39.040
You're in this confined
environment.

02:43:39.040 --> 02:43:41.550
When you're on Earth
wherever you are,

02:43:41.550 --> 02:43:45.130
even in the most
lost place on earth,

02:43:45.130 --> 02:43:48.140
if you want to take a walk
because you are mad at the rest

02:43:48.140 --> 02:43:51.010
of the crew, you take
a walk, all right,

02:43:51.010 --> 02:43:52.350
you go out and you walk.

02:43:52.350 --> 02:43:55.750
And so on Mars, there is
a limited amount of time

02:43:55.750 --> 02:43:58.310
that you can spend
out per day just

02:43:58.310 --> 02:44:00.490
because of the radiation
environment.

02:44:00.490 --> 02:44:04.360
The people you are with, you
better go along with them

02:44:04.360 --> 02:44:07.410
because you are going to be with
them for a very, very long time.

02:44:07.410 --> 02:44:10.190
And you know, so the idea
of going back to Mars,

02:44:10.190 --> 02:44:13.890
colonizing Mars, I
think needs to be--

02:44:13.890 --> 02:44:18.610
excuse me, refrained
into what we know

02:44:18.610 --> 02:44:20.370
of Mars, the reality of Mars.

02:44:20.370 --> 02:44:24.210
I think there is a little
bit of romanticism right now

02:44:24.210 --> 02:44:30.610
that is infused into the vision
of some corporate companies.

02:44:30.610 --> 02:44:33.950
But at the same time, the
dream is the driver, you know,

02:44:33.950 --> 02:44:35.370
we first dream of things.

02:44:35.370 --> 02:44:38.550
It's just like a kid who
wants to be a firefighter,

02:44:38.550 --> 02:44:41.800
why they want to do that,
because there is a red truck,

02:44:41.800 --> 02:44:43.740
you know, and they are heroes,

02:44:43.740 --> 02:44:45.300
or in explorers, a
little bit of that.

02:44:45.300 --> 02:44:47.860
There is no red truck but if
you survive, if you made it,

02:44:47.860 --> 02:44:50.050
you come back, you've
discovered something new.

02:44:50.050 --> 02:44:53.540
And then as the kid grows
up, they need that--

02:44:53.540 --> 02:44:56.400
you know, they learn that
they need to have skills

02:44:56.400 --> 02:44:57.700
and they need to, you know,

02:44:57.700 --> 02:44:59.460
being a firefighter is
not only the red track.

02:44:59.460 --> 02:45:01.820
And this is going to
be the same thing here

02:45:01.820 --> 02:45:05.640
with the romantic vision of
exploration of a planet that is

02:45:05.640 --> 02:45:09.030
so far away that you cannot
just take the next cab

02:45:09.030 --> 02:45:10.330
and come back home.

02:45:10.330 --> 02:45:13.050
So, for me, this is what
I-- you know, right now,

02:45:13.050 --> 02:45:14.380
this is a little
bit of the danger

02:45:14.380 --> 02:45:17.390
because of the romantic
approach to exploration.

02:45:17.390 --> 02:45:18.740
There are steps that are taken

02:45:18.740 --> 02:45:21.840
that might not be too
wise or too smart.

02:45:21.840 --> 02:45:25.340
But if we work together, I
think there is a great deal

02:45:25.340 --> 02:45:27.880
of good things that can
come up with the merging

02:45:27.880 --> 02:45:32.830
of the experience that NASA
or ESA or other agencies have

02:45:32.830 --> 02:45:38.360
with the-- we can do type of
approach of corporate companies.

02:45:39.490 --> 02:45:41.940
&gt;&gt; Bobak Ferdowsi: I mean, I--
obviously I love new space.

02:45:41.940 --> 02:45:44.370
It enables us to do a ton of
things that we weren't able

02:45:44.370 --> 02:45:47.770
to do, you know, 10 years
ago, which is great.

02:45:47.770 --> 02:45:50.900
I think the big concern and
sort of what you're getting on,

02:45:50.900 --> 02:45:52.760
right, which is the narrative
and sort of being seen

02:45:52.760 --> 02:45:56.290
as a very romantic, all these
habitats and these, you know,

02:45:56.290 --> 02:46:00.900
various-- when we walked by the
botany building on the way here

02:46:00.900 --> 02:46:04.190
and I kind of imagined like that
could be like a Mars settlement,

02:46:04.190 --> 02:46:05.930
right, with the glass
and I'm look out

02:46:05.930 --> 02:46:10.070
and I got plants growing
inside, making air for me.

02:46:10.070 --> 02:46:12.520
But I do think it's some sort
of-- yeah, and to be fair,

02:46:12.520 --> 02:46:15.300
right, I mean my own institution
is sometimes guilty of this,

02:46:15.300 --> 02:46:19.100
the romanticized vision of,
you know, astronauts walking

02:46:19.100 --> 02:46:21.610
on the surface of Mars
for the first time.

02:46:21.610 --> 02:46:23.840
The challenge is real.

02:46:23.840 --> 02:46:26.240
I think that the big concern
with that narrative is always

02:46:26.240 --> 02:46:28.260
that if you don't want--
if you don't need it,

02:46:28.260 --> 02:46:31.430
you get discouraged which
then sets back the legitimate,

02:46:31.430 --> 02:46:33.270
all the stuff that
we're trying to do,

02:46:33.270 --> 02:46:36.810
but also the setting
of that precedent.

02:46:36.810 --> 02:46:38.620
And it was kind of, you
know, I mentioned earlier

02:46:38.620 --> 02:46:40.890
where like people talk about
the time for doing things

02:46:40.890 --> 02:46:43.730
and of course I think if so many
people including myself, right,

02:46:43.730 --> 02:46:46.790
the time is always now because
I'm only going to be alive for,

02:46:46.790 --> 02:46:49.060
you know, any years
more and I want

02:46:49.060 --> 02:46:51.590
to discover life somewhere
else in my lifetime.

02:46:51.590 --> 02:46:53.520
I want to see people
do certain things.

02:46:53.520 --> 02:46:55.460
I want to accomplish
certain things.

02:46:55.460 --> 02:46:58.560
And so it's always this-- And
part of that is because I grew

02:46:58.560 --> 02:47:01.400
up on a vision of, oh,
these are achievable things

02:47:01.400 --> 02:47:04.710
in my lifetime, so therefore
I want to achieve them.

02:47:04.710 --> 02:47:07.050
And I think that's part of
the issue with the narrative

02:47:07.050 --> 02:47:11.970
of this, you know, let's expand
to Mars kind of thing which is--

02:47:11.970 --> 02:47:15.260
again, if we sell everybody
on a very romantic narrative

02:47:15.260 --> 02:47:20.800
and we either don't deliver
or even if we do, it just sort

02:47:20.800 --> 02:47:24.330
of sets us up to have to do
these things and not necessarily

02:47:24.330 --> 02:47:28.000
in the-- and I don't want to
say it like in a calculating way

02:47:28.000 --> 02:47:30.150
but in a sort of
methodical systematic way

02:47:30.150 --> 02:47:32.620
where we really appreciate
what we're doing.

02:47:32.620 --> 02:47:35.380
And, you know, someone
like myself,

02:47:35.380 --> 02:47:37.640
the dream is very
much alive with space.

02:47:37.640 --> 02:47:38.940
I love the challenge of it.

02:47:38.940 --> 02:47:40.240
So honestly, at the end
of the day, if I don't get

02:47:40.240 --> 02:47:42.830
to do all these things, I'm
going to be happy because it's--

02:47:42.830 --> 02:47:45.120
the fun is in trying to do it.

02:47:45.120 --> 02:47:47.540
And some-- you know, most of the
time, when we try to succeed--

02:47:47.540 --> 02:47:48.840
I mean, we are trying
to succeed,

02:47:48.840 --> 02:47:50.150
most of the time, we succeed.

02:47:50.150 --> 02:47:53.720
But if there wasn't a little
bit of a gamble or a risk to it,

02:47:53.720 --> 02:47:55.810
it would certainly be
a lot less exciting.

02:47:55.810 --> 02:47:58.510
But I think, right, it's one of
the we're really need to find,

02:47:58.510 --> 02:48:04.330
is what is the balance of
storytelling that we strike

02:48:04.330 --> 02:48:07.280
between encouraging
people to sort of wants

02:48:07.280 --> 02:48:11.040
to tackle these seemingly
insurmountable challenges and,

02:48:11.040 --> 02:48:13.060
you know, dream big and
do certain, you know,

02:48:13.060 --> 02:48:16.630
things and how do we do that
in a way that's constructive

02:48:16.630 --> 02:48:17.930
for society, right?

02:48:17.930 --> 02:48:20.150
Is it focusing in
on different areas?

02:48:20.150 --> 02:48:22.200
Is it telling a story
that is more

02:48:22.200 --> 02:48:25.110
about the journey than the end?

02:48:25.110 --> 02:48:27.100
You know, I don't have
an answer for that,

02:48:27.100 --> 02:48:29.710
but I think that's kind of one
other things that are, you know,

02:48:29.710 --> 02:48:32.080
as you were talking,
it sort of reminded me.

02:48:32.080 --> 02:48:34.730
And again, I'm very optimistic

02:48:34.730 --> 02:48:36.520
about the work that's
being done.

02:48:36.520 --> 02:48:38.160
I think that's incredible stuff.

02:48:38.160 --> 02:48:43.830
But I am concerned about
the subdivision of it all,

02:48:43.830 --> 02:48:46.550
or sort of the salesmanship
of it all.

02:48:47.980 --> 02:48:49.710
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: Nathalie,
do you have something--

02:48:49.710 --> 02:48:51.010
&gt;&gt; Nathalie Cabrol: Yeah,
just to add something.

02:48:51.010 --> 02:48:54.160
I think that with
becoming interplanetary,

02:48:54.160 --> 02:48:59.200
there is something that, you
know, that was not present for--

02:48:59.200 --> 02:49:01.540
in the exploration of our
own planet, and which is

02:49:01.540 --> 02:49:03.730
that now you are
adding a new world.

02:49:03.730 --> 02:49:06.110
And it's not a new planet Earth.

02:49:06.110 --> 02:49:07.960
We're not starting with that.

02:49:07.960 --> 02:49:09.260
We're starting with a world

02:49:09.260 --> 02:49:11.500
that is very hostile
in the first place.

02:49:11.500 --> 02:49:14.680
And I think this is-- when
you think about implications,

02:49:14.680 --> 02:49:15.990
you have to think at two levels.

02:49:15.990 --> 02:49:19.550
So the first implication
is, OK, how is this going

02:49:19.550 --> 02:49:23.550
to serve society as a whole, you
know, here and somewhere else?

02:49:23.550 --> 02:49:26.330
But there is also, you
know, what's happening

02:49:26.330 --> 02:49:29.620
on this humankind on Mars?

02:49:29.620 --> 02:49:31.580
What are they becoming,

02:49:31.580 --> 02:49:33.340
especially if they
are not coming back?

02:49:33.340 --> 02:49:35.900
So we have to-- You
know, maybe this is

02:49:35.900 --> 02:49:38.190
where the big difference
is between exploration here

02:49:38.190 --> 02:49:41.210
on Earth and what has happened
with the exploration of Mars,

02:49:41.210 --> 02:49:45.070
is that when you are on Mars,
you are completely on your own,

02:49:45.070 --> 02:49:46.400
which you were somewhere,
you know,

02:49:46.400 --> 02:49:49.040
on Earth as well
and in some places.

02:49:49.040 --> 02:49:51.790
But here, you are
in an environment

02:49:51.790 --> 02:49:54.650
that you were not
the master of it.

02:49:54.650 --> 02:49:58.550
The environment is going to
dominate you for very long time.

02:49:58.550 --> 02:50:00.520
And you have to count
on each other.

02:50:00.520 --> 02:50:02.830
You have to use each
other smart.

02:50:02.830 --> 02:50:04.660
It's the big equalizer, yeah,

02:50:04.660 --> 02:50:07.550
the environment will
completely dominate you

02:50:07.550 --> 02:50:09.070
for hundreds of times.

02:50:09.070 --> 02:50:11.640
And by the way, those
beautiful spheres that you see,

02:50:11.640 --> 02:50:14.610
you know as much as I
do how many, you know,

02:50:14.610 --> 02:50:16.300
asteroids are falling
at the surface

02:50:16.300 --> 02:50:18.000
of Mars every single year.

02:50:18.000 --> 02:50:21.430
So we better be under the
surface for quite some time.

02:50:21.430 --> 02:50:25.040
But what I'm saying
is that unlike Earth,

02:50:25.040 --> 02:50:28.750
you just cannot take a walk
and find the next spring,

02:50:28.750 --> 02:50:32.220
the next cascade and, you
know, leave off and ride away.

02:50:32.220 --> 02:50:34.330
You're going to have
to count on each other.

02:50:34.330 --> 02:50:38.280
You have to-- So this is where
maybe differences between people

02:50:38.280 --> 02:50:40.030
and race and gender,
et cetera is going

02:50:40.030 --> 02:50:43.660
to be maybe a little less
important, because well,

02:50:43.660 --> 02:50:46.260
you are one against
the environment.

02:50:46.260 --> 02:50:47.560
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz:
I think I'm--

02:50:47.560 --> 02:50:50.050
I actually wanted to spend
the last couple of moments

02:50:50.050 --> 02:50:54.770
of our panel here talking about
Mars as a physical environment

02:50:54.770 --> 02:50:59.780
because I think, you know, often
we think of ourselves as masters

02:50:59.780 --> 02:51:02.400
of our environment,
which we objectively

02:51:02.400 --> 02:51:04.930
on this planet are clearly not.

02:51:04.930 --> 02:51:08.780
And also, you know, the
relationship of the environment

02:51:08.780 --> 02:51:10.750
as being something
we can or should try

02:51:10.750 --> 02:51:15.240
to control I think is not
shared by every culture.

02:51:15.240 --> 02:51:17.240
You know, one of the
things that came up,

02:51:17.240 --> 02:51:20.660
and since I haven't specifically
mention it in this panel,

02:51:20.660 --> 02:51:23.890
all of us where co-creators of
the things that we're talking

02:51:23.890 --> 02:51:25.930
about here, so we did
these pre-event calls.

02:51:25.930 --> 02:51:28.180
And one of the things
you brought up, Margaret,

02:51:28.180 --> 02:51:31.720
was environmental personhood
and some of the ways

02:51:31.720 --> 02:51:35.950
in which indigenous cultures
have thought of environments

02:51:35.950 --> 02:51:39.220
but also engaged with the
level system and with policy,

02:51:39.220 --> 02:51:42.340
so maybe if you could
speak to that.

02:51:42.340 --> 02:51:43.640
&gt;&gt; Margaret Huettl: Yeah.

02:51:43.640 --> 02:51:48.100
So, I was thinking of an
example from New Zealand

02:51:48.100 --> 02:51:51.380
where the indigenous
people there were able

02:51:51.380 --> 02:51:53.420
to get legal personhood
protections

02:51:53.420 --> 02:51:57.600
for a particular river,
so that any violations

02:51:57.600 --> 02:52:03.410
of the river are the same as
violations of like a human body,

02:52:03.410 --> 02:52:06.090
and the treat-- you know,
they have legal recourse

02:52:06.090 --> 02:52:11.550
to environmental damage done
to this like physical entity

02:52:11.550 --> 02:52:16.060
that represents their
relationship with this place.

02:52:16.060 --> 02:52:20.360
So that's one way that
indigenous people have,

02:52:20.360 --> 02:52:24.550
you know, used the legal
system both to their advantage

02:52:24.550 --> 02:52:27.020
and to the advantage of
the environment, right?

02:52:27.020 --> 02:52:30.800
I know India has also given
personhood status to at least

02:52:30.800 --> 02:52:34.150
to two of its rivers in
order to fight pollution.

02:52:34.150 --> 02:52:37.200
And so, you know, for me,
the question is there's a--

02:52:37.200 --> 02:52:43.350
if there isn't-- like there's
not necessarily other people,

02:52:43.350 --> 02:52:45.550
right, out on Mars?

02:52:45.550 --> 02:52:49.350
But does Mars, right, as
an entity have a same right

02:52:49.350 --> 02:52:52.350
to some sort of status,
you know,

02:52:52.350 --> 02:52:55.190
equivalent to the
personhood status

02:52:55.190 --> 02:52:58.880
that this river in
New Zealand has?

02:52:58.880 --> 02:53:00.180
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: Yeah.

02:53:00.180 --> 02:53:04.700
And this also came up in our
call in the sense of I think one

02:53:04.700 --> 02:53:07.700
of the ways I hear people
sometimes split the difference,

02:53:07.700 --> 02:53:11.580
right, is well, you know,
we'll be able to do whatever

02:53:11.580 --> 02:53:14.950
or industry can do whatever to
an environment after we're sure

02:53:14.950 --> 02:53:17.540
that life is not there.

02:53:17.540 --> 02:53:24.980
And I don't know when that could
possibly ever actually happen.

02:53:24.980 --> 02:53:28.540
Yeah. So, what are-- And I'll
throw this out to the panel

02:53:28.540 --> 02:53:31.990
as a whole just as a parting
thought, what are your thoughts

02:53:31.990 --> 02:53:36.130
about how we should conceive
of Mars as an environment

02:53:36.130 --> 02:53:39.620
or even why we study
other planets?

02:53:39.620 --> 02:53:43.980
And maybe I'll give
that to you first, Dana.

02:53:43.980 --> 02:53:47.900
&gt;&gt; Dana Burton: So, a couple
of kind of branching thoughts

02:53:47.900 --> 02:53:51.720
with this is that Mars
as an environment is

02:53:51.720 --> 02:53:54.340
as much an environment
here on Earth.

02:53:54.340 --> 02:53:57.650
And in preparing to go
to Mars, there are lots

02:53:57.650 --> 02:54:02.470
of different strategies and
protocols and programs being put

02:54:02.470 --> 02:54:05.410
into effect that are
changing the landscape.

02:54:05.410 --> 02:54:09.590
So, just thinking of new
space, right, they're trying

02:54:09.590 --> 02:54:13.970
to create different types of
rockets, so reusable rockets

02:54:13.970 --> 02:54:16.940
which could technically
land in different places

02:54:16.940 --> 02:54:20.460
and don't necessarily have to
be launched from certain places,

02:54:20.460 --> 02:54:24.450
I don't know, the science stuff,
I could move to these guys.

02:54:24.450 --> 02:54:26.230
But just taking into
consideration

02:54:26.230 --> 02:54:28.430
like what places are we
then changing in order

02:54:28.430 --> 02:54:31.990
to fulfill these goals
of space exploration?

02:54:31.990 --> 02:54:33.740
So, if we're thinking
about Mars and we need

02:54:33.740 --> 02:54:37.690
to understand constables of life
or, you know, is it organic,

02:54:37.690 --> 02:54:42.650
is it carbon-base, again the
science, we also have to think

02:54:42.650 --> 02:54:45.320
about what kind of tests are
we performing on entities

02:54:45.320 --> 02:54:48.000
and bodies here in
order to understand

02:54:48.000 --> 02:54:49.880
that type of environment.

02:54:49.880 --> 02:54:51.930
So, I think these
larger questions

02:54:51.930 --> 02:54:54.740
of like the Mars environment
are as much a reflection

02:54:54.740 --> 02:54:57.780
of how we've treated the
environment here on Earth.

02:54:57.780 --> 02:55:00.760
And I think that would-- as
a parting thought would be

02:55:00.760 --> 02:55:06.350
to really take a good reflection
of how our search for knowledge

02:55:06.350 --> 02:55:11.950
and our understandings of life
are impacting how we work with

02:55:11.950 --> 02:55:14.900
and see life here and
I wonder if we could--

02:55:14.900 --> 02:55:17.950
you know, maybe that would be a
point of doing something better,

02:55:17.950 --> 02:55:23.700
is incorporating a more
perspective that is respectful

02:55:23.700 --> 02:55:28.230
and incorporates-- or is
collaborative with difference

02:55:28.230 --> 02:55:31.970
and understands difference
better.

02:55:31.970 --> 02:55:40.720
&gt;&gt; Nathalie Cabrol: I'm going to
take a slightly different take

02:55:40.720 --> 02:55:43.070
at this obviously and I
don't have your expertise

02:55:43.070 --> 02:55:47.610
and I'm dealing with the aspects
of, well, yeah, carbon-based

02:55:47.610 --> 02:55:49.640
and environment and
things like that.

02:55:49.640 --> 02:55:52.290
So I think that we are
doing our homework,

02:55:52.290 --> 02:55:54.660
astrobiology is doing its
homework right now in trying

02:55:54.660 --> 02:55:56.820
to figure out what kind of
environment and what kind

02:55:56.820 --> 02:55:58.860
of coevolusion Mars
could have been.

02:55:58.860 --> 02:56:01.200
Because if you're looking
for a life on a planet,

02:56:01.200 --> 02:56:03.150
you have to think about
coevolusion, you have to think

02:56:03.150 --> 02:56:04.810
of Mars as a biosphere.

02:56:04.810 --> 02:56:07.810
And that goes back a
little bit to the personhood

02:56:07.810 --> 02:56:12.050
that you are mentioning that
is not exactly the same thing.

02:56:12.050 --> 02:56:15.160
I know exact-- I think I
understand very well what's

02:56:15.160 --> 02:56:17.900
happening here where you're
giving, you know, legal rights

02:56:17.900 --> 02:56:20.430
to a planet, to a
river, et cetera.

02:56:20.430 --> 02:56:23.910
But in terms of environment
where you are recognizing

02:56:23.910 --> 02:56:28.170
that we are part of a
biosphere, we are not outside

02:56:28.170 --> 02:56:30.630
of a biosphere, we
are part of a system,

02:56:30.630 --> 02:56:32.570
and then if you are
hurting that system,

02:56:32.570 --> 02:56:34.560
you are hurting the
entire biosphere.

02:56:34.560 --> 02:56:37.510
Then there is a little bit of
that too, there is a respect

02:56:37.510 --> 02:56:38.810
of the system you are part of.

02:56:38.810 --> 02:56:41.170
I think that what we
are doing is trying

02:56:41.170 --> 02:56:42.870
to put ourselves
outside of that.

02:56:42.870 --> 02:56:45.370
We're seeing this with the
environmental change right now.

02:56:45.370 --> 02:56:50.150
But to go back to your question,
as in astrobiology going

02:56:50.150 --> 02:56:52.500
to extreme environments
and looking

02:56:52.500 --> 02:56:55.210
at what we think could be
the most evolved type of life

02:56:55.210 --> 02:56:57.980
that could be on Mars right now,
which basically are microbes

02:56:57.980 --> 02:56:59.880
because there's not
enough energy

02:56:59.880 --> 02:57:04.350
to just sustain complex
life on Mars,

02:57:04.350 --> 02:57:09.390
I'm looking at what these
microbes are in an environment

02:57:09.390 --> 02:57:14.230
that is very relevant to what
Mars was 3.5 billion years ago.

02:57:14.230 --> 02:57:16.970
And they are telling me
something very profound

02:57:16.970 --> 02:57:22.100
about humans, and which is that
in those places where we go,

02:57:22.100 --> 02:57:25.760
the earliest organism we see
are blue and green algae.

02:57:25.760 --> 02:57:31.430
And you see them and they
can't thrive in radiation,

02:57:31.430 --> 02:57:34.540
in places where radiation
is extremely strong,

02:57:34.540 --> 02:57:37.900
in places that are a little
bit cold where there is a lot

02:57:37.900 --> 02:57:39.790
of aridity, et cetera,
et cetera.

02:57:39.790 --> 02:57:42.780
Fundamentally, they are the same

02:57:42.780 --> 02:57:44.410
but they become a
little different.

02:57:44.410 --> 02:57:45.950
They are developing
different pigment.

02:57:45.950 --> 02:57:49.910
They are developing different
capabilities to adapt

02:57:49.910 --> 02:57:51.880
because of the place
they are at.

02:57:51.880 --> 02:57:54.270
And so this is telling
me about, you know,

02:57:54.270 --> 02:57:56.930
something about our humanity,

02:57:56.930 --> 02:57:59.370
our new evolution,
we are adaptable.

02:57:59.370 --> 02:58:03.260
We are the product of our
environment of our history.

02:58:03.260 --> 02:58:08.300
Going back to Mars, I am
wondering if by going to a place

02:58:08.300 --> 02:58:10.980
that is environmentally
completely different is going

02:58:10.980 --> 02:58:14.530
to help us finally figure
out what it means to be human

02:58:14.530 --> 02:58:17.650
when you are removed from
your planet of origin.

02:58:17.650 --> 02:58:20.520
And when you are getting, you
know, confronted to something

02:58:20.520 --> 02:58:24.260
that is completely different,
you finally all of a sudden,

02:58:24.260 --> 02:58:28.970
you know, what is-- what it
means to be human is going to,

02:58:28.970 --> 02:58:32.220
you know, get to the surface but
being on another planet then all

02:58:32.220 --> 02:58:37.120
of a sudden you will lose your
humanity what was making you

02:58:37.120 --> 02:58:38.420
human in the first place.

02:58:38.420 --> 02:58:42.920
So it's an interesting paradox
that exploration of environment

02:58:42.920 --> 02:58:45.050
and the Martian environment
could bring

02:58:45.050 --> 02:58:47.330
to humans finally
discover of who they are.

02:58:47.330 --> 02:58:50.160
What it means to be us.

