03:40:40.730 --> 03:40:43.230
So, the overview of
this particular panel

03:40:43.230 --> 03:40:46.960
if you understand the program
is called alternative futurism.

03:40:46.960 --> 03:40:49.810
And this of-- as we
should probably be evident

03:40:49.810 --> 03:40:53.480
of by now is centered on science
fiction in the imagination.

03:40:53.480 --> 03:40:56.570
It has really has a power
to inspire and instruct us

03:40:56.570 --> 03:40:58.220
as we invention the future.

03:40:58.220 --> 03:41:02.190
But it's also long bit a vehicle
for myths of Manifest Destiny.

03:41:02.190 --> 03:41:05.060
And so, we wanted to start today
by talking about the view points

03:41:05.060 --> 03:41:08.140
of humanities future that
are alternative to some

03:41:08.140 --> 03:41:10.610
of these mainstream narratives

03:41:10.610 --> 03:41:12.900
and how we might
conceptualize life off world

03:41:12.900 --> 03:41:14.800
in radically different ways.

03:41:14.800 --> 03:41:16.940
And so, I'm going to
start by throwing this

03:41:16.940 --> 03:41:20.220
out to the entire panel probably
the central concern that came

03:41:20.220 --> 03:41:24.840
up in our pre-event call
which is alternative to what?

03:41:24.840 --> 03:41:27.140
So, if we could take a moment
to talk about distinctions

03:41:27.140 --> 03:41:30.430
between kinds of science
fiction and how they interface

03:41:30.430 --> 03:41:36.370
with your work to whoever
wants to take it first.

03:41:36.370 --> 03:41:38.880
&gt;&gt; Hi everyone, I'm
so happy to be here.

03:41:38.880 --> 03:41:43.270
So, one of the things that
comes up for me in response

03:41:43.270 --> 03:41:45.460
to that question is I think

03:41:45.460 --> 03:41:48.590
about Bell Hooks
centering the margins.

03:41:48.590 --> 03:41:53.050
I also think about some
problems as I continue to teach

03:41:53.050 --> 03:41:56.780
that her text in
that particular one.

03:41:56.780 --> 03:42:00.970
The problems that I'm
beginning to have around the--

03:42:00.970 --> 03:42:07.680
even the term margin, and so
that's something where I think

03:42:07.680 --> 03:42:11.250
about what does that mean to be
centered or to center oneself,

03:42:11.250 --> 03:42:15.350
and what does it mean
to claim the margin

03:42:15.350 --> 03:42:18.410
or to reject that terminology?

03:42:18.410 --> 03:42:22.490
And so, for myself, I
really approach Afrofuturism

03:42:22.490 --> 03:42:28.150
and the teaching of it as a
kind of shape shifters art.

03:42:28.150 --> 03:42:31.210
And I think that that is also
something that draws people

03:42:31.210 --> 03:42:34.700
and students in particular
to my classes and to

03:42:34.700 --> 03:42:39.970
that particular approach, where
it offers a kind of inclusivity

03:42:39.970 --> 03:42:42.240
and space for people
who are coming

03:42:42.240 --> 03:42:46.960
from many different
backgrounds and ways of being

03:42:46.960 --> 03:42:52.010
and seeing themselves an
identity to enter into that

03:42:52.010 --> 03:42:56.410
and see it as a kind of radical
space for creative production.

03:42:58.390 --> 03:42:59.690
&gt;&gt; Enongo Lumumba-Kasongo:
Thank you.

03:42:59.690 --> 03:43:06.930
I think there are a few kind of
cultural myths that Afrofuturism

03:43:06.930 --> 03:43:11.360
as some of the related works
they're trying to reject

03:43:11.360 --> 03:43:13.870
and specifically in regards
to science and technology,

03:43:13.870 --> 03:43:17.230
I think one of the most
prominent ones is that,

03:43:17.230 --> 03:43:21.890
you know, black folks are like
a modern outside of modernity

03:43:21.890 --> 03:43:25.540
that they exist in some sort
of primitive or above or beyond

03:43:25.540 --> 03:43:30.850
or like extrapolated away
from technology and science.

03:43:30.850 --> 03:43:33.790
And then the other thing
that I've encountered a lot

03:43:33.790 --> 03:43:37.410
in regards to my work is this
idea of being an anomaly.

03:43:37.410 --> 03:43:40.690
I found that when I perform,

03:43:40.690 --> 03:43:42.150
a lot of white folks
will approach me

03:43:42.150 --> 03:43:44.090
as though I'm an
anomaly and I'm saying--

03:43:44.090 --> 03:43:46.330
and a big part of what
I want to do is say--

03:43:46.330 --> 03:43:49.600
is express that this is
the perspective that a lot

03:43:49.600 --> 03:43:53.550
of black folks have, right,
that I'm not a unicorn,

03:43:53.550 --> 03:43:57.320
and so I think Afrofuturism
has helped me to figure out how

03:43:57.320 --> 03:43:59.230
to kind of work through
that, but that's one

03:43:59.230 --> 03:44:01.260
of the myths I think that
there can only be one

03:44:01.260 --> 03:44:05.010
or that there's-- we represent
one particular perspective

03:44:05.010 --> 03:44:14.180
or one group, when that's
not necessarily the case.

03:44:14.180 --> 03:44:15.480
&gt;&gt; Willi Lemper: Test.

03:44:15.480 --> 03:44:17.560
We're absolutely thinking on
what you said about Bell Hooks.

03:44:17.560 --> 03:44:19.060
I've been thinking a
lot about this book

03:44:19.060 --> 03:44:22.560
by Ngugi wa Thiong'o,
"Moving the Center".

03:44:22.560 --> 03:44:25.000
And similar to what's come
up a lot today about who's

03:44:25.000 --> 03:44:28.740
in the center in a variety
of ways and who's not

03:44:28.740 --> 03:44:30.040
in the center, who's
at the margin,

03:44:30.040 --> 03:44:34.020
but also who's just not
there at all, who's absent.

03:44:34.020 --> 03:44:37.320
And that's harder to see
because it's not present

03:44:37.320 --> 03:44:39.920
and requires a critical eye.

03:44:39.920 --> 03:44:43.460
Another quote that comes
to mind that was written

03:44:43.460 --> 03:44:47.770
by Peter Gourevitch,
about the Rwandan genocide

03:44:47.770 --> 03:44:51.240
that I come back to a lot
around this question is

03:44:51.240 --> 03:44:53.520
that power largely
consist in the ability

03:44:53.520 --> 03:44:57.940
to make others inhabit your
story of their reality.

03:44:57.940 --> 03:45:02.240
I think that's powerful
and specially this panel,

03:45:02.240 --> 03:45:04.860
I think there is this
connection between creative work

03:45:04.860 --> 03:45:06.920
and scholarship, and there's
something that happens

03:45:06.920 --> 03:45:09.600
in that space that
doesn't happen

03:45:09.600 --> 03:45:12.550
in purely journal
articles alone.

03:45:12.550 --> 03:45:15.810
And that imagining the future
is very much about the image

03:45:15.810 --> 03:45:18.750
or some sort of engagement
that's not one way

03:45:18.750 --> 03:45:22.750
and through this very old
colonial structure is not

03:45:22.750 --> 03:45:24.210
as essential.

03:45:24.210 --> 03:45:26.510
Yeah.

03:45:27.880 --> 03:45:29.180
&gt;&gt; Ytasha L. Womack: Hi.

03:45:29.180 --> 03:45:30.480
This is so exciting.

03:45:30.480 --> 03:45:32.710
I guess when I think about--

03:45:32.710 --> 03:45:36.200
whenever I talk about
Afrofuturism,

03:45:36.200 --> 03:45:41.010
I like to give sort of a ground
floor reference definition

03:45:41.010 --> 03:45:42.310
for it.

03:45:42.310 --> 03:45:45.880
One of the definitions I
often you don't use is to say

03:45:45.880 --> 03:45:48.160
that it's a way of
looking at their future

03:45:48.160 --> 03:45:52.530
or ultimate realities, but
through a black cultural ends.

03:45:52.530 --> 03:45:56.030
And then I have to define black,
you know, and say that that's,

03:45:56.030 --> 03:45:58.630
you know, people of the
African continent and, you know,

03:45:58.630 --> 03:46:01.240
people of the African Diaspora.

03:46:01.240 --> 03:46:05.560
And then I also say that it
intersects the imagination,

03:46:05.560 --> 03:46:08.070
technology, mysticism.

03:46:08.070 --> 03:46:12.090
I highlight mysticism,
because that separates it

03:46:12.090 --> 03:46:14.900
from the way we usually
talk about science fiction.

03:46:14.900 --> 03:46:19.840
And that it obviously
intersects black culture,

03:46:19.840 --> 03:46:24.290
but that there is a lot of
appreciation for the concept

03:46:24.290 --> 03:46:27.570
of the divine feminine,
a lot of women creators,

03:46:27.570 --> 03:46:31.570
but also this idea
of valuing intuition

03:46:31.570 --> 03:46:37.350
or the emotions is being a
valued space for information.

03:46:37.350 --> 03:46:40.330
Intuition is a valued space
for information in the same way

03:46:40.330 --> 03:46:43.590
that logic is and looking
at that as a balance.

03:46:43.590 --> 03:46:45.940
So, if you take something
like the oak, and you think

03:46:45.940 --> 03:46:49.920
about masculinity and femininity
in sort of these larger not

03:46:49.920 --> 03:46:54.280
in a binary space per se but
just sort of this concept

03:46:54.280 --> 03:46:57.540
that there are ideas we both
connect with and that express,

03:46:57.540 --> 03:47:00.040
you know, very much
these different ways

03:47:00.040 --> 03:47:02.060
that we can process information,

03:47:02.060 --> 03:47:04.060
and come to understand
ourselves.

03:47:04.060 --> 03:47:06.390
And then, you know, this
relationship with time,

03:47:06.390 --> 03:47:10.640
you know, with the future
and the past and the present,

03:47:10.640 --> 03:47:12.610
being various expressions
of what

03:47:12.610 --> 03:47:14.850
and these are all
concepts you see coming

03:47:14.850 --> 03:47:17.940
out of the Afrofuturism which
also overlap in a lot of ways

03:47:17.940 --> 03:47:19.570
with indigenous futurism.

03:47:19.570 --> 03:47:24.090
But what is interesting about
Afrofuturism which is different

03:47:24.090 --> 03:47:26.090
from how we kind of
talk about this sci-fi,

03:47:26.090 --> 03:47:28.690
this is why the whole
alternative futurism gets really

03:47:28.690 --> 03:47:31.940
interesting, Afrofuturism
at least acknowledges

03:47:31.940 --> 03:47:35.570
that it's a perspective, right?

03:47:35.570 --> 03:47:38.800
And so, we start talking
about this idea of,

03:47:38.800 --> 03:47:42.570
oh science fiction, and then
there is this general assumption

03:47:42.570 --> 03:47:45.080
that this is the way, right?

03:47:45.080 --> 03:47:46.950
And that there's
one approach to it,

03:47:46.950 --> 03:47:50.680
and a lot of times
it's very nationalistic

03:47:50.680 --> 03:47:53.950
or militaristic and, you know,
it might explore various things.

03:47:53.950 --> 03:47:56.740
So, I mean, I've been on
a science fiction panels

03:47:56.740 --> 03:47:58.310
and I just have to say,
"Look, I don't speak

03:47:58.310 --> 03:48:00.280
from a marginalized space."

03:48:00.280 --> 03:48:01.580
I don't know what that is.

03:48:01.580 --> 03:48:02.880
That's not my background.

03:48:02.880 --> 03:48:05.370
That's not my perspective,
and there was gasp.

03:48:05.370 --> 03:48:08.780
Like, oh my goodness, but that's
what you're here to inform us

03:48:08.780 --> 03:48:15.120
of in a psychology sorry, you
know, because I don't relate

03:48:15.120 --> 03:48:17.060
to that concept, right?

03:48:17.060 --> 03:48:19.720
And so generally
speaking, you know,

03:48:19.720 --> 03:48:23.980
this is the point I'm talking
about these perspectives is

03:48:23.980 --> 03:48:28.030
to integrate and share and look
at how we can integrate them,

03:48:28.030 --> 03:48:30.420
how we can overlap them and
how we can pull the best

03:48:30.420 --> 03:48:33.030
so you create this sort
of societies in the world

03:48:33.030 --> 03:48:36.270
that makes the most
sense for us.

03:48:36.270 --> 03:48:38.330
&gt;&gt; D. Denenge Duyst-Akpem:
I wanted to kind of respond

03:48:38.330 --> 03:48:41.260
and just, you know, affirm
what you said in terms

03:48:41.260 --> 03:48:45.430
of to throwing this idea of
the black object and the need

03:48:45.430 --> 03:48:49.570
that people have where the
largest societies seems to have

03:48:49.570 --> 03:48:53.710
for depictions of
black objection.

03:48:53.710 --> 03:48:56.570
And so that, you know,
this idea that no,

03:48:56.570 --> 03:48:58.400
I'm not speaking from a margin.

03:48:58.400 --> 03:49:01.930
I'm-- you know, and I'm
speaking from a point of joy,

03:49:01.930 --> 03:49:07.320
of radical joy, which is
something that Wanuri Kahiu,

03:49:07.320 --> 03:49:11.950
a filmmaker who did Pumzi,
the film and many others,

03:49:11.950 --> 03:49:15.420
and Rafiki which is now
showing in Kenya, it was banned

03:49:15.420 --> 03:49:19.120
and now it's currently
showing which is awesome.

03:49:19.120 --> 03:49:25.410
But, you know, thinking about
depictions and how we are,

03:49:25.410 --> 03:49:29.490
you know, there's a sort of
consumption of black object.

03:49:29.490 --> 03:49:33.710
And so, the Afrofuturism
as a genre is the space

03:49:33.710 --> 03:49:38.610
where we can vary directly,
you know, go up against

03:49:38.610 --> 03:49:40.820
that in a sense, you
know, at the same time,

03:49:40.820 --> 03:49:45.700
I also reject the idea and this
is connected with, you know,

03:49:45.700 --> 03:49:50.070
in terms of definitions that
Afrofuturism is a response

03:49:50.070 --> 03:49:55.990
to whiteness in the same way
that black guards movement,

03:49:55.990 --> 03:49:58.770
authors, and practitioners
were saying, you know,

03:49:58.770 --> 03:50:01.720
basically Malcolm
was assassinated

03:50:01.720 --> 03:50:04.020
and Baraka [assumed spelling]
moved up North to Harlem

03:50:04.020 --> 03:50:06.760
and said, you know, this
basically, we are going

03:50:06.760 --> 03:50:09.150
to address ourselves, two black
people, four black people,

03:50:09.150 --> 03:50:11.030
about black people,
we are not going

03:50:11.030 --> 03:50:13.460
to be responding to whiteness.

03:50:13.460 --> 03:50:20.220
And so, it was art as action,
and so I really root my approach

03:50:20.220 --> 03:50:23.360
to Afrofuturism, very much
in the black guards movement

03:50:23.360 --> 03:50:26.800
in that time period I thought
about that for a long times,

03:50:26.800 --> 03:50:29.010
and I feel and very
connected with a number

03:50:29.010 --> 03:50:31.540
of the practitioners who
are still working today.

03:50:31.540 --> 03:50:35.380
And one of the things
I want to say too

03:50:35.380 --> 03:50:39.540
about the term Afrofuturism
is there's also and I guess,

03:50:39.540 --> 03:50:43.370
this is a little more detailed
in terms of the specifics

03:50:43.370 --> 03:50:47.670
of this-- the genre, but there
are sometimes arguments about,

03:50:47.670 --> 03:50:50.900
well, what should it be called
and the more Afrofuturism gets

03:50:50.900 --> 03:50:55.520
to be this phenomena, you
know, as the years go by.

03:50:55.520 --> 03:50:58.680
Some folks would say,
"Well, I don't want to--

03:50:58.680 --> 03:51:01.270
Afrofuturism, that term
was invented by white men.

03:51:01.270 --> 03:51:03.620
I don't want this to be
something that I'm using

03:51:03.620 --> 03:51:06.780
to define this radical
practice."

03:51:06.780 --> 03:51:09.100
Which I understand and I
think that's why I go back

03:51:09.100 --> 03:51:12.330
to shape shifting,
Afrofuturism, black sci-fi,

03:51:12.330 --> 03:51:16.690
a black speculative
science, you know,

03:51:16.690 --> 03:51:19.820
all of these terminologies
have space,

03:51:19.820 --> 03:51:22.500
and I think they're
all connected.

03:51:22.500 --> 03:51:25.890
One of the reasons I hold
to that term at least

03:51:25.890 --> 03:51:28.920
for the moment, giving myself
space to shape shift out of

03:51:28.920 --> 03:51:32.830
that if I should so desire
is there's an article

03:51:32.830 --> 03:51:35.920
by Mark Rockymore called
"What is Afrofuturism?"

03:51:35.920 --> 03:51:38.810
that really has moved
me over the years.

03:51:38.810 --> 03:51:41.390
And he talks about the afro.

03:51:41.390 --> 03:51:43.760
So for me it's kind
of two parts,

03:51:43.760 --> 03:51:45.820
one is the form of the afro.

03:51:45.820 --> 03:51:47.120
It can't be contained.

03:51:47.120 --> 03:51:50.610
It can't be constrained,
spirals, moving this way

03:51:50.610 --> 03:51:52.920
and that, you know,
of their own volition.

03:51:52.920 --> 03:51:56.420
And so, his beautiful poetic
description of the afro

03:51:56.420 --> 03:51:59.620
for me is what roots
the practice.

03:51:59.620 --> 03:52:03.380
And then also, thinking
about Malcolm rooted

03:52:03.380 --> 03:52:07.490
in Black Arts Movement as well,
and in that particular moment

03:52:07.490 --> 03:52:09.990
in time, where there
was a constant speaking

03:52:09.990 --> 03:52:12.460
to the Afro-American.

03:52:12.460 --> 03:52:15.030
And so something about
using the term Afro

03:52:15.030 --> 03:52:18.740
for me also roots
it in that moment.

03:52:18.740 --> 03:52:21.640
And so, I really, for myself
I think about Afrofuturism

03:52:21.640 --> 03:52:25.070
as an action, it's a practice.

03:52:25.070 --> 03:52:29.100
I describe it as a
methodology of black liberation.

03:52:29.100 --> 03:52:34.840
So it's definitely a space
where people can express

03:52:34.840 --> 03:52:37.400
and be creative, and all
of that is part of it.

03:52:37.400 --> 03:52:41.510
For me, I'm very invested
in it, it not necessarily

03:52:41.510 --> 03:52:44.680
to say political,
but just an action,

03:52:44.680 --> 03:52:47.590
a statement, a methodology.

03:52:47.590 --> 03:52:50.960
&gt;&gt; Enongo Lumumba-Kasongo:
And I think leaping on that,

03:52:50.960 --> 03:52:55.990
just quickly in the anthology
Octavia's Brood distinction is

03:52:55.990 --> 03:53:00.310
made in the introduction between
sort of speculative fiction

03:53:00.310 --> 03:53:02.360
and visionary fiction
and this idea

03:53:02.360 --> 03:53:05.910
that this is explicitly rooted
in sort of social justice ideas,

03:53:05.910 --> 03:53:08.260
and that there's no
shying away from that,

03:53:08.260 --> 03:53:11.660
and sort of what you're
expressing around,

03:53:11.660 --> 03:53:14.840
the recognition of a
perspective, like acknowledging

03:53:14.840 --> 03:53:16.150
that is a big part of the work.

03:53:16.150 --> 03:53:18.970
Not saying that they
occupy the view from nowhere

03:53:18.970 --> 03:53:22.430
that there's an objective
perspective there, right,

03:53:22.430 --> 03:53:25.440
instead, that's a full part
of kind of visionary fictions,

03:53:25.440 --> 03:53:28.890
so I think-- and kind
of this distinction

03:53:28.890 --> 03:53:32.180
that you were talking about
around kind of the action of it

03:53:32.180 --> 03:53:35.970
that there's this social justice
framework for a lot of the work

03:53:35.970 --> 03:53:38.610
that falls in that category.

03:53:38.610 --> 03:53:39.910
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: Willi,
I wonder if you could speak

03:53:39.910 --> 03:53:42.280
to this from the standpoint
of indigenous futurism

03:53:42.280 --> 03:53:43.580
and how it functions for you

03:53:43.580 --> 03:53:46.810
in the communities
that you work with.

03:53:46.810 --> 03:53:48.110
&gt;&gt; Willi Lemper: Yeah.

03:53:48.110 --> 03:53:51.470
I mean it operates in a very
practical way for people

03:53:51.470 --> 03:53:53.990
because in Australia,
for example, there is--

03:53:53.990 --> 03:53:57.360
there are no treaties
sort of as much

03:53:57.360 --> 03:54:00.270
as treaties have been
broken in North America.

03:54:00.270 --> 03:54:02.070
There are no treaties.

03:54:02.070 --> 03:54:05.640
[Inaudible] is established
that there were no people there

03:54:05.640 --> 03:54:10.120
and so it was considered moral.

03:54:10.120 --> 03:54:14.740
And so the way that citizens
imagine indigenous futures

03:54:14.740 --> 03:54:16.160
in Australia has a huge impact

03:54:16.160 --> 03:54:19.090
on whether communities
will be funded.

03:54:19.090 --> 03:54:22.510
There's a reason that for to
close half of all communities--

03:54:22.510 --> 03:54:24.120
aboriginal communities
in Australia.

03:54:24.120 --> 03:54:27.020
And it would have happen except
there was a public outcry.

03:54:27.020 --> 03:54:30.540
So a lot hangs on sort
of broader coalitions

03:54:30.540 --> 03:54:34.070
of people imagining that
there's a future for people,

03:54:34.070 --> 03:54:37.320
but it's very stark funding,
it was cut by 40% recently,

03:54:37.320 --> 03:54:41.260
and there's this larger
way, I think especially

03:54:41.260 --> 03:54:43.470
in indigenous futurisms
around temporality

03:54:43.470 --> 03:54:47.270
in which the past
becomes a place for--

03:54:47.270 --> 03:54:50.950
in which indigenous people are
slotted into the mythic at best,

03:54:50.950 --> 03:54:52.610
and then it gets
worse from there.

03:54:52.610 --> 03:54:55.590
Then the present is about
suffering in problems

03:54:55.590 --> 03:54:57.690
and the future is absent.

03:54:57.690 --> 03:54:59.110
And so there's this
way in which--

03:54:59.110 --> 03:55:01.060
there's this great books
"Silencing the Past"

03:55:01.060 --> 03:55:02.500
by Michel-Rolph Trouillot.

03:55:02.500 --> 03:55:04.940
He talks about how the past
is a bundle of silence.

03:55:04.940 --> 03:55:07.110
It's more than it
is anything else.

03:55:07.110 --> 03:55:10.620
And the future is also silenced,
that the future mostly has to do

03:55:10.620 --> 03:55:12.910
with things that
have been edited out.

03:55:12.910 --> 03:55:14.400
But we focused on the
things that are there

03:55:14.400 --> 03:55:17.160
because that makes sense to do,

03:55:17.160 --> 03:55:19.670
especially for indigenous
people.

03:55:19.670 --> 03:55:22.750
Western civilization is
dependent on them not existing

03:55:22.750 --> 03:55:28.060
and always has been in
Southern colonization.

03:55:28.060 --> 03:55:31.840
And so, I think temporality
becomes especially important

03:55:31.840 --> 03:55:35.060
in that case, yeah.

03:55:35.060 --> 03:55:36.750
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: You know
one of the things that came

03:55:36.750 --> 03:55:40.660
up in our pre-event call
was the potentiality

03:55:40.660 --> 03:55:42.510
of these frameworks
for transformation.

03:55:42.510 --> 03:55:46.680
And I think that's something,
even though you each work well,

03:55:46.680 --> 03:55:50.210
you use work in a variety of
different media, then different

03:55:50.210 --> 03:55:54.800
from each other and wide in
scope in each one of your work.

03:55:54.800 --> 03:55:58.090
And I wonder if you could
speak a little to the way

03:55:58.090 --> 03:56:01.290
that transformation
is realized during

03:56:01.290 --> 03:56:03.620
or at least implemented
in your work.

03:56:03.620 --> 03:56:08.190
So, I know Ytasha, you had done
a dance therapy workshop this

03:56:08.190 --> 03:56:09.490
summer, is that correct?

03:56:09.490 --> 03:56:10.790
&gt;&gt; Ytasha L. Womack: Right.

03:56:10.790 --> 03:56:12.090
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: Yeah.

03:56:12.090 --> 03:56:13.480
&gt;&gt; Ytasha L. Womack: Yes,
very eventful program.

03:56:13.480 --> 03:56:16.970
I worked with teenage girls
which is always great.

03:56:16.970 --> 03:56:22.320
And the program was really based
on this concept of using dance

03:56:22.320 --> 03:56:28.610
as a way to connect people
with ideas about the future.

03:56:28.610 --> 03:56:34.060
And to connect them with more
of a historical grounding

03:56:34.060 --> 03:56:36.540
around identity in
culture and so forth,

03:56:36.540 --> 03:56:38.640
but more importantly
just to kind touch

03:56:38.640 --> 03:56:41.370
on all aspect of ourselves.

03:56:41.370 --> 03:56:46.520
So the course, it included
breathing exercises, meditation,

03:56:46.520 --> 03:56:48.120
but then they also
learned a little

03:56:48.120 --> 03:56:50.430
about different dances of--

03:56:50.430 --> 03:56:51.730
from different parts

03:56:51.730 --> 03:56:53.200
of the African continents
and Diasporas.

03:56:53.200 --> 03:56:56.330
So they learned West
African traditional dance,

03:56:56.330 --> 03:56:58.030
they're learning
Chicago style stepping,

03:56:58.030 --> 03:57:03.170
they're learning samba, salsa
and seeing the relationship

03:57:03.170 --> 03:57:05.890
between the music and
the rhythm patterns.

03:57:05.890 --> 03:57:08.940
But then also there would
be some essay writing.

03:57:08.940 --> 03:57:10.240
They would journal.

03:57:10.240 --> 03:57:11.540
Talk about themselves.

03:57:11.540 --> 03:57:13.100
We would do group exercises

03:57:13.100 --> 03:57:16.790
where they would pick a
celestial phenomenon and then do

03:57:16.790 --> 03:57:20.360
like a freestyle dance
movement thinking

03:57:20.360 --> 03:57:24.150
about Andromeda or
a particular star.

03:57:24.150 --> 03:57:27.430
And what it did over
time was they started

03:57:27.430 --> 03:57:30.820
to see a relationship between
themselves and the earth

03:57:30.820 --> 03:57:32.810
and then the larger universe.

03:57:32.810 --> 03:57:36.570
And with, you know, start
to speak in that way

03:57:36.570 --> 03:57:40.960
and they saw the value of art
in going to museums and thinking

03:57:40.960 --> 03:57:44.580
about dance and movement
as being art forms

03:57:44.580 --> 03:57:47.240
that had been preserved
in some respect

03:57:47.240 --> 03:57:49.020
for several thousand years.

03:57:49.020 --> 03:57:51.030
Looking at a dance
like samba and looking

03:57:51.030 --> 03:57:53.930
at how old it really is, so
some of the rhythms from--

03:57:53.930 --> 03:57:56.270
some of the music
from West African,

03:57:56.270 --> 03:57:58.690
the West African dances
they were learning.

03:57:58.690 --> 03:58:01.480
And seeing that, you
know, in different spaces,

03:58:01.480 --> 03:58:05.770
there was sometimes, they were
different symbolism with that.

03:58:05.770 --> 03:58:07.260
And then you say, "Well,
what does that have

03:58:07.260 --> 03:58:09.570
to do with the future?"

03:58:09.570 --> 03:58:13.150
Well they saw a relationship
between themselves,

03:58:13.150 --> 03:58:16.400
people in the past and
people in the future.

03:58:16.400 --> 03:58:19.900
And that the dances that they
were doing were connected

03:58:19.900 --> 03:58:22.470
to people who were doing
those dances before.

03:58:22.470 --> 03:58:25.940
And that the ideas and the
actions they were taking now

03:58:25.940 --> 03:58:28.840
were going to shape things
for people in the future

03:58:28.840 --> 03:58:32.540
and it also help them to feel
like they have more agency

03:58:32.540 --> 03:58:34.380
in part because of
the physical activity,

03:58:34.380 --> 03:58:37.820
they're pushing through,
you know, body limitations

03:58:37.820 --> 03:58:40.400
to do things they weren't
normally used to doing.

03:58:40.400 --> 03:58:44.010
And that made them think
more about their own futures.

03:58:44.010 --> 03:58:47.060
And so, it was, you know,
very holistic in that sense,

03:58:47.060 --> 03:58:50.910
but of course, you can imagine
certain things come up as well

03:58:50.910 --> 03:58:52.830
that kind of had
to be addressed.

03:58:52.830 --> 03:58:56.070
And so it was a very
transformative experience,

03:58:56.070 --> 03:58:59.750
but from me as a person who is a
writer and a dancer growing up,

03:58:59.750 --> 03:59:02.640
most people would think there
wasn't much of a relationship

03:59:02.640 --> 03:59:08.010
and to-- so-- but the
natural evolution of that is

03:59:08.010 --> 03:59:10.570
to see this logic connectivity.

03:59:10.570 --> 03:59:14.230
So I did do a film called a
"Love Letter to the Ancestors

03:59:14.230 --> 03:59:18.120
from Chicago" which also
dealt with dance as a kind

03:59:18.120 --> 03:59:24.800
of like the body as a-- the
body as a portal of sorts

03:59:24.800 --> 03:59:28.300
between the future, the past
and the present specifically

03:59:28.300 --> 03:59:29.680
around kind of house music.

03:59:29.680 --> 03:59:33.040
I'm from Chicago and
I'm excited about that.

03:59:33.040 --> 03:59:36.370
But looking at freestyle
dances being part of the sort

03:59:36.370 --> 03:59:39.420
of interconnected way
of reminding ourselves

03:59:39.420 --> 03:59:42.130
that we have a relationship
with one another,

03:59:42.130 --> 03:59:45.660
with the universe
and with the earth.

03:59:45.660 --> 03:59:46.960
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz:
Yeah, and I don't know

03:59:46.960 --> 03:59:48.990
if you all are familiar
with the dancer PhD contest

03:59:48.990 --> 03:59:51.680
or I guess it's a contest.

03:59:51.680 --> 03:59:57.490
So this was something that
started a number of years ago

03:59:57.490 --> 04:00:03.000
that I think, well, for lack
of less punny word embodies,

04:00:03.000 --> 04:00:05.740
a lot of the ways that people

04:00:05.740 --> 04:00:08.890
from scientific disciplines
think about the dialogue

04:00:08.890 --> 04:00:10.770
between the arts and sciences

04:00:10.770 --> 04:00:14.000
that it will be an
interpretive relationship.

04:00:14.000 --> 04:00:16.500
And I think one of the
things that's really missing

04:00:16.500 --> 04:00:20.520
from the way folks from the
science side, city arts is

04:00:20.520 --> 04:00:22.190
that they don't realize

04:00:22.190 --> 04:00:25.180
that there's this possible
relationship they can form just

04:00:25.180 --> 04:00:28.450
through movement
through from physicality.

04:00:28.450 --> 04:00:32.930
Yeah. I wonder and whoever
wants to take it first,

04:00:32.930 --> 04:00:35.180
if you can speak a little bit
about some of the projects

04:00:35.180 --> 04:00:39.080
that you've worked on and
their relationships to the sort

04:00:39.080 --> 04:00:41.960
of transformative
potentialities.

04:00:41.960 --> 04:00:47.440
&gt;&gt; Enongo Lumumba-Kasongo:
I think touching

04:00:47.440 --> 04:00:50.450
on what Ytasha was
talking about.

04:00:50.450 --> 04:00:56.530
Actually my PhD work has helped
me in some regards in thinking

04:00:56.530 --> 04:01:00.480
about transformative potentials
of spaces and in myself

04:01:00.480 --> 04:01:05.560
and my community in a sense
that one of the areas of science

04:01:05.560 --> 04:01:08.930
and technology studies, it was
kind of history of technology,

04:01:08.930 --> 04:01:13.270
and broadening our definitions
of technology, broadening them

04:01:13.270 --> 04:01:17.410
to think less about kind of
discrete specific objects

04:01:17.410 --> 04:01:21.860
that often kind of thrive
or are tied in deeply

04:01:21.860 --> 04:01:24.150
to like masculinity or
particular, you know,

04:01:24.150 --> 04:01:27.670
constructs of power and instead
thinking more about, you know,

04:01:27.670 --> 04:01:29.740
"Monday in Technologies"
or even--

04:01:29.740 --> 04:01:33.360
not even technologies as objects
but as ways of doing things.

04:01:33.360 --> 04:01:35.740
And so opening up this idea

04:01:35.740 --> 04:01:39.810
that technology could be
something more, and that is part

04:01:39.810 --> 04:01:41.250
of a-- it only has meaning.

04:01:41.250 --> 04:01:44.590
And so far as the people around
it give it that meaning, it--

04:01:44.590 --> 04:01:45.970
I think as Ytasha
was saying, it gave--

04:01:45.970 --> 04:01:48.810
it felt like I had agency,
right, that the things

04:01:48.810 --> 04:01:51.170
that we do in our
actions were not just sort

04:01:51.170 --> 04:01:52.470
of dropped from the sky.

04:01:52.470 --> 04:01:53.770
There's a context.

04:01:53.770 --> 04:01:55.070
There's a broader history.

04:01:55.070 --> 04:01:56.380
There's a relationship
with other things

04:01:56.380 --> 04:01:57.680
that have happened before.

04:01:57.680 --> 04:02:01.170
And I think power functions
by cutting people off

04:02:01.170 --> 04:02:03.830
from their past, right, by
not allowing people to feel

04:02:03.830 --> 04:02:05.240
like there's a connection
and that the things

04:02:05.240 --> 04:02:07.070
that you do actually matter.

04:02:07.070 --> 04:02:08.990
And I think once I
started to recognize that,

04:02:08.990 --> 04:02:12.370
that's when I dug into my music.

04:02:12.370 --> 04:02:16.080
And explicitly talking about,
you know, hardships that I'd had

04:02:16.080 --> 04:02:18.760
but not in the sort of
like grand, you know,

04:02:18.760 --> 04:02:22.550
black suffering narrative
but instead this is a thing

04:02:22.550 --> 04:02:24.280
that I've dealt with
personally in my life.

04:02:24.280 --> 04:02:26.330
And let me share my
testimony with you.

04:02:26.330 --> 04:02:28.480
And in doing that, you know,
people have come up to me

04:02:28.480 --> 04:02:30.650
after shows and said, you know,
I started going to therapy

04:02:30.650 --> 04:02:32.400
because you started talking

04:02:32.400 --> 04:02:34.530
about the importance
of that in your life.

04:02:34.530 --> 04:02:36.480
Or I had a conversation
with my adviser

04:02:36.480 --> 04:02:38.020
that I have been
putting off for forever

04:02:38.020 --> 04:02:40.260
because we were talking
about the breakdown.

04:02:40.260 --> 04:02:43.790
And so, I think I started to
realized what I do matters,

04:02:43.790 --> 04:02:47.310
the music that I make matters
and the words that I put

04:02:47.310 --> 04:02:51.460
down should be well intention
because it reverberates.

04:02:51.460 --> 04:02:52.760
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz:
If I could ask,

04:02:52.760 --> 04:02:54.710
there's a quick follow
up to that.

04:02:54.710 --> 04:02:59.250
How often do you engage
with your students?

04:02:59.250 --> 04:03:00.980
So for example, you
just thought the science

04:03:00.980 --> 04:03:02.990
of feminism course at NYU.

04:03:02.990 --> 04:03:06.060
How often do you engage
with your students also

04:03:06.060 --> 04:03:07.970
through like a musical lens.

04:03:07.970 --> 04:03:10.830
Is that all what we've been
entering together for you or is

04:03:10.830 --> 04:03:14.860
that sort of different parts of
your life that you separate or?

04:03:14.860 --> 04:03:16.160
&gt;&gt; Enongo Lumumba-Kasongo:
So I've kind

04:03:16.160 --> 04:03:18.180
of separated them
from my sanity.

04:03:18.180 --> 04:03:21.020
I've got my academic stuff over
here and then my musical self,

04:03:21.020 --> 04:03:23.530
but of course they sort of
bleed and it was really cool

04:03:23.530 --> 04:03:28.030
because one of my students at
the beginning of the class was

04:03:28.030 --> 04:03:30.800
like maybe this sounds
awkward, but are you a rapper?

04:03:30.800 --> 04:03:32.100
And I guess he had
done some research.

04:03:32.100 --> 04:03:36.250
And so it was cool, we got a
chance to have a conversation.

04:03:36.250 --> 04:03:38.800
We started taking my headphones
and other stuff and sort

04:03:38.800 --> 04:03:41.130
of opened up this,
this dialogue.

04:03:41.130 --> 04:03:44.840
But I still haven't figured out
how to weave it all together

04:03:44.840 --> 04:03:46.650
but I would like to because
I think that they are--

04:03:46.650 --> 04:03:49.610
they do speak to each other.

04:03:49.610 --> 04:03:50.980
&gt;&gt; D. Denenge Duyst-Akpem:
I love that question

04:03:50.980 --> 04:03:53.600
because I think just
thinking about that as well.

04:03:53.600 --> 04:03:58.530
It's something that
I've been thinking how--

04:03:58.530 --> 04:03:59.830
what are the ways

04:03:59.830 --> 04:04:01.280
that I incorporate my
performative nature

04:04:01.280 --> 04:04:03.380
into my teaching practice.

04:04:03.380 --> 04:04:08.620
One if-- my kind of funny
story, there's a shaman,

04:04:08.620 --> 04:04:13.950
multiple PhD having a-- his
name is Malidoma Patrice Some,

04:04:13.950 --> 04:04:15.450
some of you may know him.

04:04:15.450 --> 04:04:17.900
He's a Dagara from Burkina Faso.

04:04:17.900 --> 04:04:20.350
And I've been studying his
work following what he does

04:04:20.350 --> 04:04:21.650
for many years.

04:04:21.650 --> 04:04:24.850
And I had the chance to do
divination with him last year

04:04:24.850 --> 04:04:26.960
which was deeply transformative.

04:04:26.960 --> 04:04:30.470
And one of the stories in his
book, Of Water and the Spirit,

04:04:30.470 --> 04:04:32.060
he talks about his grandfather--

04:04:32.060 --> 04:04:36.360
he was very close and how
grandfather would hypnotize

04:04:36.360 --> 04:04:37.660
small children.

04:04:37.660 --> 04:04:39.580
If you ever saw a
small child walking

04:04:39.580 --> 04:04:42.830
around the village just
wordlessly doing a task,

04:04:42.830 --> 04:04:44.130
you know, handling a task,

04:04:44.130 --> 04:04:47.750
you knew that they had been
hypnotized by grandfather.

04:04:47.750 --> 04:04:50.840
And so, I think about that in
the context of my teaching.

04:04:50.840 --> 04:04:54.930
You know, one of the ways that
I can sort of hypnotize and,

04:04:54.930 --> 04:04:56.590
you know-- and use the voice.

04:04:56.590 --> 04:05:00.230
And, you know, I'm trained as
a jazz singer and trained--

04:05:00.230 --> 04:05:03.610
My voice is my mother's voice
so I used it very much in terms

04:05:03.610 --> 04:05:06.890
of self soothing, my sister is
a speech pathologist, you know,

04:05:06.890 --> 04:05:08.770
she taught me about
my performance

04:05:08.770 --> 04:05:10.120
that I'll be doing later.

04:05:10.120 --> 04:05:14.660
So I'm really, really
interested in the use of voice,

04:05:14.660 --> 04:05:18.550
word force thinking
about Yoruba Oriki.

04:05:18.550 --> 04:05:21.840
The power of drawing forts,
the person's essential nature

04:05:21.840 --> 04:05:24.000
through the use of voice.

04:05:24.000 --> 04:05:26.480
And so that's something
that I think about a lot,

04:05:26.480 --> 04:05:30.650
and I do ritual engaging
ritual with students

04:05:30.650 --> 04:05:31.950
and that sort of thing.

04:05:31.950 --> 04:05:35.920
I also wanted to kind of,
you know, speak to, Willi,

04:05:35.920 --> 04:05:37.900
what you're talking
about in terms of Ongogi

04:05:37.900 --> 04:05:40.550
who actually was I
took a class with him

04:05:40.550 --> 04:05:41.910
as an undergrad at Smith.

04:05:41.910 --> 04:05:46.110
He was recently out of
prison and an exile.

04:05:46.110 --> 04:05:50.920
And he talks about the cultural
bomb in decolonizing the mind.

04:05:50.920 --> 04:05:55.390
And that has been deeply
meaningful to me in terms

04:05:55.390 --> 04:06:00.720
of this idea of how it destroys
the people's belief in terms

04:06:00.720 --> 04:06:05.610
of the colonial project in
their own culture, in their own.

04:06:05.610 --> 04:06:08.770
And so thinking about that
belief and one's performance,

04:06:08.770 --> 04:06:12.720
the belief in one's--
what one has to share.

04:06:12.720 --> 04:06:17.560
And one of the interesting
things is that years ago

04:06:17.560 --> 04:06:19.510
and I won't say the
exact year but I was--

04:06:19.510 --> 04:06:24.330
when I was at Smith I was chosen
for this Smithsonian Internship

04:06:24.330 --> 04:06:27.970
where they sent 12 students
per year to different museums

04:06:27.970 --> 04:06:31.370
at the Smithsonian and I was
stationed at the National Museum

04:06:31.370 --> 04:06:35.680
of African Art to work on
King Ajman [inaudible] cloth

04:06:35.680 --> 04:06:36.980
and exhibition.

04:06:36.980 --> 04:06:40.250
At that time doing an
interactive exhibit,

04:06:40.250 --> 04:06:44.120
having a play written about
Ajman [inaudible] life,

04:06:44.120 --> 04:06:48.000
having [inaudible] family that
come from Ghana doing libations

04:06:48.000 --> 04:06:51.430
and a procession, this was
radical for the Smithsonian,

04:06:51.430 --> 04:06:54.870
you know, all kinds of
permissions to have libations

04:06:54.870 --> 04:06:57.990
and processions and all of
that may still be, you know,

04:06:57.990 --> 04:07:00.290
but to come back
here now, you know,

04:07:00.290 --> 04:07:04.860
and I will say it almost
20 years after that,

04:07:04.860 --> 04:07:08.820
it really makes me think about
this idea of engaged practice.

04:07:08.820 --> 04:07:12.600
And one of the things that I was
writing about and interviewing

04:07:12.600 --> 04:07:16.810
and working with the museum was
how do you exhibit African art

04:07:16.810 --> 04:07:19.080
in the western museum context.

04:07:19.080 --> 04:07:23.410
And I had-- many of my
teachers were doing performances

04:07:23.410 --> 04:07:26.300
with works of art and
moving through the museum,

04:07:26.300 --> 04:07:30.940
dancing to the, you know,
exhibitions and all of that.

04:07:30.940 --> 04:07:33.430
And so, that was really
the foundation, you know,

04:07:33.430 --> 04:07:35.010
Andrea Hairston, Tony
Baka [assumed spelling]

04:07:35.010 --> 04:07:38.690
and so many others for my
understanding of what it means

04:07:38.690 --> 04:07:41.230
to activate not only a space.

04:07:41.230 --> 04:07:44.420
And so, I think of
myself a space sculptor.

04:07:44.420 --> 04:07:48.600
But to activate not just the
physical space but the space

04:07:48.600 --> 04:07:52.510
of your body thinking of our
bodies as vessels of liberation

04:07:52.510 --> 04:07:55.880
as much as the music
as a vessel,

04:07:55.880 --> 04:07:57.680
the mothership as a vessel.

04:07:57.680 --> 04:08:00.490
And so, what are the
ways that we use voice

04:08:00.490 --> 04:08:07.210
or we use other methodologies
to activate that individual

04:08:07.210 --> 04:08:10.450
and in response to works
of art or otherwise.

04:08:10.450 --> 04:08:14.180
So, that I think, you know,
for me the idea of immersion,

04:08:14.180 --> 04:08:21.120
interaction, performitivity,
the ritual practice

04:08:21.120 --> 04:08:25.740
within the space
of Afrofuturism.

04:08:25.740 --> 04:08:28.510
You know, for me, it's
all in my work it ends

04:08:28.510 --> 04:08:30.360
up being a really collage.

04:08:30.360 --> 04:08:33.730
And in that the same
time when I was at Smith,

04:08:33.730 --> 04:08:35.720
I remember having
a tarot reading.

04:08:35.720 --> 04:08:39.570
And I remember the woman
who read my cards said,

04:08:39.570 --> 04:08:42.460
"The thing that you're going
to end up doing doesn't exist.

04:08:42.460 --> 04:08:44.310
You're going to create it."

04:08:44.310 --> 04:08:48.110
And so now,, you know, it's--
that many years later, you know,

04:08:48.110 --> 04:08:49.970
I real-- and it can
be very scary

04:08:49.970 --> 04:08:54.170
because this performance style,
this collage style, this thing,

04:08:54.170 --> 04:08:55.580
this Afrofuturism thing,

04:08:55.580 --> 04:09:01.880
a lot of it hasn't existed till
what I've put out there and

04:09:01.880 --> 04:09:03.320
or that particular style.

04:09:03.320 --> 04:09:09.970
And so, you know, it's a sort of
continual evolution into being--

04:09:09.970 --> 04:09:11.950
into the being that
I already am I guess.

04:09:11.950 --> 04:09:14.690
Yeah.

04:09:14.690 --> 04:09:16.090
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: Willi,
I wonder if you could speak

04:09:16.090 --> 04:09:20.310
to your process so-- you
refer yourself and what you do

04:09:20.310 --> 04:09:23.530
as collaborative film making
with indigenous communities.

04:09:23.530 --> 04:09:27.510
So, can you tell us a little
bit about how that process works

04:09:27.510 --> 04:09:31.210
and for you, for
them, for everyone?

04:09:31.210 --> 04:09:32.510
&gt;&gt; Willi Lemper: Yeah.

04:09:32.510 --> 04:09:35.350
Collaboration is a word
that's turned around a lot now

04:09:35.350 --> 04:09:38.260
and it can mean a lot of things.

04:09:38.260 --> 04:09:42.320
Some, you know, very
admirable, some, some not.

04:09:42.320 --> 04:09:43.800
So, I've tried to
think for collab--

04:09:43.800 --> 04:09:48.050
about collaboration for a long
time and what that really means.

04:09:48.050 --> 04:09:53.550
So, for me, it involves trying
to-- from the very beginning

04:09:53.550 --> 04:09:54.850
and through the very end,

04:09:54.850 --> 04:09:56.540
through the writing
process as well.

04:09:56.540 --> 04:09:59.870
Start off with not the question
of can I do this or anything

04:09:59.870 --> 04:10:03.630
like that, but would you like
to do something together?

04:10:03.630 --> 04:10:06.990
And at a sort of larger metal
level trying to create a dynamic

04:10:06.990 --> 04:10:10.700
in which to the extent that's
possible instead of studying

04:10:10.700 --> 04:10:14.160
of people or that sort of
history of anthropology

04:10:14.160 --> 04:10:16.670
of doing projects with people.

04:10:16.670 --> 04:10:20.880
Working on something and looking
the same direction together.

04:10:20.880 --> 04:10:25.300
And so, going-- asking if you
would like to work on a project.

04:10:25.300 --> 04:10:27.950
And if so, what would--
and the second step for me

04:10:27.950 --> 04:10:30.400
at least is what would be the
single most useful thing for me

04:10:30.400 --> 04:10:33.240
to do in this context.

04:10:33.240 --> 04:10:37.450
And then, and still leave out
the research, a complete list

04:10:37.450 --> 04:10:40.140
at that point then go
home, think about it.

04:10:40.140 --> 04:10:42.930
And then build a project
from that foundation

04:10:42.930 --> 04:10:45.920
so that the Venn diagram
of what your project is

04:10:45.920 --> 04:10:50.860
and what would be on a daily
level productive in their point

04:10:50.860 --> 04:10:54.220
of view are not in
conflict to extent possible.

04:10:54.220 --> 04:10:56.630
And then, build the
project from there.

04:10:56.630 --> 04:10:58.860
So, for me, I've been
following the social life

04:10:58.860 --> 04:11:00.160
with film projects.

04:11:00.160 --> 04:11:02.650
So, whatever was happening with
the project, I was just get

04:11:02.650 --> 04:11:06.080
in the land cruise
and off, we were.

04:11:06.080 --> 04:11:09.020
And the collaboration
is often discussed

04:11:09.020 --> 04:11:11.200
as a sort of ethical issue.

04:11:11.200 --> 04:11:15.270
And ethics is a very sort of
western mentality too because,

04:11:15.270 --> 04:11:18.770
of course, for addition
scholars, it's obligation.

04:11:18.770 --> 04:11:20.800
So, ethics present it
as a sort of option

04:11:20.800 --> 04:11:22.340
that you should feel good about.

04:11:22.340 --> 04:11:27.090
But beyond that as well, I think
it has profound implications

04:11:27.090 --> 04:11:30.890
as to what you find because I
was interested in futurism and,

04:11:30.890 --> 04:11:32.730
you know, speculative thinking

04:11:32.730 --> 04:11:34.630
from following native
science fiction

04:11:34.630 --> 04:11:37.190
from many years and those films.

04:11:37.190 --> 04:11:39.460
But what I also found is that
when you approach your project

04:11:39.460 --> 04:11:42.900
to certain way, different
types of things come out.

04:11:42.900 --> 04:11:47.600
Whereas, generally, there's
assumption that anthropologist

04:11:47.600 --> 04:11:49.580
or why people in general
are always just trying

04:11:49.580 --> 04:11:52.190
to learn more dreaming
stories, song lines.

04:11:52.190 --> 04:11:56.580
But when things open up
to in a more options,

04:11:56.580 --> 04:11:59.500
people are very interested
in telling other stories.

04:11:59.500 --> 04:12:03.330
And what I found is people often
want you talk about the future

04:12:03.330 --> 04:12:04.630
which is something I think

04:12:04.630 --> 04:12:08.550
that they feel is perhaps
silence specially in Australia

04:12:08.550 --> 04:12:12.150
where people are sort of
symbolically understood

04:12:12.150 --> 04:12:16.660
to be the oldest living
societies, set of societies.

04:12:16.660 --> 04:12:21.670
And that is taken as being
sort of the window into a past

04:12:21.670 --> 04:12:23.200
and there's a long
history of that.

04:12:23.200 --> 04:12:28.130
So, I think engaging in the
future is also lot about process

04:12:28.130 --> 04:12:32.690
and understanding the history
of how things have often work

04:12:32.690 --> 04:12:34.700
and the research process.

