So, this was--

04:13:11.520 --> 04:13:13.540
Thank you for that question.

04:13:13.540 --> 04:13:15.750
This was for Afrofuturism.

04:13:15.750 --> 04:13:18.340
I started teaching Afrofuturism

04:13:18.340 --> 04:13:21.890
at Columbia College
Chicago in 2010.

04:13:21.890 --> 04:13:25.040
I knew there were other
courses here and there about it.

04:13:25.040 --> 04:13:28.320
Many of them, I believe, tended
to be focus perhaps on music

04:13:28.320 --> 04:13:30.570
in particular or specific area.

04:13:30.570 --> 04:13:32.410
This was I think one
of the first courses

04:13:32.410 --> 04:13:38.160
that was looking really across
disciplinary at the subject.

04:13:38.160 --> 04:13:41.310
I had students in the class,

04:13:41.310 --> 04:13:47.260
13 different countries
represented 14 different majors

04:13:47.260 --> 04:13:48.940
across the college.

04:13:48.940 --> 04:13:53.490
So, it was really diverse as
far as classes, you know, go.

04:13:53.490 --> 04:13:56.110
It was a pretty diverse group.

04:13:56.110 --> 04:13:58.840
And this was-- there
was the announcement

04:13:58.840 --> 04:14:03.450
of Mars 1 planning
to settle by 2023.

04:14:03.450 --> 04:14:06.390
So, we were 10 years
out and I thought, "OK.

04:14:06.390 --> 04:14:08.730
Let's do-- we got to
something with this."

04:14:08.730 --> 04:14:11.640
And one of the big
points with Mars 1 is many

04:14:11.640 --> 04:14:13.890
of you probably know is
that they were doing a sort

04:14:13.890 --> 04:14:17.980
of reality TV style so you
could, you know, upload people

04:14:17.980 --> 04:14:19.280
from all over the world.

04:14:19.280 --> 04:14:21.840
And you could track the
demographics which I did

04:14:21.840 --> 04:14:24.870
because I want to see, you
know, how many Nigerians out.

04:14:24.870 --> 04:14:26.320
I'm very, you know,
being from Nigeria,

04:14:26.320 --> 04:14:28.410
I'm interested how many
Nigerians had actually,

04:14:28.410 --> 04:14:30.400
you know, submitted in
the application to go.

04:14:30.400 --> 04:14:32.420
But, you know, really
interested in kind

04:14:32.420 --> 04:14:34.420
of the data around that as well.

04:14:34.420 --> 04:14:37.880
Who is submitting
and why and what?

04:14:37.880 --> 04:14:44.010
So, anyway, we have all
these-- oh goodness, costuming.

04:14:44.010 --> 04:14:47.330
All of these individuals from
around the world who are--

04:14:47.330 --> 04:14:48.980
I think it was in the
hundreds of thousands

04:14:48.980 --> 04:14:50.280
of people who had submitted.

04:14:50.280 --> 04:14:52.370
So, I thought let's
do something similar.

04:14:52.370 --> 04:14:55.880
We didn't use the application
online but I wanted students

04:14:55.880 --> 04:14:58.860
to have the experience
of applying.

04:14:58.860 --> 04:15:00.160
I did a poll.

04:15:00.160 --> 04:15:02.700
I think there were 27
students in the class.

04:15:02.700 --> 04:15:07.860
And out of that number, only
two said they would actually go.

04:15:07.860 --> 04:15:10.720
So, this wasn't based on
the actual desire to travel

04:15:10.720 --> 04:15:14.380
to Mars just sort
of hypotheticals.

04:15:14.380 --> 04:15:16.940
And so, I created
an application.

04:15:16.940 --> 04:15:22.830
And every class session was
basically completing another

04:15:22.830 --> 04:15:24.870
step in that application.

04:15:24.870 --> 04:15:30.910
Part of that was discussing
your strengths and kind of--

04:15:30.910 --> 04:15:32.610
and it would be everything.

04:15:32.610 --> 04:15:34.470
Strengths, what do
you have to offer?

04:15:34.470 --> 04:15:39.030
So, one person in the class,
young man who's very tall.

04:15:39.030 --> 04:15:42.810
So, he said, "Well, my height,
you know, I can reach things."

04:15:42.810 --> 04:15:46.970
So, if I'm claiming out of
Mars, you know, a cavern,

04:15:46.970 --> 04:15:48.270
you know, I'd be useful.

04:15:48.270 --> 04:15:51.060
And then someone else said,
"I'm really, really short.

04:15:51.060 --> 04:15:53.490
I can fit into small spaces.

04:15:53.490 --> 04:15:56.390
So, if there's, you know,
technological things,

04:15:56.390 --> 04:15:58.630
things that need to be
fixed, I can get in there."

04:15:58.630 --> 04:16:01.040
So, they were really
thinking, you know,

04:16:01.040 --> 04:16:03.240
really practically
someone else--

04:16:03.240 --> 04:16:06.720
I'm just going to mention
some of the fun ones here.

04:16:06.720 --> 04:16:08.700
Someone said, you
know, hockey sack.

04:16:08.700 --> 04:16:10.270
You know, I'm really
good at that.

04:16:10.270 --> 04:16:14.340
It promotes community,
friendship and it's really good

04:16:14.340 --> 04:16:16.650
for exercise and
keeping the body limber

04:16:16.650 --> 04:16:17.950
when you're, you know.

04:16:17.950 --> 04:16:20.500
So, there were-- they were
really getting into it.

04:16:20.500 --> 04:16:24.510
And, but really, we read a lot.

04:16:24.510 --> 04:16:26.630
Of course, always in my
class is reading a lot

04:16:26.630 --> 04:16:30.150
for from a wide range of authors
and thinking about what some

04:16:30.150 --> 04:16:31.910
of the problems might be.

04:16:31.910 --> 04:16:36.580
And then, they created as part
of the application package,

04:16:36.580 --> 04:16:40.320
they developed a work of
art that would be included

04:16:40.320 --> 04:16:44.380
to be sent off to the committee.

04:16:44.380 --> 04:16:46.450
And so, everything,
I'll be sharing

04:16:46.450 --> 04:16:48.880
in the performance later.

04:16:48.880 --> 04:16:50.180
Kelsey came up.

04:16:50.180 --> 04:16:51.610
She's a vocal composition major.

04:16:51.610 --> 04:16:55.560
So, she created a Mars Anthem
complete with the salute.

04:16:55.560 --> 04:16:58.620
And we all sang and she
brought in a drummer.

04:16:58.620 --> 04:17:04.270
We had someone who was
combination of graphic design

04:17:04.270 --> 04:17:10.460
and also health food-- I'm not
sure exactly what her major was.

04:17:10.460 --> 04:17:12.820
So she researched
what astronauts eat,

04:17:12.820 --> 04:17:20.060
what some of the initiatives
were for Mars and growing plants

04:17:20.060 --> 04:17:21.360
and that sort of thing.

04:17:21.360 --> 04:17:22.980
So they were-- they
really just went

04:17:22.980 --> 04:17:24.370
into all their different areas.

04:17:24.370 --> 04:17:27.440
Some went out just really
about designing and recycling

04:17:27.440 --> 04:17:29.410
and just she said, you
know, rather than F up,

04:17:29.410 --> 04:17:33.230
Mars just that way we have
Earth, let's set up the system

04:17:33.230 --> 04:17:36.390
from the get go so that it's
already connected directly

04:17:36.390 --> 04:17:39.880
to your pad and when you need
something it comes to you

04:17:39.880 --> 04:17:41.760
and then when you need
to, you send it out

04:17:41.760 --> 04:17:43.060
and there's essential.

04:17:43.060 --> 04:17:46.040
So they all have these
amazing designs and ideas

04:17:46.040 --> 04:17:47.770
and it was just incredible.

04:17:47.770 --> 04:17:54.540
So that was exciting and then,
yeah, and then this fall,

04:17:54.540 --> 04:17:58.620
I'm teaching a course on Octavia
Butler's Parable of the Sower

04:17:58.620 --> 04:18:02.090
which is a prophetic text for
this moment in times especially

04:18:02.090 --> 04:18:06.020
down to whole "Make
America Great Again."

04:18:06.020 --> 04:18:11.630
Yeah. So basically we are--
it's a seminar studio.

04:18:11.630 --> 04:18:14.360
We're doing urban
foraging with Nance Klehm

04:18:14.360 --> 04:18:16.830
who is very well-known
especially in Chicago.

04:18:16.830 --> 04:18:22.100
We are meeting with Jessica
Charlesworth [assumed spelling]

04:18:22.100 --> 04:18:27.160
who teaches in the design
objects to do survival packs.

04:18:27.160 --> 04:18:32.210
So we are looking also at
disaster scenarios and thinking

04:18:32.210 --> 04:18:34.440
about what are the
ways that we want

04:18:34.440 --> 04:18:39.620
to develop these packs
based on current situations

04:18:39.620 --> 04:18:45.760
and what we envision to be our
ideas of what might be needed.

04:18:45.760 --> 04:18:49.030
So it's just a-- it's an
exciting class and it's a way

04:18:49.030 --> 04:18:52.720
to really kind of get it to
parable and think about future,

04:18:52.720 --> 04:18:57.840
past, present all in
this moment right now.

04:18:57.840 --> 04:18:59.140
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz:
Thank you.

04:18:59.140 --> 04:19:02.240
Ytasha, I wanted to ask
you since you [inaudible]

04:19:02.240 --> 04:19:05.200
for futures but you
literally wrote the book.

04:19:05.200 --> 04:19:08.870
And I wonder-- and you
touched on this a little bit

04:19:08.870 --> 04:19:11.530
at the beginning of the panel,
but I wonder if you can you talk

04:19:11.530 --> 04:19:17.490
about the way in which that as
a label functions for you both

04:19:17.490 --> 04:19:21.900
as something that can be
productive, but do you ever find

04:19:21.900 --> 04:19:26.910
that it's limiting or doesn't
allow you access to the spaces

04:19:26.910 --> 04:19:29.890
that you would like to have?

04:19:29.890 --> 04:19:31.190
&gt;&gt; Ytasha L. Womack: No.

04:19:31.190 --> 04:19:32.490
I don't find it to
be limiting at all.

04:19:32.490 --> 04:19:37.480
As a matter of fact, it's been
very liberating in a lot of ways

04:19:37.480 --> 04:19:40.350
and there's something
about naming power

04:19:40.350 --> 04:19:46.150
that I think really opens
the door to helping people

04:19:46.150 --> 04:19:49.800
to recognize that what
they are doing exist

04:19:49.800 --> 04:19:54.620
or to really synergize
ideas of-- Denenge was--

04:19:54.620 --> 04:19:58.150
Denenge I think in a
conversation with Denenge

04:19:58.150 --> 04:20:01.310
and I put this in the book,
it was through a conversation

04:20:01.310 --> 04:20:05.120
with her that I remember first
hearing the term Afrofuturism.

04:20:05.120 --> 04:20:07.720
Now, in retrospect,
I heard it before

04:20:07.720 --> 04:20:11.110
but I-- it didn't click then.

04:20:11.110 --> 04:20:14.630
And hearing the term, you
know, I would research then--

04:20:14.630 --> 04:20:16.940
and talk to these people

04:20:16.940 --> 04:20:20.770
and what I realize was I've
been having conversations

04:20:20.770 --> 04:20:23.990
and engaging in Afrofuturism
in my entire life.

04:20:23.990 --> 04:20:27.400
It really synergize
for me when I was

04:20:27.400 --> 04:20:30.240
at Clark Atlanta University and
the Atlanta University Center

04:20:30.240 --> 04:20:33.130
because everyone was
creating this Afrofuturism.

04:20:33.130 --> 04:20:36.230
Art and work and contemplating
the future and really working

04:20:36.230 --> 04:20:40.450
with the concepts of-- we were
even reading some of the essays,

04:20:40.450 --> 04:20:43.290
but again the term just
did not really click.

04:20:43.290 --> 04:20:46.730
And so for-- so when I
had that conversation,

04:20:46.730 --> 04:20:50.570
and Denenge brought up the
term and then retroactively,

04:20:50.570 --> 04:20:54.690
you know, starting to
look at how they were--

04:20:54.690 --> 04:20:58.140
all these relationships in
music and science and the art

04:20:58.140 --> 04:21:01.950
that you'd see within a
culture and then in my own life,

04:21:01.950 --> 04:21:04.820
it really pushed my
storytelling ability--

04:21:04.820 --> 04:21:08.460
excuse me, my storytelling
ability's further

04:21:08.460 --> 04:21:13.230
and that I was primarily
doing a lot of nonfiction.

04:21:13.230 --> 04:21:15.770
And, you know, working as
a journalist and then some

04:21:15.770 --> 04:21:18.930
of the fiction I did
was very off the time.

04:21:18.930 --> 04:21:22.030
And I felt like that
was limiting.

04:21:22.030 --> 04:21:26.230
Something about these narratives
of talking about love found,

04:21:26.230 --> 04:21:28.640
love lost in the present,

04:21:28.640 --> 04:21:30.940
this didn't really make
a lot of sense to me.

04:21:30.940 --> 04:21:34.190
And when I started thing
about Afrofuturism,

04:21:34.190 --> 04:21:37.750
I felt very compelled
to tell a story,

04:21:37.750 --> 04:21:41.870
the first one is the Rayla 2212
story about a woman who lived

04:21:41.870 --> 04:21:43.830
in the distant planet.

04:21:43.830 --> 04:21:48.140
She's third generation deep on
this planet and asked to kind

04:21:48.140 --> 04:21:49.440
of reconnect with Earth.

04:21:49.440 --> 04:21:52.360
And find these missing
astronauts who got stuck

04:21:52.360 --> 04:21:54.700
in space in time trying to
travel with their minds.

04:21:54.700 --> 04:21:58.740
And for me, it really became
a deconstruction around a lot

04:21:58.740 --> 04:22:02.860
of assumptions about identity
because there's the question

04:22:02.860 --> 04:22:04.840
of are you-- you know,

04:22:04.840 --> 04:22:07.700
what perspective am I
writing about her from?

04:22:07.700 --> 04:22:10.960
You know, I can't say that she
is, you know, in my perspective

04:22:10.960 --> 04:22:13.230
of being African-American
are being the black woman,

04:22:13.230 --> 04:22:16.030
I can't entirely
project that onto her

04:22:16.030 --> 04:22:20.320
because those identities shift
when you're on another planet,

04:22:20.320 --> 04:22:25.020
in another solar system and
or another galaxy, you know.

04:22:25.020 --> 04:22:28.570
What does it mean to be a woman
in another galaxy, you know?

04:22:28.570 --> 04:22:34.120
What does it mean to-- is she
thinking in the default terms

04:22:34.120 --> 04:22:36.600
of being American in
the way that I would.

04:22:36.600 --> 04:22:41.050
Probably not, but how do you
recognize some of these concepts

04:22:41.050 --> 04:22:42.750
and how they might
shape her perspective?

04:22:42.750 --> 04:22:45.600
And then that became really
interesting, but then that goes

04:22:45.600 --> 04:22:48.850
into the whole time travel
dynamic of seeing relationships

04:22:48.850 --> 04:22:51.340
between the future,
the past, the present.

04:22:51.340 --> 04:22:55.080
You know, these names, names
of schools, names of months

04:22:55.080 --> 04:22:56.430
of the year and so forth.

04:22:56.430 --> 04:23:01.140
So for me Afrofuturism really
opened me up to doing a lot

04:23:01.140 --> 04:23:04.110
of writing and story
telling that it--

04:23:04.110 --> 04:23:07.020
I could have deemed as
being very nontraditional

04:23:07.020 --> 04:23:09.310
and kind of stuck myself.

04:23:09.310 --> 04:23:12.810
And I think that's one of the
beauties of the term itself is

04:23:12.810 --> 04:23:16.370
that it helps people to feel
comfortable creating stories

04:23:16.370 --> 04:23:21.710
and creating works that they
didn't feel working were

04:23:21.710 --> 04:23:25.100
validated in very
specific spaces.

04:23:25.100 --> 04:23:29.050
And that helps to really
free the imagination

04:23:29.050 --> 04:23:31.810
or in some cases
decolonize the mind.

04:23:31.810 --> 04:23:35.520
And that's when you can
start talking about futures.

04:23:35.520 --> 04:23:38.490
And people feel comfortable
looking at their own lives

04:23:38.490 --> 04:23:41.040
and their own ideas and
saying, "Hey, you know I think

04:23:41.040 --> 04:23:44.700
that these are ways that we
can really build together."

04:23:44.700 --> 04:23:47.990
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: And
Enongo, maybe you can add

04:23:47.990 --> 04:23:50.600
to this as well because I know
that this has been something

04:23:50.600 --> 04:23:52.930
that you've actively
adapted as a lens

04:23:52.930 --> 04:23:56.660
for your music career after,
you know, being kind of lumped

04:23:56.660 --> 04:23:58.560
in with the nerdcore thing

04:23:58.560 --> 04:23:59.860
&gt;&gt; Enongo Lumumba-Kasong: Yeah.

04:23:59.860 --> 04:24:03.320
So I reference video
games and cartoons a lot

04:24:03.320 --> 04:24:04.620
because that's the
stuff that I love.

04:24:04.620 --> 04:24:07.610
That's what I grew up with
and that shaped my world view.

04:24:07.610 --> 04:24:12.500
And so I found that as an emcee
who does that quite a bit,

04:24:12.500 --> 04:24:16.660
my work started to be attached
to the subgenre called nerdcore

04:24:16.660 --> 04:24:21.390
which is basically a lot of
white guys who can't rap.

04:24:21.390 --> 04:24:25.520
And they, you know, and they'll
kind of have their references

04:24:25.520 --> 04:24:27.810
to Star Wars and
whatever-- whatever else.

04:24:27.810 --> 04:24:31.320
But I was-- I think very
offended by the fact

04:24:31.320 --> 04:24:32.690
that I didn't get to
shape that narrative.

04:24:32.690 --> 04:24:34.940
But I saw this term and
started to be associated

04:24:34.940 --> 04:24:37.690
with me I didn't even
know where it came from,

04:24:37.690 --> 04:24:39.440
but I would see nerdcore
rapper Samus.

04:24:39.440 --> 04:24:40.740
There's nerdcore artist.

04:24:40.740 --> 04:24:42.950
And so I think, at first I tried
to wrestle with it and say,

04:24:42.950 --> 04:24:44.430
"OK, maybe I can adopt it.

04:24:44.430 --> 04:24:48.330
Maybe-- black perspective
that I'm trying to assert

04:24:48.330 --> 04:24:51.310
through my work, it's not
just that I love video games

04:24:51.310 --> 04:24:52.750
and it's not just
that I'm a black girl

04:24:52.750 --> 04:24:54.860
who loves videos games, I
have a particular perspective,

04:24:54.860 --> 04:24:58.630
and I think that Afrofuturism
as a term for thinking

04:24:58.630 --> 04:25:02.480
about like repurposing was like
a really interesting way for me

04:25:02.480 --> 04:25:05.260
to engage with the idea of
repurposing this character.

04:25:05.260 --> 04:25:09.410
This character who's a white
blonde lady and putting my face

04:25:09.410 --> 04:25:11.940
in that, you know,
cybernetic power suit.

04:25:11.940 --> 04:25:14.490
And all of the work that I ended
up doing, I mean I've have had

04:25:14.490 --> 04:25:17.130
so many folks who have come
up to me and said, "You know,

04:25:17.130 --> 04:25:18.730
I didn't know who
Mae Jemison was

04:25:18.730 --> 04:25:20.500
but I did know what Metroid was.

04:25:20.500 --> 04:25:23.570
And so I listen to your album
and now I'm following her

04:25:23.570 --> 04:25:25.570
and then now I think she's
amazing and vice versa.

04:25:25.570 --> 04:25:27.990
You know, folks who are
interested black feminist

04:25:27.990 --> 04:25:30.230
thought or who are
interested in engaging with,

04:25:30.230 --> 04:25:31.530
you know, the academy.

04:25:31.530 --> 04:25:34.530
Who don't care about video
games or cartoons but they're--

04:25:34.530 --> 04:25:39.490
my favorite story from
this is a woman in Ithaca

04:25:39.490 --> 04:25:41.300
and she started playing
the video game Metroid

04:25:41.300 --> 04:25:44.260
with her daughter after her
daughter started asking,

04:25:44.260 --> 04:25:45.560
who's Samus?

04:25:45.560 --> 04:25:47.040
Like I see this rapper
and she looks like me.

04:25:47.040 --> 04:25:49.090
And I want to know more
about this video game.

04:25:49.090 --> 04:25:50.830
So now, they've started to play

04:25:50.830 --> 04:25:53.710
with that the kind
realities of that universe.

04:25:53.710 --> 04:25:58.920
So I think that the term
as Ytasha was saying it,

04:25:58.920 --> 04:26:01.260
I find that it's not
restrictive in the ways

04:26:01.260 --> 04:26:05.330
that that nerdcore was
to me because built

04:26:05.330 --> 04:26:09.100
in to the understanding of it
is this idea on reprocessing

04:26:09.100 --> 04:26:11.850
or shape shifting or a kind
of movement that it's not sort

04:26:11.850 --> 04:26:14.490
of a fluid or not
sort of a static thing

04:26:14.490 --> 04:26:18.100
and that fluid it is a part
of kind of essentially working

04:26:18.100 --> 04:26:19.860
with an Afrofuture's frameworks.

04:26:19.860 --> 04:26:23.420
So it was-- it allowed me to
reject this whole other part

04:26:23.420 --> 04:26:25.750
of music that I did not
feel like I wasn't making.

04:26:25.750 --> 04:26:30.130
&gt;&gt; Lucianne Walkowicz: You know,
I want to return to as something

04:26:30.130 --> 04:26:32.650
that I think has a reason
in different ways and each

04:26:32.650 --> 04:26:35.170
of the panels today which
is the relationship of time.

04:26:35.170 --> 04:26:38.750
And I believe you brought it up
at the beginning of this panel

04:26:38.750 --> 04:26:41.570
that outside of, you know, to--

04:26:41.570 --> 04:26:44.250
let's remove the
position from nowhere

04:26:44.250 --> 04:26:48.710
and call it white
western futurism.

04:26:48.710 --> 04:26:51.040
It seems like in a
indigenous and Afrofuturism,

04:26:51.040 --> 04:26:53.920
there is a much more
nonlinear relationship to time

04:26:53.920 --> 04:26:57.110
and much more of a
relationship to both deep time

04:26:57.110 --> 04:26:59.320
and history and into the future.

04:26:59.320 --> 04:27:02.390
And I wonder if you can
speak to that in the light

04:27:02.390 --> 04:27:06.950
of how we talk about,
well, now is the moment

04:27:06.950 --> 04:27:08.690
that we must go to space.

04:27:08.690 --> 04:27:11.550
Now is the moment that
humans must live off world.

04:27:11.550 --> 04:27:16.180
How do you think those two
ideas interact with each other?

04:27:16.180 --> 04:27:17.480
&gt;&gt; Ytasha L. Womack: That's it.

04:27:17.480 --> 04:27:24.000
Well it's fascinating
because you can be in--

04:27:24.000 --> 04:27:31.290
you can be very present
and still be connected

04:27:31.290 --> 04:27:34.330
to what we call a
future or past.

04:27:34.330 --> 04:27:37.000
And it's being so present

04:27:37.000 --> 04:27:40.900
that you can really feel
how they're all interweave

04:27:40.900 --> 04:27:45.750
or interwoven rather into a
way to really express and be.

04:27:45.750 --> 04:27:52.380
And to see that these actions
of now can impact the future

04:27:52.380 --> 04:27:53.920
and the past and I think that's

04:27:53.920 --> 04:27:55.680
where it gets really
interesting.

04:27:55.680 --> 04:27:58.810
So when we usually talk about
the feature this is linear

04:27:58.810 --> 04:28:02.120
like now is the time
to move forward, right?

04:28:02.120 --> 04:28:06.180
But any action that you take
now at least in this way we talk

04:28:06.180 --> 04:28:09.330
about time it can impact
the so called feature

04:28:09.330 --> 04:28:11.850
and it can impact
the so called past.

04:28:11.850 --> 04:28:16.610
You know, it can be a healing
process in both directions.

04:28:16.610 --> 04:28:20.710
And that's where it gets really
intriguing because there's a--

04:28:20.710 --> 04:28:24.970
there's just-- it's
a holistic recog--

04:28:24.970 --> 04:28:27.710
it's a holistic way
of recognizing

04:28:27.710 --> 04:28:32.380
that your actions always
have some sort of impact.

04:28:32.380 --> 04:28:35.300
And so then now is the time I
think it's really fascinating

04:28:35.300 --> 04:28:39.230
because you can look, you know,
back in linear past you can say,

04:28:39.230 --> 04:28:43.620
"Well, now is always
the time, wasn't it?"

04:28:43.620 --> 04:28:47.380
You know, often times I
hear people, you know,

04:28:47.380 --> 04:28:50.570
they'll describe, you
know, if you're talking

04:28:50.570 --> 04:28:52.200
about the antebellum
south, right,

04:28:52.200 --> 04:28:55.480
and they'll describe someone
who's very noble figure

04:28:55.480 --> 04:28:59.130
supposedly and that they may
have a lot of isms attached

04:28:59.130 --> 04:29:01.020
to their philosophy
and they'll say, "Oh,

04:29:01.020 --> 04:29:03.090
he was a man of his time."

04:29:03.090 --> 04:29:07.240
It's like, yeah, but you also
had people who were fighting

04:29:07.240 --> 04:29:10.730
against slavery, people
who were advocating

04:29:10.730 --> 04:29:12.910
to protect native communities.

04:29:12.910 --> 04:29:15.510
So, you know, this
whole retroactive man

04:29:15.510 --> 04:29:18.230
of its time thing or woman
of its time, it's really,

04:29:18.230 --> 04:29:20.910
really interesting and I'm
starting to hear people say

04:29:20.910 --> 04:29:23.320
that around times that
I've lived in, you know.

04:29:23.320 --> 04:29:26.790
It's like, well, wait
a second, you know.

04:29:26.790 --> 04:29:32.620
They'll say, "Oh, well,
you can't indict the people

04:29:32.620 --> 04:29:37.440
of the '80s because
of their kind

04:29:37.440 --> 04:29:41.250
of their perspective
on sexuality."

04:29:41.250 --> 04:29:44.890
OK. Where are we going
with this at some point?

04:29:44.890 --> 04:29:48.280
You know, is this just always
going to be the conversation

04:29:48.280 --> 04:29:51.640
where we don't acknowledge that
there were always a variety

04:29:51.640 --> 04:29:54.960
of voices in the so
called linear past.

04:29:54.960 --> 04:29:56.580
And that gets into something

04:29:56.580 --> 04:29:58.690
that our previous
panelist mentioned,

04:29:58.690 --> 04:30:00.500
the gentlemen over here.

04:30:00.500 --> 04:30:04.400
My apologies for not remembering
your name exactly, but--

04:30:04.400 --> 04:30:08.610
and that was this whole concept
of the narrative, you know,

04:30:08.610 --> 04:30:12.620
what is the narrative around
going to Mars, you know,

04:30:12.620 --> 04:30:15.750
because it's the dominant
narrative that we seem

04:30:15.750 --> 04:30:19.760
to remember sometimes almost
more than the actual actions

04:30:19.760 --> 04:30:24.570
of people in the so called past
that gets really fascinating.

04:30:24.570 --> 04:30:27.550
So now is the time, now
is always been the time

04:30:27.550 --> 04:30:29.530
to do any number of things.

04:30:29.530 --> 04:30:33.660
But the narratives we
associate with that

04:30:33.660 --> 04:30:35.420
and then the actions
people taking,

04:30:35.420 --> 04:30:37.700
why they take those actions?

04:30:37.700 --> 04:30:42.400
Is-- it says more
about our belief

04:30:42.400 --> 04:30:45.330
around agency in our lives.

04:30:45.330 --> 04:30:47.540
And that's why it's so great
to talk about the future

04:30:47.540 --> 04:30:51.140
and to talk about Afrofuturism
and indigenous featurism

04:30:51.140 --> 04:30:54.220
and other-- and bringing
people to the table

04:30:54.220 --> 04:30:57.070
or making them feel
comfortable about who they are

04:30:57.070 --> 04:31:02.800
so that they can have agency
to make the now moment of--

04:31:02.800 --> 04:31:06.790
be the now moment and
create these holistic spaces

04:31:06.790 --> 04:31:11.950
that help all of us.

04:31:11.950 --> 04:31:13.250
&gt;&gt; D. Denenge Duyst-Akpem:
Excuse me.

04:31:13.250 --> 04:31:14.550
[Inaudible] here.

04:31:14.550 --> 04:31:15.850
Yes. Yes, yes, yes.

04:31:15.850 --> 04:31:20.220
In terms of the narrative,
I think one of the reasons

04:31:20.220 --> 04:31:24.510
that I love being in the
art history department

04:31:24.510 --> 04:31:28.800
which is a little strange but
also perfect and I kind of go

04:31:28.800 --> 04:31:31.530
in between art history and
sculpture and, you know.

04:31:31.530 --> 04:31:35.210
But thinking a lot of the work
that I do with students is

04:31:35.210 --> 04:31:37.550
around decolonizing the canon.

04:31:37.550 --> 04:31:40.360
And so thinking about
going back to the story,

04:31:40.360 --> 04:31:41.660
what are the narratives.

04:31:41.660 --> 04:31:45.030
That is a kind of
active reclamation

04:31:45.030 --> 04:31:50.140
that for me is I believe a kind
of time travel and a shifting

04:31:50.140 --> 04:31:52.860
because we are reframing
the narrative,

04:31:52.860 --> 04:31:55.690
we're reframing how
we see the center.

04:31:55.690 --> 04:31:59.280
And a lot of that is through the
action of students themselves.

04:31:59.280 --> 04:32:00.780
You know, we do projects
that just

04:32:00.780 --> 04:32:02.610
with the grad students
this summer.

04:32:02.610 --> 04:32:08.270
The final offering that we gave
to the other low rez students

04:32:08.270 --> 04:32:13.530
and to the library is who are
very amazing and receptive.

04:32:13.530 --> 04:32:16.440
Basically out of the 30 students

04:32:16.440 --> 04:32:21.670
in the class everyone brought
an artist that they felt needed

04:32:21.670 --> 04:32:23.420
to be included in the canon.

04:32:23.420 --> 04:32:26.570
We also unpack people
to find how, you know,

04:32:26.570 --> 04:32:28.620
how are you defining the canon

04:32:28.620 --> 04:32:33.180
and then created basically a
sheet with images and names

04:32:33.180 --> 04:32:36.590
and titles of books to be
given to the library to order,

04:32:36.590 --> 04:32:38.710
but just, you know,
small actions

04:32:38.710 --> 04:32:42.000
like that actually are not small
but thinking about this idea

04:32:42.000 --> 04:32:43.640
of a kind of a healing
of the past

04:32:43.640 --> 04:32:46.800
as you were mentioning
Ytasha, which is why I also go

04:32:46.800 --> 04:32:49.870
so much back to the
black guards movement

04:32:49.870 --> 04:32:51.300
in this idea of an action.

04:32:51.300 --> 04:32:54.240
What are the actions
that we're taking?

04:32:54.240 --> 04:32:58.240
I look also to Rasheedah
Phillips and Moor Mother

04:32:58.240 --> 04:33:01.540
and Philly, North Philly
with Black Quantum Futurism

04:33:01.540 --> 04:33:05.580
and not only with their
community future's lab

04:33:05.580 --> 04:33:10.140
that they've setup, which is
basically and now has been,

04:33:10.140 --> 04:33:11.690
you know, the work
that's come from that.

04:33:11.690 --> 04:33:15.730
It's being shown at, you
know, museums and everything.

04:33:15.730 --> 04:33:19.280
And so there's that sense of
agency that people have in terms

04:33:19.280 --> 04:33:20.580
of wait a minute,

04:33:20.580 --> 04:33:23.010
our neighborhood is
being rapidly gentrified.

04:33:23.010 --> 04:33:24.310
What can we do?

04:33:24.310 --> 04:33:28.120
And setting up almost like sun
runs bases the place, you know,

04:33:28.120 --> 04:33:31.020
that remember Spaceways
Incorporated that sort

04:33:31.020 --> 04:33:36.200
of storefront and having the
storefront and transforming it

04:33:36.200 --> 04:33:37.500
and saying, "Wait a minute.

04:33:37.500 --> 04:33:39.330
We can like claim."

04:33:39.330 --> 04:33:42.470
I also love-- I had the
fortune to experience one

04:33:42.470 --> 04:33:46.520
of Rasheedah's time travel
exercises that she does

04:33:46.520 --> 04:33:50.720
where she takes you through
the steps of imagining,

04:33:50.720 --> 04:33:55.390
taking your something from
the past physically, you know,

04:33:55.390 --> 04:33:57.320
just through her
instruction locating it

04:33:57.320 --> 04:34:01.030
in a different place, sending it
back, something from the future,

04:34:01.030 --> 04:34:04.200
putting it in the past and
through that sort of gesture

04:34:04.200 --> 04:34:08.330
of that exercise, what
was in the past and what's

04:34:08.330 --> 04:34:11.740
in the future-- it all of a
sudden it starts to shift.

04:34:11.740 --> 04:34:14.630
And your relationship
to it starts to shift.

04:34:14.630 --> 04:34:18.000
And the power that things
have start to shift.

04:34:18.000 --> 04:34:20.020
So even for instance
with the performance

04:34:20.020 --> 04:34:22.850
that I'll be doing
later, I was imagining it

04:34:22.850 --> 04:34:24.900
as having already occurred then

04:34:24.900 --> 04:34:26.770
and it's also something
that runners do.

04:34:26.770 --> 04:34:29.450
You know, in sports,
you know, you imagine--

04:34:29.450 --> 04:34:32.170
and this is related but,
you know, somewhat different

04:34:32.170 --> 04:34:37.490
but thinking about how we, where
we place information in our mind

04:34:37.490 --> 04:34:41.440
and in our energy field and
Wendy Walters in speaking

04:34:41.440 --> 04:34:44.290
about electronic
science in Detroit,

04:34:44.290 --> 04:34:47.390
city of past, present, future.

04:34:47.390 --> 04:34:50.400
She talks about this in
relationship to the creation

04:34:50.400 --> 04:34:55.090
of techno music and
traveling the digital pathways

04:34:55.090 --> 04:34:59.640
and how Detroit is sort
of situated, you know,

04:34:59.640 --> 04:35:03.990
at the simultaneously
in all of these moments

04:35:03.990 --> 04:35:08.690
and resisting a particular
location and time is nonlinear.

04:35:08.690 --> 04:35:11.540
And so there's so much in that
that I find very inspiring

04:35:11.540 --> 04:35:14.350
as to thinking about how
do we understand now.

04:35:14.350 --> 04:35:16.880
In Rasheedah's Black
Quantum Futurism,

04:35:16.880 --> 04:35:22.920
she posits that now is only
ever about three seconds.

04:35:22.920 --> 04:35:25.170
I mean there's much more to
it and much more in-depth,

04:35:25.170 --> 04:35:28.390
you know, which is
genius, but, you know,

04:35:28.390 --> 04:35:32.060
if we think about what's
now, I mean now is--

04:35:32.060 --> 04:35:34.670
it's already gone before you
can even say the word now.

04:35:34.670 --> 04:35:36.890
So things like that,
I like to just kind

04:35:36.890 --> 04:35:38.880
of play with that in my mind.

04:35:38.880 --> 04:35:42.070
I'm not a scientist but, yeah,

04:35:42.070 --> 04:35:43.440
that kind of stuff
gets me going.

04:35:43.440 --> 04:35:46.130
&gt;&gt; Enongo Lumumba-Kasongo:
And just quickly to jump

04:35:46.130 --> 04:35:48.290
on some names that
were mentioned.

04:35:48.290 --> 04:35:50.660
So Moor Mother is
absolutely incredible.

04:35:50.660 --> 04:35:54.890
She-- I don't want to say
just musician because she's

04:35:54.890 --> 04:35:58.490
so much more than that
as M-O-O-R Mother.

04:35:58.490 --> 04:36:02.220
And one of the things that she
says and some of her experiences

04:36:02.220 --> 04:36:05.210
and I think this is drawing on
summer from sunrise that the end

04:36:05.210 --> 04:36:07.700
of the world has already
happened that we are

04:36:07.700 --> 04:36:11.510
in the post apocalypse--
post-apocalyptic times.

04:36:11.510 --> 04:36:13.700
And I think it's a really
interesting way to think

04:36:13.700 --> 04:36:15.980
about our existence because
on the one hand, you know,

04:36:15.980 --> 04:36:20.010
you could sort of frame it
through this sort of perspective

04:36:20.010 --> 04:36:22.120
where it's gloom and doom
but I think in other ways

04:36:22.120 --> 04:36:24.990
that invites us to do the
stuff that we would do

04:36:24.990 --> 04:36:28.100
in the post-apocalyptic time,
right, to kind of come together

04:36:28.100 --> 04:36:31.080
to figure out new
possibilities, to repurpose

04:36:31.080 --> 04:36:35.570
and to really see this as an
opportunity to reshape some

04:36:35.570 --> 04:36:36.870
of the existence of power

04:36:36.870 --> 04:36:39.020
that existed before
the apocalypse happen.

04:36:39.020 --> 04:36:41.960
So, I think I always love
coming back to this idea

04:36:41.960 --> 04:36:44.510
that the world has
already ended.

04:36:44.510 --> 04:36:47.920
&gt;&gt; Willi Lemper: And
relating to a lot

04:36:47.920 --> 04:36:51.100
of these topics including
the power of a term

04:36:51.100 --> 04:36:53.780
or its limitations, I
think indigenous futures

04:36:53.780 --> 04:36:56.240
since had that impact as well.

04:36:56.240 --> 04:37:00.030
It was developed by someone
Anishinaabe scholar named Grace

04:37:00.030 --> 04:37:02.060
Dillon who's at Portland
State University.

04:37:02.060 --> 04:37:05.170
She has this great book
called "Walking the Clouds."

04:37:05.170 --> 04:37:07.280
And what she essentially
did is take all this work

04:37:07.280 --> 04:37:10.370
that was indigenous futurist
and put it into conversation

04:37:10.370 --> 04:37:12.740
and theorized it and bring it
together around a certain issue

04:37:12.740 --> 04:37:15.540
so that people were part
of the conversation.

04:37:15.540 --> 04:37:19.200
It wasn't fringe,
something science fiction.

04:37:19.200 --> 04:37:22.340
And one of the themes that
she develops is this idea

04:37:22.340 --> 04:37:27.380
of slipstream which is this way
of thinking about how time works

04:37:27.380 --> 04:37:30.260
that strikes this
balance of honoring

04:37:30.260 --> 04:37:34.520
that time works differently in
a lot of indigenous societies

04:37:34.520 --> 04:37:38.840
but not uttering it in a
way that depoliticizes it

04:37:38.840 --> 04:37:42.140
which could be difficult
balance.

04:37:42.140 --> 04:37:46.420
Another thing that she talks
about is the native apocalypse

04:37:46.420 --> 04:37:50.530
and she says this powerful thing
in the intro that, you know,

04:37:50.530 --> 04:37:52.660
if contemplated seriously,

04:37:52.660 --> 04:37:55.450
the native apocalypse
has already happened.

04:37:55.450 --> 04:37:59.420
But it's a very nuance and
thoughtful discussion about--

04:37:59.420 --> 04:38:00.720
also how there's a difference

04:38:00.720 --> 04:38:03.050
between post-apocalyptic
and dystopian.

04:38:03.050 --> 04:38:05.000
All right, dystopian
is an end point.

04:38:05.000 --> 04:38:07.960
Post-apocalyptic is
a beginning point.

04:38:07.960 --> 04:38:11.170
Since that have kind of
considering through health stats

04:38:11.170 --> 04:38:14.300
and everything is equal, if
you start from a point of view

04:38:14.300 --> 04:38:15.990
in which communities are

04:38:15.990 --> 04:38:19.450
in a post apocalyptic
situation then it's like, well,

04:38:19.450 --> 04:38:23.150
communities are doing
really well in that way

04:38:23.150 --> 04:38:26.670
of changing the frame and
comparing them in all sorts

04:38:26.670 --> 04:38:28.860
of ways that stops making sense.

04:38:28.860 --> 04:38:32.820
And there's just a lot of
great, I think films coming back

04:38:32.820 --> 04:38:35.390
to the creative side of things
that they're doing this.

04:38:35.390 --> 04:38:38.970
Most related perhaps to this
discussion is the 6th World

04:38:38.970 --> 04:38:41.160
by Nanobah Becker who's Navajo.

04:38:41.160 --> 04:38:44.060
And you see some stills
on floating through.

04:38:44.060 --> 04:38:45.850
And I really recommend watching.

04:38:45.850 --> 04:38:48.480
It's called the 6th World,
it's streaming online.

04:38:48.480 --> 04:38:51.430
But long story short, it
centers the Navajo nation

04:38:51.430 --> 04:38:58.480
as the leading funder in
organizing kind of organization

04:38:58.480 --> 04:39:01.130
that is pushing for
this mission to Mars.

04:39:01.130 --> 04:39:06.470
And it stars scientist who is
Navajo woman who's an astronaut

04:39:06.470 --> 04:39:11.070
and the lead scientist and sort
to causing the question GMO

04:39:11.070 --> 04:39:18.020
and the way that what Mars
is becomes very different.

04:39:18.020 --> 04:39:25.030
If it's into the cosmology
of Navajo in broad strokes

04:39:25.030 --> 04:39:30.000
around the 6th World is
not just in an earth rock.

04:39:30.000 --> 04:39:33.380
And there's great
work that's been done

04:39:33.380 --> 04:39:37.120
on understanding
perspectives on the moon landing

04:39:37.120 --> 04:39:38.420
from indigenous communities

04:39:38.420 --> 04:39:42.050
where the moon is not just
some an earth rock either,

04:39:42.050 --> 04:39:45.380
it's a sacred space for a lot of
people in going there trampling

04:39:45.380 --> 04:39:47.970
on it, driving around,
taking things from it.

04:39:47.970 --> 04:39:51.160
For a lot of people is a
violation of something.

04:39:51.160 --> 04:39:54.100
And that's often, you know,
we had discussions about sort

04:39:54.100 --> 04:39:58.010
of personhood for
places and these kind

04:39:58.010 --> 04:40:01.670
of things are not even
in the discussion.

04:40:01.670 --> 04:40:02.970
And the other piece I wanted

04:40:02.970 --> 04:40:04.840
to mention very briefly
is Lisa Jackson.

04:40:04.840 --> 04:40:06.870
She has this short
called "The Visit"

04:40:06.870 --> 04:40:11.130
and it involves extraterrestrial
space saucer visiting earth.

04:40:11.130 --> 04:40:14.800
And they don't go to a
Kansas farm, they don't go

04:40:14.800 --> 04:40:19.920
to Washington D.C., they go
to a native reserve in Canada.

04:40:19.920 --> 04:40:22.340
And there's not a colonial
interaction and it's hard

04:40:22.340 --> 04:40:25.530
to think of extraterrestrial,
any narratives

04:40:25.530 --> 04:40:28.330
that don't have some sort
of colonial engagement.

04:40:28.330 --> 04:40:32.880
It's an engagement that's
spiritual, it's part of the sort

04:40:32.880 --> 04:40:36.890
of the coyote sign in the
sky and it's constellation.

04:40:36.890 --> 04:40:38.440
It's something else,
it's the sort

04:40:38.440 --> 04:40:41.400
of otherwise you've mentioned
and I think that's the power

04:40:41.400 --> 04:40:43.370
of a lot of the stuff
that it involves things

04:40:43.370 --> 04:40:47.510
that are not already
known sort of at the edge

04:40:47.510 --> 04:40:51.260
of what could can be imagined
which makes some people

04:40:51.260 --> 04:40:54.430
or some people have challenged
with because it's a ephemeral

04:40:54.430 --> 04:40:58.050
in a way but I think it's very
practical and politically,

04:40:58.050 --> 04:41:02.320
you know, potent especially
to creative endeavors.

04:41:02.320 --> 04:41:05.240
And that's where the edge of
what can be imagined comes

04:41:05.240 --> 04:41:09.580
into being even more so
than academic settings.

04:41:09.580 --> 04:41:10.880
Yeah.

