always be a sacred place

04:42:14.750 --> 04:42:19.460
that we can never visit and
this static idea is then held

04:42:19.460 --> 04:42:23.390
as an excuse for
colonial activities.

04:42:23.390 --> 04:42:27.210
And so, I was kind of wondering
about how you all kind of think

04:42:27.210 --> 04:42:32.540
about the idea of indigeneity
as static and Afrofuturisms

04:42:32.540 --> 04:42:36.820
and indigenous futurisms
as kind of a way

04:42:36.820 --> 04:42:41.220
around that narrative about us.

04:42:44.350 --> 04:42:45.650
&gt;&gt; D. Denenge Duyst-Akpem:
Thank you.

04:42:45.650 --> 04:42:46.950
I love that.

04:42:46.950 --> 04:42:50.390
I think that's why I
keep coming back to--

04:42:50.390 --> 04:42:55.510
I feel like my rule as
educator and in the classroom

04:42:55.510 --> 04:42:59.860
or in creating projects,
I guess, with students

04:42:59.860 --> 04:43:03.600
to explore their own
relationships, you know,

04:43:03.600 --> 04:43:07.460
so there's this kind of--
to keep that dynamic aspect

04:43:07.460 --> 04:43:11.630
and incorporating especially
for people who may not be--

04:43:11.630 --> 04:43:14.400
you know I don't teach in
the performance departments.

04:43:14.400 --> 04:43:16.000
So most of the people I get--

04:43:16.000 --> 04:43:18.460
you know, they might
becoming from, you know,

04:43:18.460 --> 04:43:20.920
who knows what department.

04:43:20.920 --> 04:43:29.150
And so to incorporate ritual or
preformative or-- yeah, that--

04:43:29.150 --> 04:43:31.550
because that's big issue,
you know, I teach African art

04:43:31.550 --> 04:43:34.420
as well and so that's
always this idea of--

04:43:34.420 --> 04:43:37.580
yes there's this static
pass that we're looking

04:43:37.580 --> 04:43:41.060
at versus understanding
it, the dynamism.

04:43:41.060 --> 04:43:47.120
So, I think for me and
it sort of in the action

04:43:47.120 --> 04:43:52.480
in the engagement and seeing
Afrofuturism as been and stating

04:43:52.480 --> 04:43:54.520
that it is a space
of shape shifting.

04:43:54.520 --> 04:43:56.770
We're really, really
clear about that.

04:43:56.770 --> 04:44:00.000
There has a lot of portals
and an entry points.

04:44:00.000 --> 04:44:03.710
That's that kind of how
I sort of deal with that.

04:44:03.710 --> 04:44:08.750
So a little more
general but yeah.

04:44:08.750 --> 04:44:12.870
&gt;&gt; Willi Lemper: Very
briefly, I think with a lot

04:44:12.870 --> 04:44:16.810
of indigenous futurist creative
filmmakers and writers talk

04:44:16.810 --> 04:44:20.070
about is that asserting
something in the future

04:44:20.070 --> 04:44:22.760
which is often silence is a way
of breaking out of this sort

04:44:22.760 --> 04:44:29.490
of endless binaries around
authenticity versus modernity

04:44:29.490 --> 04:44:32.800
that become-- unless they
reinscribe and they're so baked

04:44:32.800 --> 04:44:36.510
into the entire settler
colonial project and language.

04:44:36.510 --> 04:44:40.840
And so the future-- by imagining
and envisioning the future

04:44:40.840 --> 04:44:43.560
like in the 6th World,
it's envisioning a future

04:44:43.560 --> 04:44:47.560
that it's very Navajo and
it's very technological

04:44:47.560 --> 04:44:49.850
and like the white
people have to be saved.

04:44:49.850 --> 04:44:54.350
And their science is the one
that has limitations and it's--

04:44:54.350 --> 04:45:00.600
you know, the Navajo corn that
it is what works in the end.

04:45:00.600 --> 04:45:03.910
So, I think it's-- an
imaginative space that can

04:45:03.910 --> 04:45:06.420
to some extent break
out of things

04:45:06.420 --> 04:45:07.720
and Grace Dillon talks a lot

04:45:07.720 --> 04:45:10.030
about how the pluralist
is essential.

04:45:10.030 --> 04:45:15.050
The futurisms is important for
the reasons that you mentioned.

04:45:15.050 --> 04:45:17.590
&gt;&gt; Enongo Lumumba-Kasongo:
I'm so sorry.

04:45:17.590 --> 04:45:20.490
&gt;&gt; Ytasha L. Womack:
No, go ahead.

04:45:20.490 --> 04:45:24.110
&gt;&gt; Enongo Lumumba-Kasongo: So I
thinking in a teaching context,

04:45:24.110 --> 04:45:25.750
one of the questions--

04:45:25.750 --> 04:45:27.450
one of the things that
I always push back

04:45:27.450 --> 04:45:30.440
against with my students is
when we talk about progress.

04:45:30.440 --> 04:45:35.180
Always asking progress for
whom like forcing them to stick

04:45:35.180 --> 04:45:38.530
that in there because it
starts to dislodge all

04:45:38.530 --> 04:45:39.910
of these assumptions, I think,

04:45:39.910 --> 04:45:42.060
for them about exactly
what you're speaking

04:45:42.060 --> 04:45:43.830
about these ideas about
what modernity looks like

04:45:43.830 --> 04:45:46.640
or like I was saying earlier
what technology looks like,

04:45:46.640 --> 04:45:49.390
what technology means,
what science means.

04:45:49.390 --> 04:45:51.230
So always sticking
for whom, I think,

04:45:51.230 --> 04:45:53.090
at the end of their
statement is a way

04:45:53.090 --> 04:45:55.800
that I've been able
to trouble that.

04:45:55.800 --> 04:45:59.510
And then on my personal
work, I've started thinking

04:45:59.510 --> 04:46:04.890
about how I can cooperate ideas
around sort of cyborg feminism

04:46:04.890 --> 04:46:09.330
or the idea of sitting
in the discomfort

04:46:09.330 --> 04:46:12.970
between all these different
aspects of ourselves and knowing

04:46:12.970 --> 04:46:15.880
that those things can't be
reconciled and trying to figure

04:46:15.880 --> 04:46:19.620
out how to speak
to parts of myself

04:46:19.620 --> 04:46:23.700
that I'll later contradicts
and in other works and feeling

04:46:23.700 --> 04:46:26.300
like that's a part of
the work and that helps

04:46:26.300 --> 04:46:30.380
to reject this sort of static
ideas of what, you know,

04:46:30.380 --> 04:46:34.290
conscious rap looks
like or what, you know,

04:46:34.290 --> 04:46:38.380
rap from a black women
looks like or sounds like.

04:46:38.380 --> 04:46:41.750
And like always trying to
challenge myself in that regard

04:46:41.750 --> 04:46:43.960
but that's an awesome question,
something to think about.

04:46:43.960 --> 04:46:49.510
&gt;&gt; Ytasha L. Womack: Oh,
I was just going to note

04:46:49.510 --> 04:46:56.070
that even the way we talk about
the past, there's an assumption

04:46:56.070 --> 04:47:01.040
around technologies,
there's an assumption

04:47:01.040 --> 04:47:06.150
around how people function,
how they lived their lives.

04:47:06.150 --> 04:47:12.090
I mean so many records from so
many societies no longer exist.

04:47:12.090 --> 04:47:16.770
And many of the records that
do exist we're trying to put

04:47:16.770 --> 04:47:21.050
in a framework of who we think
they should have been as opposed

04:47:21.050 --> 04:47:22.780
to who they actually were.

04:47:22.780 --> 04:47:26.130
So we read all the time
about objects that are found

04:47:26.130 --> 04:47:27.580
and people don't know
what it is and they say

04:47:27.580 --> 04:47:30.550
"Oh must be a religious
symbol," you know,

04:47:30.550 --> 04:47:34.470
so if someone found a television
set, you know, 10,000 years

04:47:34.470 --> 04:47:37.240
from now and say "Oh it must
have been a religious symbol.

04:47:37.240 --> 04:47:38.540
Look at these pictures.

04:47:38.540 --> 04:47:40.130
They're all staring at it."

04:47:40.130 --> 04:47:44.960
Right? How to you explain
what a television was

04:47:44.960 --> 04:47:47.360
and the electricity and
plugging it into a wall

04:47:47.360 --> 04:47:50.000
of those systems don't
exist in the same ways.

04:47:50.000 --> 04:47:54.620
So, so I just always
question, you know,

04:47:54.620 --> 04:47:59.660
how we talk about the past
particularly because of some

04:47:59.660 --> 04:48:01.470
of the records that
we're working with

04:48:01.470 --> 04:48:04.140
and because we don't
always value oral histories

04:48:04.140 --> 04:48:06.370
in the same way.

04:48:06.370 --> 04:48:08.510
And, you know, the arguments

04:48:08.510 --> 04:48:10.730
that one can get
into about that.

04:48:10.730 --> 04:48:14.490
And when you start talking
about that kind of a past

04:48:14.490 --> 04:48:17.790
where there was more
technological advancement,

04:48:17.790 --> 04:48:20.930
then we really understand
even if it was just sometimes

04:48:20.930 --> 04:48:25.890
of how societies work that
sometimes mirrors the same sort

04:48:25.890 --> 04:48:28.660
of futures, we say that
we're working towards.

04:48:28.660 --> 04:48:32.200
And that's where the
storytelling gets fun

04:48:32.200 --> 04:48:35.930
because you can leap over
these traumatic moments

04:48:35.930 --> 04:48:40.710
and in cultural paradigms
and you can, in some ways,

04:48:40.710 --> 04:48:44.720
ague that you're intuitively
trying to tap into the ideas

04:48:44.720 --> 04:48:47.060
of what this other past
could be and you're

04:48:47.060 --> 04:48:49.320
at least putting
it into a story.

04:48:49.320 --> 04:48:52.590
And the fact that that's
challenge sometimes I think says

04:48:52.590 --> 04:48:57.970
a lot about what it
means to tell a story

04:48:57.970 --> 04:49:02.410
and how stories really
function for human beings

04:49:02.410 --> 04:49:06.210
and for our ideas of--
for how ideas are spread

04:49:06.210 --> 04:49:09.030
or what we think is
valuable to preserve.

04:49:09.030 --> 04:49:11.320
&gt;&gt; D. Denenge Duyst-Akpem:
On that note,

04:49:11.320 --> 04:49:15.320
I wanted to just quickly add
if I might about Malidoma

04:49:15.320 --> 04:49:18.110
in his introduction to
"Of Water and the Spirit".

04:49:18.110 --> 04:49:21.710
He actually talks about
introducing the elders

04:49:21.710 --> 04:49:25.330
in the village and
at Dagara in Dano

04:49:25.330 --> 04:49:27.980
where he is from to Star Trek.

04:49:27.980 --> 04:49:31.200
He was doing this as a kind of
an experiment just to understand

04:49:31.200 --> 04:49:36.200
because the Dagara people
don't have a word for fiction.

04:49:36.200 --> 04:49:37.940
They only have a
word "Yielbongura"

04:49:37.940 --> 04:49:41.270
which means the thing
that knowledge can't eat.

04:49:41.270 --> 04:49:44.070
So, if you know-- And again
this is a book that I share

04:49:44.070 --> 04:49:47.040
with every student, every person
that I-- because, you know,

04:49:47.040 --> 04:49:50.740
I think there's so much in
that, you know to shifting.

04:49:50.740 --> 04:49:53.970
And so, he showed them an
episode and the elders looked

04:49:53.970 --> 04:49:56.440
at that and they
said "Well, Spock,"

04:49:56.440 --> 04:50:01.160
is "kontombili" he's just too
tall but he's at, you know,

04:50:01.160 --> 04:50:02.580
the seventh dimension
kontombili.

04:50:02.580 --> 04:50:06.310
So they recognized, you
know, Spock as being someone

04:50:06.310 --> 04:50:11.200
who is part of their, you know,
world view and but then also

04:50:11.200 --> 04:50:14.420
with the teleportation
they thought

04:50:14.420 --> 04:50:19.760
that the Star Trek episode
was from a people in the past

04:50:19.760 --> 04:50:22.940
because they looked and they
said, "We do this without all

04:50:22.940 --> 04:50:25.410
of those [inaudible]"
then we don't need all

04:50:25.410 --> 04:50:28.240
that junk and it's so slow.

04:50:28.240 --> 04:50:30.030
You know, what is all of these?

04:50:30.030 --> 04:50:35.480
So in their eyes this was the
Star Trek as a future vision

04:50:35.480 --> 04:50:42.420
from the West was a vision
of past clanky process as far

04:50:42.420 --> 04:50:43.850
as they were concerned.

04:50:43.850 --> 04:50:46.160
And so stories like, you know,

04:50:46.160 --> 04:50:48.610
as far as storytelling
that's the kind of thing

04:50:48.610 --> 04:50:52.220
that I get really excited
about sharing and because it,

04:50:52.220 --> 04:50:56.570
you know, that kind of forced
shift around how do you--

04:50:56.570 --> 04:51:00.190
if people thinking about Africa
and it was idea of construction

04:51:00.190 --> 04:51:03.390
of Africa as a background
backward,

04:51:03.390 --> 04:51:08.630
but then we actually have ways
and methods and ideas that are

04:51:08.630 --> 04:51:12.950
so far beyond the clunkiness
of the West's future vision.

